<FIRST>u w AM-HUDProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0735 06-29 1014</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0735,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Produces Memo Linking Member of Bush's Veep Staff to Project</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERT 3 grafs, bngn ``On a'', after 6th graf, bgng ``If advance,''
to update with information about Kemp's cancellation of land development
program.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional panel produced a memorandum on
Thursday linking a member of George Bush's vice presidential staff
to a project that has figured in alleged influence-peddling in a
federal housing program.
   Meanwhile, Fred Bush, the chief fund-raiser for George Bush's
1988 presidential campaign, making a second appearance before the
House Government Operations subcommittee on employment and housing,
substantially changed his previous sworn testimony about his initial
contacts with the memo's author.
   The memo, dated June 10, 1987, was sent from Deborah Gore Dean,
former executive assistant to then-housing Secretary Samuel Pierce
Jr., to Tony Benedi, coordinator of special projects in the vice
president's office.
   The memo details more than $2 million in funding from the
Department of Housing and Urban Development to the city of Bayamon,
Puerto Rico, during fiscal years 1986 and 1987, information Dean
provided ``per your request'' to Benedi.
   Although no HUD inspector general's investigations at that time
involved Bayamon, the city had been asked to repay $1 million to the
agency.
   ``If advance work is handled properly, this should not present a
problem, but it is potentially dangerous,'' she said.
   On a related matter, HUD Secretary Jack Kemp ordered Thursday
cancellation of a troubled program in his department, one designed
to prepare building sites for housing projects and said by the
department to have been ``riddled with abuse.''
   Twenty-five of 58 projects financed through the 12-year-old
``Title Ten Land Development Mortgage Insurance Program'' have
defaulted, costing the government $90 million, the department said.
   This program guarantees mortgages to finance land acquisition and
site preparation, such as street construction and sewer line
installation, for smaller developers who would include housing for
low-income and moderate income families in their projects.
   Earlier this week, President Bush said he would accept some
responsibility for alleged influence-peddling, favoritism and
mismanagement in several HUD programs while he was vice president in
the Reagan administration.
   ``If you want to assign blame to the vice president for what
happened over the past ... eight years, OK, that's fine, I accept
it,'' President Bush said. He added that he wanted to make sure
there is no recurrence of ``cronyism'' and ``special favors'' in
awarding government contracts.
   Meanwhile, Fred Bush, former deputy chief of staff for then-Vice
President Bush, sought to make what he termed ``clarifying
statements'' to the House subcommittee. Fred Bush, who is not
related to George Bush, previously testified May 25.
   At that time, Fred Bush told the subcommittee he contacted Dean
about the Bayamon project after finding her name in an federal
executive telephone directory.
   However, Bush said one of his former colleagues at Bush &amp; Co.
reminded him later that they had contacted Dean after another former
official at HUD spoke with the colleague at a social gathering.
   ``They have told me of their best recollection. Sometime in late
1984 or early 1985 one of my colleagues met Hunter Cushing at a
social gathering and learned that he worked at HUD,'' said Bush.
   ``My colleague's recollection is that Mr. Cushing told him we
should talk to Deborah Gore Dean,'' he said, adding that the
colleague asked Bush if he knew Dean.
   Bush said he didn't and it was then that he consulted the
directory, subsequently called Dean and later met with her at her
office to discuss the project.
   ``No one at Bush &amp; Co. understood at the time that Ms. Dean might
have the power to approve this project,'' Bush added.
   Bush, ambassador-designate to Luxembourg, said he could not
explain why Benedi had sent the memo to Dean about the Bayamon
project. Bush said he didn't know Benedi, who joined the staff after
Bush had left.
   ``I think it's extremely important that we have this different
version which ... seems to be a dramatically more plausible version
than your initial testimony,'' said Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., the
subcommittee chairman.
   ``I'm getting a little confused as to whether you knew Deborah
Dean or Hunter Cushing first,'' said Rep. Christopher Shays,
R-Conn., questioning Bush extensively on Thursday's version of his
initial contacts with HUD officials.
   Lantos also cited Bush's access to those officials in repeatedly
questioning why the Los Jamines project was subsequently approved by
HUD political appointees over the objections of career HUD
employees. Bush earned $253,000 as a consultant on the project which
was subsequently canceled by the municipality.
   ``I did not feel, nor do I feel today that I had political
infulence,'' said Bush.
   ``I made the distinction between what I call political access and
political influence,'' he added.
   But Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., countered with a question about
Bush's nomination as ambassador, asking whether it had to do more
with his influence than with his layman's knowledge of foreign
policy.
   Cushing, former deputy assistant secretary for multifamily
housing, on Thursday asked the panel to postpone his testimony until
he could review documents that would help him prepare to answer
questions.
   ``I've only recently been retained and not had adequate
opportunity to review the facts in this case,'' said Jamie Gorelick,
an attorney who accompanied the former HUD official.
   Gorelick said Cushing, a deputy assistant secretary at the
Commerce Department, would appear voluntarily before the
subcommittee after the congressional recess for the Fourth of July.
   Lantos excused Cushing and said he would be recalled.
   Investigators also questioned why Bush had failed in his previous
testimony to mention several other HUD projects in which his company
was involved, including a $268,000 technical assistance grant for
another project in Puerto Rico.
   ``Because there has been no Bush &amp; Co. since November of last
year, it has been particularly difficult to pull all this
together,'' said Bush.
   Additionally, he said he was only peripherally involved in the
projects because from March 1986 to November 1988 he worked from
three offices and was involved in fund-raising.
</TEXT>
