<DOCNO> AP890629-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FlagWaver Bjt   06-29 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flag Waver, Bjt,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capitol Flag Waver Opposes Supreme Court Decision</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Howe, who proudly waves hundreds of
American flags daily atop the Capitol, believes flag burners should
be punished _ no matter what the Supreme Court says _ and says he
hopes he never meets one.
   Howe, 32, of Hollywood, Md., is foreman of the crew that spends
eight hours every weekday on the roof of the Capitol, raising and
lowering flags for members of Congress who send them to constituents
on request.
   For prices ranging from $7.38 to $56.25 each, depending on size
and such accessories as a pole and decorative eagle, constituents
can boast that their flags actually flew over the Capitol _ even if
only for a few seconds.
   ``I take pride in my work,'' Howe said in an interview during a
coffee break from his rooftop labors. ``How many people have the job
of flying the flag over the Capitol?''
   Howe would be surprised if there weren't a patriotic surge in
requests for flags inspired by the furor over the Supreme Court's
ruling last week that flag-burning is a form of free speech
guaranteed by the First Amendment.
   ``I don't agree with that decision, and you can quote me,'' Howe
said, ``and I don't agree with people who burn flags.''
   What would be suitable punishment for a flag burner? A lengthy
stint on Howe's work crew, raising flags on the Capitol roof in the
sweltering heat and suffocating humidity of summertime Washington?
   ``That's not stiff enough,'' Howe replied. He thought a moment
and added: ``I wouldn't want to be up there with someone who's
burned a flag.''
   Howe and his nine helpers raise and lower an average of more than
350 flags each weekday. They sometimes work on weekends to meet
requests for flags to be flown on special anniversary dates that
happen to fall on a Saturday or Sunday.
   The heaviest demand occurs on such patriotic holidays as Memorial
Day and the Fourth of July, when as many as 1,200 flags have been
flown in a single day.
   Using three small flagpoles on the roof of the House side of the
Capitol, they raise a flag for a few seconds, lower it and fold it
back into its box. In bad weather, they use six ropes equipped with
flag hooks under the sheltered skirt of the Capitol dome to ``fly''
their flags.
   The practice began in 1937, when a dozen flags were flown over
the Capitol for legislators' constituents. Last year, the number had
risen to more than 114,000. Altogether, more than 1.4 million flags
have been flown over the Capitol to meet public requests in the past
half-century.
   Down in the ``flag room'' in the Capitol basement, the busy
staging area for the flag flying operation, boxed flags are stacked
to the ceilings in four cramped rooms decorated with portraits of
Betsy Ross and a plaque bearing a poem titled ``Our Flag.''
   Chris Benza, who has run the flag room for 28 years, said the
public demand for the Stars and Stripes is growing so fast that
she's been promised a fifth storage room to handle the crush.
   ``The last few weeks we've been overwhelmed with flag requests,
and I don't know why,'' said William F. Raines, administrative
assistant to the Architect of the Capitol, who oversees the flag
program. Raines said the trend began before the Supreme Court's June
22 decision.
   Asked if the court ruling had any effect on her business, Ms.
Benza replied: ``I haven't noticed any yet, but it's possible we'll
get swamped.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
