<FIRST>r w PM-SEC-InsideTraders     06-29 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-Inside Traders,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Seeks Wall Street Bounty Hunters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission is using
greed to battle greed.
   The agency, by a 5-0 vote Wednesday, decided to take advantage of
a new law giving it the power to offer cash rewards to tipsters who
provide information leading to the conviction of inside traders.
   Legislation enacted in November authorizes the SEC to pay
bounties of up to 10 percent of any civil fine it collects from
violators who use inside information to illegally profit or avoid
loss in securities markets.
   ``Rather than relying on scorned lovers or on people who weren't
dealt in on the inside information, it makes sense to treat this as
a business matter,'' said commission member Charles C. Cox.
   The commission will require bounty recipients to apply in
writing, starting when they first contact the SEC but no later than
180 days after a court imposes a fine. Within the 10 percent limit,
the SEC will have sole discretion to decide whether and how much to
pay.
   Meanwhile, in a separate case growing out of the Washington
Public Power Supply System default, the commission voted 5-0 to
adopt rules aimed at providing more information to purchasers of
government bonds.
   Congress included the bounty provision in broader legislation
passed in response to the wave of Wall Street corruption cases.
Inside trading can be difficult to detect and the goal was to
improve the government's chances of uncovering violations.
   The reward is aimed at volunteers rather than people already
subpoenaed by investigators, although anyone can apply.
   The securities industry has been skeptical, arguing that
informants will hold out for SEC rewards rather than passing their
knowledge on to firms' internal compliance officers.
   Gary G. Lynch, SEC enforcement director, said his investigators
have received about 25 tips that could be eligible for bounties
since the legislation passed in November.
   ``Several of the calls were extremely helpful,'' he said.
   Lynch said the agency will make every effort to preserve the
anonymity of bounty recipients when asked, but said it was possible
that a court could order release of an informant's name.
   The new municipal bond rules were written in response to the 1983
default on $2.25 billion in revenue bonds by the Washington Public
Power Supply System, the largest municipal bond default in U.S.
history.
   The system had issued the bonds to pay for the construction of
two nuclear power plants, but cost overruns forced it to abandon the
projects. The SEC decided last September that it could not pursue
enforcement action in the case because that would drain the agency's
resources.
   Instead, the SEC will require firms underwriting municipal bond
issues of more than $1 million to obtain and disclose more extensive
and timely information about the projects being financed and the
governments issuing the bonds.
   Commission member Joseph A. Grundfest said the new regulation
probably will not prevent defaults. But forcing disclosure of more
information will force issuers financing risky projects to pay
higher interest rates, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890629-0031 </DOCNO>
