<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSProstitute     06-29 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Prostitute,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Probation for AIDS-Afflicted Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former prostitute has received her
punishment by becoming infected with AIDS, a judge said in sparing
her from prison.
   Elizabeth Kay Sherouse, seriously ill with the deadly disease,
was once charged with attempted manslaughter for having sex with two
men while knowing she had the AIDS virus.
   Those charges were dropped, but Miss Sherouse, 26, appeared
before Circuit Judge Michael Cycmanick on Tuesday for sentencing on
six prostitution-related misdemeanors for which should could have
been sentenced to more than four years in prison.
   The judge placed her on four years' probation, and sent her home
to spend her remaining days with her family.
   ``There is no question that punishment in this case is what you
have sustained and are enduring because of your conduct,'' Cycmanick
told her.
   Miss Sherouse has been living under house arrest with her mother
for more than a year. She was just released from a hospital after a
weeklong bout with pneumonia and weighs 88 pounds.
   Defense lawyer Bill Sheaffer said she sleeps up to 15 hours a
day, eats and sees a doctor.
   ``Any sentence this court imposes would equal a life sentence for
Miss Sherouse,'' Sheaffer told the judge.
   With the probation order, the judge closed the case that cast a
prostitute and drug addict with a seventh-grade education in the
national spotlight.
   Her arrest in December 1987 is believed to have been the first of
a prostitute charged with attempted manslaughter in an AIDS-related
case.
   The two men wore condoms and have since tested negative for the
virus.
   Cycmanick dismissed the attempted manslaughter charges last year,
saying Miss Sherouse showed no intent to kill the men. An appeals
court upheld the judge's ruling, saying the charges did not fit the
crime.
   Earlier this year, Cycmanick also dismissed racketeering charges,
and she pleaded guilty to the six misdemeanors.
   ``The protection of society is best served ... by the home
confinement restrictions that I've assigned,'' said the judge.
   Sheaffer said Wednesday Miss Sherouse was ``relieved that she can
return home to her family. ... Her health is not good.''
   Assistant State Attorney Rick Bogle, who in the past has argued
that Miss Sherouse be imprisoned, agreed with the defense lawyer on
his request for probation.
</TEXT>
