<FIRST>r w PM-North     06-29 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Trial Juror Says She Forgot About Brother's Prison Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Lead prospects uncertain; ruling expected in late afternoon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A juror in Oliver North's trial acknowledges
she forgot to disclose her brother's prison record when she was
being considered for jury duty in the Iran-Contra case.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell said he would rule today on
claims by North's lawyers that juror Tara King's misstatements
tainted the proceedings that led to North's conviction on three
felony counts.
   Gesell's most serious remedy would be to grant a mistrial.
   Ms. King testified at a hearing Wednesday that she forgot to
disclose on a jury questionnaire form that her brother, Samuel King,
served a year in prison for armed robbery and that she had been
subpoenaed and testified before a grand jury investigating that case.
   Ms. King answered ``no'' in filling out a jury questionnaire Feb.
1 when asked whether she or any member of her immediate family had
ever been involved in a court proceeding or an investigation.
   ``I had forgotten about it after I shed tears ... I couldn't let
it tear me down,'' she testified.
   Ms. King also acknowledged she failed to note her brother's
military service on the juror questionnaire.
   North lawyer Brendan Sullivan asked whether she had omitted it
``for fear someone would check'' and find out the rest of his
background.
   ``That never crossed my mind,'' said Ms. King, who works as a
copy machine operator. She said she was only 2 years old when Sam
King was in the military. She is 34, while he is 51.
   ``It's all coming back to me now,'' Ms. King said at one point as
Sullivan went over documents in the armed robbery investigation.
   North's sentencing had been set for June 23 but was postponed to
July 5 when the juror problem arose. He faces up to 10 years in
prison for aiding and abetting in obstruction of Congress,
destroying or mutilating official documents and accepting a gratuity.
</TEXT>
