<SECOND>AM-Marcos, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0452,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Marcos Suffers Liver Failure; Is Semi-Comatose</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd-4th grafs `Marcos has been ...'' with 5 grafs to UPDATE
with quote from Imelda; raise reference to children; DELETES now outdated
final three grafs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos has
suffered liver failure and the prognosis was ``extremely poor,'' a
hospital administrator said Wednesday night.
   ``Mr. Marcos is semi-comatose, his condition has worsened and
he's not recognizing friends or family,'' said Eugene Tiwanak,
assistant administrator of St. Francis Medical Center, where the
exiled former leader has been hospitalized more than five months.
   ``Everything that can be done has been done. We are hoping for a
miracle,'' Marcos' wife, Imelda, said in an interview outside the
hospital. ``If we could just tell him he could go home, I know that
would save him.''
   The Marcoses' son, Ferdinand ``Bong Bong'' Marcos Jr., also was
at the hospital but declined to talk to reporters.
   The couple's daughter Irene Araneta was on her way to Honolulu
from California, aides said.
   Marcos, who has not been allowed to return to the Philippines,
has been listed in critical condition.
   Marcos suffered heart, lung and kidney failure late last month,
and has been on life-support equipment since.
   ``He's still on the respirator and he's still undergoing kidney
dialysis, but his prognosis is extremely poor,'' Tiwanak said.
   The 71-year-old Marcos has been plagued by a widespread infection
that was not responding to antibiotics, Tiwanak said.
   ``Doctors are trying to treat him, but he's not responding,''
Tiwanak said. ``His fever is real high _ around 103 _ and his
heartbeat is irregular.''
   Marcos and his wife have lived in Honolulu since a 1986 popular
revolt catapulted Corazon Aquino to the presidency, ending his
20-year rule.
   The Marcoses are under indictment in the United States, accused
of stealing more than $100 million from the Philippine treasury and
stashing it in the United States.
</TEXT>
