<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0500EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     06-29 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Blame Environmentalists For Scuttling Ancient Forest Compromise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest lawmakers say despite the collapse of
a proposed compromise, they won't stop trying to negotiate a plan to
provide mills in Oregon and Washington with an adequate supply of
logs while protecting the ancient forests where the spotted owl
nests.
   ``Momentum has been lost, but the public should know that we will
be working to find a way to patch this together,'' Rep. Les AuCoin,
D-Ore., said after emerging from a joint meeting of the Oregon and
Washington state congressional delegations Wednesday.
   Last-minute efforts to revive a compromise that came out of a
weekend ``timber summit'' collapsed Wednesday and congressmen said
they would not try and attach it to the House interior
appropriations bill today.
   However, legislative action may still be possible when the Senate
considers the spending bill in late July.
   AuCoin and other lawmakers blamed environmentalists for scuttling
the compromise, but officials of national environmental groups said
they too were prepared to continue negotiations and thought the
proposal offered a framework for a possible solution.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Report Says 40 Percent Of Hispanic Children Living In Poverty</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 40 percent of Hispanic children are
living in poverty, yet federal policy makers continue to overlook
their needs, according to a Latino advocacy group.
   A report by the National Association of Latino Elected and
Appointed Officials released this week said a Hispanic child is born
into poverty in this country every 3{ minutes.
   NALEO said two of five Hispanic children in 1987 was living at or
below the poverty level of $11,611 for a family of four.
   ``Moreover, the increasing growth of the Hispanic population, a
community which has increased by 30 percent from 1980 to 1987, in
addition to the relative youth of the community, compounds an
already alarming situation,'' the report said. ``Simply stated,
significant numbers of Hispanic children constitute a population at
risk.''
   While Hispanic children comprise approximately 10 percent of all
children in the United States, they represent 27 percent of all
children in poverty, the report said.
   ``Yet the unique needs of Hispanic children in poverty continue
to be overlooked by the nation's federal policy makers, civil
affairs researchers, and the media,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Efforts to Streamline Nuclear Licensing Suffer Setback</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel has dealt a major setback to
efforts by nuclear power supporters to simplify and shorten reactor
licensing.
   The Energy and Commerce Committee on Wednesday voted 22-20 to
omit from a Nuclear Regulatory Commission budget bill a provision
that would have allowed a utility to get both a construction permit
and an operating license at the same time.
   Under current law, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission must wait
until construction is complete to commence hearings on whether to
grant an operating license.
   A major streamlining of commission rules, which took effect last
month, limits the issues that can be raised in hearings on an
operating license. But without legislation the commission may not do
away with that step.
   The industry believes the new commission rules will not produce
the simplification the commission expects and will not do enough to
remove uncertainty.
   The industry has complained for years that the two-stage process
takes too much time and causes too much financial risk, since the
second hearing opens the door to last-minute challenges that can
kill plants that already are completed.
</TEXT>
