<FIRST>r w PM-HUDAudit     06-29 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Audit,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Audit: Healthy Apartment Projects Got Undeserved Federal Money</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-HUD Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development
gave millions of dollars in aid to apartment projects around the
country in 1987 and 1988 that did not meet the department's
eligibility requirements, according to an auditor's report.
   The funds came from a special discretionary fund controlled by
Thomas Demery, then an assistant HUD secretary, that was intended to
help financially ailing projects insured by the Federal Housing
Administration, according to the report released Wednesday by Rep.
Bill Green, R-N.Y.
   Green said the audit of 25 projects that got grants in the 1987
and 1988 fiscal years showed found 11 did not meet HUD
qualifications and that $30 million to $35 million ``went to
undeserving or low-need projects.''
   ``That also means more needy projects went without help and some
of those ultimately failed, adding to the FHA's insurance costs,''
said Green, a former HUD regional housing administrator and the
ranking Republican on the House Appropriations housing subcommittee.
   ``Many of the discretionary funds were made in direct conflict
with existing Office of Housing policies,'' the report concluded,
according to today's editions of The New York Times.
   ``Documentation was not available to justify why these policies
were not followed for the particular awards,'' the Times quoted the
report as saying. ``Consequently, these awards raise concern as to
whether any other factors entered into the decision-making process.''
   In some cases, local HUD offices had recommended against awarding
federal assistance to the apartment projects, while in others, the
local HUD office was bypassed, according to the audit of the Section
8 Discretionary Loan Management Set-Aside Program.
   In one instance, a Chicago apartment owner received $11 million
from HUD even though the apartment building had 100 percent
occupancy, no tenants paying more than 40 percent of their income in
rent, and was rated by HUD as being at no financial risk.
   The audit covered grants for the 1987 and 1988 fiscal years; the
report was completed March 31, 1989.
   The program was designed to avoid failures of troubled housing
projects insured by HUD through the FHA. Failure requires HUD to
assume the mortgages.
   Under the program, projects with low vacancy rates and-or low
tenant income levels are eligible for subsidies to improve a
building's cash flow and ability to meet mortgage payments.
   Many of the projects receiving awards did not file formal
requests for aid through local HUD offices but went directly to
headquarters, according to the audit.
   Demery told the Times that decisions were made only on merit and
need.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
