<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-USPhones     06-29 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-US Phones,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Welcomes Accord on U.S. Access to Tokyo Cellular Phone Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government and industry officials today welcomed an
agreement that would open Japan's multibillion dollar Tokyo
marketplace to American cellular telephones and ease restraints on
business radios.
   The agreement, reached in Washington Wednesday after 10 days of
high-level talks, averts a threatened showdown on U.S.-Japan
telecommunications trade. Washington had said it was prepared to
impose tariffs of as much as 100 percent on more than 50 Japanese
electronics exports.
   ``I am very pleased that the significance of our country's effort
and proposals toward solving the issue was understood by the U.S.
government. I hope again that the latest agreement will contribute
to maintaining and developing Japan-U.S. friendly relations,''
Kanezo Muraoka, minister of Posts and Telecommunications, told a
news conference Wednesday night.
   Prime Minister Sousuke Uno, meeting Japanese reporters this
morning, also hailed as ``very good'' the accord reached between the
two countries, Kyodo News Service said.
   The latest agreement affects cellular phones and ``third-party''
radios, including pagers and equipment for dispatching taxis and
delivery trucks.
   Motorola Inc., the major American maker of cellular phones and
business radios, based in Schaumberg, Ill. contended that the
Japanese restrictions were caysing it $2 billions in lost sales of
five years.
   The American company began selling its cellular phones in Japan
through a Japanese company, Daini-Denden Inc., in 1987.
   But Motorola's phones do not work in the Tokyo area, because
Motorola equipment is not compatible with the cellular phone network
operated by Japan's giant Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp.
   ``We highly value that U.S. retaliation was avoided by the
settlement,'' Haruo Ozawa, an executive director of the
Communications Industry Association of Japan, a grouping of 230
telecommunications equipment makers, said in a statement.
   But Ozawa said Japanese industry should not be optimistic about
future trade relations, as the countries' trade imbalance has yet to
be solved. According to U.S. figures, the United States ran a $52
billion trade defict with Japan last year.
</TEXT>
