<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--PoisonedCooler     06-29 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Poisoned Cooler,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cleaning Crew Man Charged with Poisoning Water Cooler</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cleaning-crew worker tried to poison his boss
by dumping cyanide into a water cooler in a U.S. Food and Drug
Administration office, authorities said.
   The boss didn't drink the water. But an electrician working in
the federal building office in Brooklyn drank from the cooler and
become violently ill June 21.
   The electrician was treated at a hospital but was not seriously
injured.
   FDA officials analyzed the water cooler and found up to 3 grams
of powdered cyanide in the container.
   Hector Cabassa, 25, was arraigned Wednesday before U.S.
Magistrate John Caden.
   Cabassa had told the FBI he stole the cyanide from the FDA's
laboratory and put it into the cooler after he argued with his boss,
authorities said.
   Cabassa was charged with reckless endangerment on a government
reservation, said FBI spokesman Joe Valiquette.
</TEXT>
