<FIRST>r a PM-RockyFlats     06-29 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rocky Flats,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Called for Rocky Flats Investigation; Safety Agreement
Signed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ordered a special grand jury
impaneled to investigate alleged environmental violations at Rocky
Flats nuclear weapons plant.
   U.S. Energy Secretary James Watkins, meanwhile, pledged that the
plant will be run safely or not at all. He said, however, that an
agreement signed with Gov. Roy Romer will help ensure that it is run
properly.
   ``There's a whole new ball game at Rocky Flats,'' Watkins said
Wednesday during a visit to New Mexico. ``We have put in a new team
of line managers, working with a new site manager.''
   The agreement, signed during a meeting at the Waste Isolation
Pilot Plant near Carlsbad, N.M., will allow Colorado to monitor
Rocky Flats more closely, Romer said.
   In Denver, U.S. District Court Judge Sherman Finesilver said a
23-member special grand jury was needed because of the possibility
of a long and complicated investigation. It will be the first time
in 27 years that a special grand jury was called in the federal
district of Colorado, said court clerk Jim Manspeaker.
   ``The special grand jury will have to utilize its complete
energies in pursuance of this directive,'' Finesilver said. Colorado
has two regular grand juries.
   On Jun 6, FBI and Environmental Protection Agency investigators
raided the plant, 15 miles northwest of Denver, looking for evidence
of criminal environmental violations, including illegal disposal of
hazardous wastes. The Department of Energy plant is operated by
Rockwell International and uses plutonium to make triggers for
nuclear bombs.
   The FBI affidavit that led to the search warrant alleged that
plant workers illegally burned and dumped hazardous wastes and that
the plant illegally discharged pollutants into two creeks that flow
into water supplies serving four suburbs.
   Agents completed the search of Rocky Flats last week and are now
checking truckloads of documents.
   Acting U.S. Attorney Mike Norton said unlike a regular grand
jury, the special grand jury will have the power to issue public
reports on its investigation, even if no criminal activity is found.
   Finesilver issued the order Wednesday at the request of the
prosecutors. The 23 jurors are to be chosen and ready for duty Aug.
1.
   Romer hailed the decision.
   ``I welcome anything that helps get the complete facts on the
table. We need to remove the mystery about Rocky Flats and I think a
grand jury will help accomplish that. I want all of the truth to
come out,'' Romer said.
   The agreement signed by Watkins and Romer was worked out two
weeks ago after the Justice Department announced its Rocky Flats
investigation. Watkins said the purpose of the agreement was to
ensure the plant was run safely.
   ``If either of us is not convinced of that, then we'll both shut
it down,'' he said.
   The Waste Isolation Pilot Plant near Carlsbad also was a focus of
the meeting. The plant, proposed as the nation's first permanent
nuclear waste repository, originally was scheduled to open last
October.
   That date was revised to September 1989, but Watkins said this
week it won't open until the federal government shows it can safely
transport and bury nuclear waste.
   ``We will open WIPP, but we will open it when it's ready,''
Watkins said at a news conference following a meeting with the
governors of New Mexico, Idaho and Colorado.
   The governors said they were pleased with Watkins' take-charge
attitude toward the growing nuclear waste problem, but they were
unwilling to budge on their stance toward the problem.
   New Mexico Gov. Garrey Carruthers said his state won't accept any
nuclear waste until DOE meets all commitments to the state; Gov.
Cecil Andrus said Idaho won't accept any more waste after August;
and Romer said he will shut down the Rocky Flats if its storage
capacity is met.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
