<FIRST>r a PM-EscapeeSurrenders     06-29 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Escapee Surrenders,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convicted Murderer Surrenders From New Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAU CLAIRE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Harrison says she didn't know until
her husband disappeared last week that he had a hidden past as a
convicted murderer who escaped from an Alabama prison six years ago.
   Mrs. Harrison said the man she knew as Lee Wesley Harrison had
become a good stepfather to her three daughters, and the couple has
a 2-year-old daughter and another child on the way.
   ``This is just unreal,'' Mrs. Harrison said. ``He was just a
great husband and a great father. Even tempered. When we had our
little spats _ which wasn't very often _ he'd just walk away.''
   Her husband, whose real name is Larry Owen Weeks, disappeared for
a week after learning he was under investigation but surrendered
Tuesday to authorities at the Eau Claire County Airport.
   ``When he arrived at the airport he was rather emotional. He was
very scared,'' police Capt. Steve Hahn said. ``He indicated that he
did not want to hurt anybody and he did not want to be hurt himself,
so he felt the best thing to do at that point was to surrender.''
   Officials with the Alabama Department of Corrections said
Wednesday that if Weeks refused to sign a waiver, the state would
start extradition proceedings.
   Weeks appeared Wednesday in Eau Claire County Circuit Court and
was ordered held without bond. He was charged with driving a vehicle
without the owner's consent for allegedly taking his
brother-in-law's vehicle without permission when he fled.
   Authorities said Weeks worked for a contractor and stayed out of
trouble since his 1983 arrival in Eau Claire, 200 miles northwest of
Milwaukee.
   He had been serving a life sentence without parole for the 1981
murder of a 49-year-old man in Alabama. According to reports, Weeks
and a female accomplice kidnapped the man, drove him to a desolate
area and shot him in the head.
   Alabama authorities said Weeks was 21 at the time, although
police in Eau Claire said Weeks told them he was 17 when the crime
occurred.
   Weeks escaped from prison in April 1983 and came to Eau Claire
because he had relatives in the area, police said.
   Mrs. Harrison, 35, said she did not learn of her husband's past
until last week. She said when she asked about his past, he would
tell her he was sexually abused as a child and did not want to talk
about it.
   ``The children can't believe it, and they say there isn't
anything they wouldn't do for him,'' she said.
</TEXT>
