<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0537EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Children-ReportCard     06-29 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Children-Report Card,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Advocacy Group Gives California Low Grade for Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California gets an overall `D' grade for its
efforts to keep children healthy, in school and out of jail,
according to a report card from an advocacy group.
   ``I'm anything but proud of the results that have been achieved
in California for children,'' said Wendy Lazarus of Children Now,
which released the report Wednesday. ``We cannot tolerate a
situation in which we are losing so much in human lives.''
   The non-profit, non-partisan group founded last year based its
``Children's Report Card'' on 27 factors, such as test scores and
the number of children in foster homes and jails.
   The report was strongly criticized by Gov. George Deukmejian.
   ``California ... spends more on poor children than any other
state,'' he said. ``If that deserves a D, the report card deserves
an F.''
   But state schools chief William Honig agreed with the report's
conclusion.
   ``There is a major problem on comprehensive children's
programs,'' he said. ``There's been an explosive growth in poverty
... and we're all going to pay the price.''
   Statistics gathered by Children Now showed that compared to other
states, California ranked worse than the national average in many
areas, ranging from the student-teacher ratio in classes to the
number of youth homicides.
   The statistics indicated that the number of children living in
poverty _ 1.6 million _ rose 47 percent between 1981 and 1987 and
that child abuse reports jumped 135 percent between 1980 and 1988.
   The report also found that the percentage of juveniles locked up
in California is twice as high as in the nation overall and the
state's teen-age pregnancy rate is the second highest in the country.
   But the state fared better than most in a few areas, including
infant mortality rates, Scholastic Aptitude Test scores for
college-bound students and public assistance payments.
   The grades were compiled by a panel of five, based on statistics
from various state and federal agencies.
   The panel included California Supreme Court Justice Allen
Broussard; Stanford University President Donald Kennedy; former U.S.
Secretary of Education Shirley Hufstedler; teacher Jaime Escalante
whose life was depicted in the film ``Stand and Deliver''; and
former baseball commissioner Peter Ueberroth.
</TEXT>
