<FIRST>r a PM-BigamistRequest     06-29 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bigamist Request,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magistrate Delays Ruling on Request to Free Convicted Bigamist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An imprisoned bigamist who made the ``Guinness
Book of World Records'' for having more than 100 wives is seeking
his freedom on the grounds he received bad legal advice.
   But a magistrate has delayed making a decision on the case.
   Donald E. Wilkes, Jr., a University of Georgia law professor, on
Wednesday told U.S. Magistrate Morton Sitver that Giovanni Vigliotto
was influenced by questionable counsel when he withdrew his appeal
of his 1983 conviction.
   Vigliotto, now a 60-year-old diabetic and a stroke victim who
needs a wheelchair, is serving a 34-year prison term for bigamy and
fraud. He once acknowledged having married 105 women without
divorcing them, becoming the subject of the news, talk shows and
made-for-TV movies.
   State Assistant Attorney General Joe Maziarz asked Sitver to
dismiss the petition with prejudice _ meaning it could not be
refiled _ because Vigliotto had withdrawn his appeal and failed to
appeal systematically through the state courts.
   Maziarz said the state courts have ``bent over backwards'' for
the bigamist and even have appointed an attorney to discuss with
Vigliotto his decision to withdraw his appeal.
   Instead, Vigliotto refused to talk to the attorney, calling him
``a lackey of the court and a friend of the judges,'' Maziarz told
Sitver.
   Sitver gave Vigliotto's counsel 20 days to submit a revised writ
for habeas corpus to conform with Arizona requirements and said he
would issue his decision once that was done.
   Private investigator Patricia O'Connor, who is coordinating an
effort to free the former flea-market trader who has been declared
indigent by Maricopa Superior Court, said several other lawyers have
been hired to represent Vigliotto.
   ``I thought I was going to be here by myself,'' Wilkes said
before leaving to catch a plane. He was flanked by several others in
the courtroom during a posthearing press conference.
   ``The Vigliotto case is Arizona's `Mississippi Burning' in my
view,'' said Ralph Temple, a former director of the American Civil
Liberties Union in Washington.
   Temple said he and the others were aiding Vigliotto because he
was denied a fair trial and was dealt an irrationally severe
sentence.
   Maziarz said later that Vigliotto's sentencing was more severe
because of prior convictions.
   Vigliotto's petition was filed in federal court because the state
has frustrated his attempts for due process in denying him access to
legal materials needed for a trial, Temple said.
   Asked whether Arizona's courts were capable of giving Vigliotto a
fair trail, attorney Edwin Sigel said, ``They haven't done it in the
past.''
   Vigliotto's legal team claims 277 instances of judicial and
prosecutorial misconduct and ineffective counsel.
</TEXT>
