<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-Convention     06-29 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Convention,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convention Spurs Entreaties Against Civil Disobedience</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Scotus-Cases, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARREN MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates arriving for the National
Right to Life Committee's annual convention were met by pro-choice
pickets and asked not to engage in civil disobedience at abortion
clinics.
   About 1,200 members of the nation's largest anti-abortion lobby
were beginning their meeting today as the U.S. Supreme Court was
expected to release its decision on a Missouri law restricting
abortion availability and defining life as starting at conception.
   On Wednesday, Mayor Don Fraser of nearby Minneapolis urged
conventioneers to remain within the law in any demonstrations.
   Several pro-choice pickets walked outside the Radisson South
Hotel later in the day as delegates arrived.
   ``If they break the law we'll ask the police to intervene. But
we'd like to avoid that,'' Fraser told reporters as about 30
anti-abortion protesters held up posters of fetuses and fetal parts.
   Representatives of abortion clinics in the Twin Cities area had
asked the mayors of Minneapolis, St. Paul and Bloomington to issue
pleas against civil disobedience while conventioneers are in
Minnesota. Mayors George Latimer of St. Paul and Kurt Laughinghouse
of Bloomington issued no statements.
   ``With the convention coming into town, I think it's appropriate
that we call upon our mayors to set a tone,'' said Jeri Rasmussen,
executive director of Midwest Health Center for Women, one of six
Twin Cities clinics that perform abortions.
   Rasmussen said at a news conference she was especially concerned
following a demonstration at her downtown Minneapolis clinic Friday.
Police arrested 153 abortion opponents who blocked the clinic
entrance and packed the hallway outside the clinic.
   ``Clearly there are differing views on the abortion issue in the
United States and in this community,'' Fraser said. ``Active,
vigorous debate and dissent is a part of our American freedoms.
   ``Our concern is that protest and dissent be peaceful and
especially that those dissenting not inflict harm on others.''
   Rasmussen said the last three conferences of the National Right
to Life Committee, which claims 2,500 local affiliates in 50 states,
have coincided with attacks on clinics.
   ``What we're anticipating is conducting our clinic as usual, but
we're prepared for any eventuality,'' Rasmussen said.
   Jackie Schweitz, executive director of Minnesota Citizens
Concerned for Life, the convention's host group, said neither her
organization nor the National Right to Life Committee is involved in
civil disobedience.
   ``I don't know of any demonstrations planned. The business of
this convention is education,'' Schweitz said, as delegates look at
ways to provide alternatives to abortion, infanticide and euthanasia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
