<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0608EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LakeMichiganFish     06-29 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lake Michigan Fish,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wildlife Group Cautions Anglers on Cancer Risks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD EGGLESTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Wildlife Federation today said
people who eat Lake Michigan sport fish face a greater risk of
cancer than previously believed due to toxic contamination.
   Wisconsin health officials and toxic-pollution experts, however,
criticized the nation's largest conservation organization's
estimates of cancer risk as too high and likely to confuse fish
eaters.
   The federation calculated that over a lifetime a person who eats
as few as 11 meals of Lake Michigan lake trout longer than 30 inches
faces a one in 10,000 risk of cancer. The figures were based on
levels of four toxic chemicals the fish are likely to contain.
   The wildlife federation recommended that pregnant women, women
who intend to have children, nursing mothers and children age 15 or
younger not eat any lake trout, brown trout, chinook salmon, coho
salmon, walleye or yellow perch from the lake.
   In a 17-page booklet, produced after two years of research, the
federation also urges fishermen to pressure public officials to
control toxic-chemical pollution in the lake.
   ``The problem is the pollution sources, and the solution is to
insist that industry and government clean them up,'' federation
president Jay D. Hair said.
   Wisconsin officials said the group's recommendations may confuse
fishermen and their families because it conflicts with a Lake
Michigan fish advisory jointly issued by Wisconsin, Michigan,
Illinois and Indiana.
   The joint health advisory does not advise women and children
against eating lake trout less than 20 inches long, coho less than
26 inches long, chinook less than 21 inches long or brook trout or
perch.
   The longer and older a fish, the more likely it is have in its
tissues toxic chemicals like PCBs and the pesticides DDT, dieldrin
and chordane.
   ``All it's going to do is confuse the public on an issue that's
already complex,'' Lee Liebenstein, toxic substances specialist in
Wisconsin's Department of Natural Resources, said of the report.
``We've got experts arguing among themselves in the media, and
that's a no-win situation.''
   ``What they've done is not an accurate estimation of the true
risk,'' said Dr. Henry Anderson, chief of environmental epidemiology
for the Wisconsin Division of Health. ``It's a very conservative
assessment.''
   Dean Heili of Manitowoc, legislative chairman of the Wisconsin
Federation of Great Lakes Sport Fishing Clubs, said his group is
sticking with the advice issued by the four states.
   ``Public health and water quality standards are too important to
be used as political footballs,'' he said.
   Lake Michigan fishing is a $4.8 billion a year business, Heili
said, and employs 36,000 people in Wisconsin alone.
   Mark Van Putten, director of the wildlife federation's Great
Lakes Natural Resource Center in Ann Arbor, Mich., said his group
shares the concern that conflicting advice could cause confusion.
   But, according to the wildlife federation, the four states'
advice is based on outdated U.S. Food and Drug Administration
numbers. Lake Michigan anglers also eat more fish than the average
American, a figure used by the FDA to base its calculations, Van
Putten said.
   ``What we're talking about is giving the people the best
information that's available,'' he said. ``We are a conservation and
education organization, and this is consistent with our mission.''
   But Wisconsin's Liebenstein defended the states' advisory. ``We
believe what we have is very good at protecting the public health,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
