<HEAD>Judged Unfit to Stand Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of killing his wife and then
commandeering an airplane and firing an assault rifle onto Boston
streets from the air was judged incompetent to stand trial for
murder.
   Brockton District Court Judge Charles E. Black made the ruling
Wednesday after reviewing a psychiatrist's evaluation, said Stephen
O'Connell, spokesman for the Essex County district attorney's office.
   Alfred Hunter, 42, was committed to Bridgewater State Hospital
for up to six months. Another competency hearing may be scheduled at
that time.
   Hunter was accused of shooting his ex-wife, Elvira, eight times
with the assault rifle in front of their 5-year-old son on May 10.
   Authorities say he then took a small plane at gunpoint and buzzed
several Boston neighborhoods and Logan International Airport,
forcing officials to flee the control tower twice.
   Hunter later surrendered. He pleaded innocent to charges of
murder and armed robbery.
</TEXT>
