<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-29 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms in Plains, Rain on Gulf Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms blew through the Plains with 60 mph winds, damaging
hail and heavy rain, and the remnants of Tropical Storm Allison
continued to swamp Louisiana.
   Storms developed Wednesday evening from the Dakotas to the Texas
Panhandle, with some of the most severe storms in Kansas.
   In the town of Goodland, winds gusted to 68 mph, two-inch hail
smashed windows and car windshields and more than 4 inches of rain
flooded streets and basements. In western Kansas, 8{ inches of rain
covered fields and damaged crops along the Sherman-Thomas county
line.
   Winds gusting to 63 mph downed trees at Mobridge, S.D., and ping
pong ball-size hail fell at Bismarck, N.D.
   Storms also were strong over eastern portions of Colorado and New
Mexico. Winds gusted to 60 mph at Cheyenne Wells, Colo., and
combined with heavy rain to reduce visibilities to near zero.
   Allison continued to make its presence felt along the Gulf Coast.
Eleven inches of rain fell in just over 4 hours at Winnfield, La.,
closing all roads leading to the town. Nearly 2 inches of rain fell
in 2 hours at Lake Charles.
   Many streams and bayous were swollen or out of their banks across
southeast Texas and southern Louisiana, causing street flooding.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered from the middle and
southern Atlantic Coast states into Florida. A thunderstorm dumped 2
to 3 inches of rain in a two-hour period near Fort Valley, Ga.
   A cold front brought showers to the central and northern Pacific
Coast.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
eastern Texas across the Gulf Coast and the Tennessee Valley to
Florida and the southern Atlantic Coast. Scattered showers and
thunderstorms also were predicted for the upper Mississippi Valley
and eastern Montana. Rain was expected along the northern Pacific
Coast and across the Pacific Northwest.
   Highs were expected to be in the 60s and 70s from the eastern
half of the upper Mississippi Valley across the Great Lakes and much
of the Ohio Valley into New England, and in the Pacific Northwest
and along the California coast; the 90s from the northern Plains
across the central and southern Rockies, much of Arizona and New
Mexico and south-central and southwest Texas, as well as from the
South Carolina coast into Florida; above 100 degrees from the Rio
Grande Valley of Texas to the Desert Southwest; and in the 80s
elsewhere.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 35 degrees at Marquette,
Mich., to 92 degrees at Blythe, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 72 foggy; Boston 67 partly cloudy; Buffalo 54
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 77 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 69 fair;
Cleveland 58 partly cloudy; Detroit 51 fair; Miami 75 partly cloudy;
New York 73 fair; Philadelphia 68 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 58 fair;
Portland, Maine 62 fair; Washington 74 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 63 fair; Chicago 57 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 76
fair; Denver 63 cloudy; Des Moines 70 fair; Indianapolis 62 fair;
Kansas City 71 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 67 fair; Nashville 70
foggy; New Orleans 79 cloudy; St. Louis 72 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 76 fair; Anchorage 65 fair; Las Vegas 82 fair;
Los Angeles 61 fair; Phoenix 89 fair; Salt Lake City 67 fair; San
Diego 64 fair; San Francisco 57 partly cloudy; Seattle 58 rain.
   _Canada: Montreal 55 showers; Toronto 48 fair.
</TEXT>
