<FIRST>r i PM-NorthernIreland     06-29 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Passenger Train Bombed, No Injuries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passenger train was rocked by
a bomb blast this morning but no one was injured, police said.
   The device exploded at 7:25 a.m. on the tracks as a Northern
Ireland Railways train was operating a few miles west of Coleraine
on the line to Londonderry, according to the Royal Ulster
Constabulary.
   The driver was badly shaken but not hospitalized, a police
spokesman said. No group immediately claimed responsibility for the
attack.
   The Irish Republican Army has made Northern Ireland Railways the
target of more than 20 bomb attacks since mid-December. All the
bombs were on the Belfast-Dublin line but none caused any injuries
or damaged any trains.
   The IRA had usually given advance warning of bombs on the
Belfast-Dublin line, and police said many of those explosives were
accompanied by booby-trap devices apparently intended to kill
soldiers called to clear the line.
   The IRA, an outlawed, predominantly Roman Catholic paramilitary
group, has fought a 20-year guerrilla war against British rule in
Northern Ireland.
</TEXT>
