<FIRST>r a PM-Bicycle-Slaying     06-29 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bicycle-Slaying,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted 10 Years Later In Boy's Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tenacity of two detectives finally paid off
when a 27-year-old man was convicted of killing a boy 10 years ago
after he refused to hand over his new 10-speed bicycle.
   Pedro Lozado was convicted Wednesday in the death of 12-year-old
Tireak Ghandy. Lozado faces a mandatory sentence of life in prison
when he's sentenced Aug. 10.
   On July 30, 1979, Tireak took his new $250 bike to Yankee Stadium.
   ``The kid was doing what every kid who ever grew up in the Bronx
did. He rode his bike to Yankee Stadium,'' Detective John Hennessy
said last year after he and Detective Jerry Dunn finally got enough
evidence to arrest Lozado.
   Tireak was leaving the stadium when Lozado demanded the bike.
When the boy resisted, Lozado stabbed him in the heart.
   ``This guy was a lot bigger than him. He could have smacked the
kid in the mouth and taken the bike, that's all he really had to do.
He didn't have to stab him,'' Hennessy said.
   As Tireak fell, the attacker snatched a basketball from his hands
and escaped on his bike. The child was bleeding so badly that police
didn't wait for an ambulance, but drove him to the hospital
themselves. He was dead before they reached the emergency room.
   After getting a lead during questioning of another man, Hennessy
and Dunn spent 18 months tracking down witnesses to the stabbing.
   Hennessy and Dunn arrested Lozado April 20, 1988, after he
visited his parole officer and charged him with murder, robbery and
possession of a deadly weapon.
   Lozado had been released from prison in December 1987 after
serving three years for criminal possession of stolen property.
   ``He couldn't believe that after all these years, it had caught
up with him,'' Dunn said at the time. ``I guess he figured he'd beat
it.''
</TEXT>
