<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0726EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-France-Terrorism     06-29 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Terrorism,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Direct Action Leaders Given Life Sentences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYON, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special court convicted three leaders of
the left-wing terrorist group Direct Action today and sentenced them
to life in prison on charges including the murder of a civilian
guard and two policemen.
   The seven-judge court also convicted 14 other defendents and gave
them prison sentences ranging from 10 months to seven years.
   The verdict on charges running to 340 pages, arising from three
murders, three armed assaults, and 32 armed robberies committed
between 1980 and 1986 was handed down after seven hours of
deliberation.
   The Lyon-based group's ideological leader Andre Olivier, 46, and
his hand-picked deputy Maxime Frerot, 33, the group's explosives
expert, must serve at least 18 years of their sentences.
   Emile Ballandras, 40, must serve at least 16 years of his life
sentence, the court ruled.
   Olivier, his companion Joelle Crepet, 32, Frerot and Bernard
Blanc, 29, were convicted of three murders committed during a
hold-up. Killed were Henri Delrieu, an employee of an armored
vehicle company, and two police officers, Guy Hubert and Guy
Delfosse.
   Blanc was given an extra five-year sentence on top of the 15
years the prosecution had demanded, while Crepet received 18 years
in prison.
   The trial began May 16 amid tight security with hundreds of
police stationed around the courthouse.
   After the verdict was announced Andre Olivier broke into the
Internationale, the international anthem of socialism. He was joined
by Blanc and Frerot before they were led away in handcuffs.
   Direct Action first made headlines in 1979 with a series of
bombings and assasinations against Interpol, labor and immigration
offices and corporate headquarters.
   The attacks which formed the basis for the Lyon trial were
principally staged to finance the group's activities, prosecutors
said.
   Most of the defendents in Lyon will face another trial in Paris
on charges related to 27 other terrorist attacks. It has not yet
been scheduled.
</TEXT>
