<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0753EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SouthKorea     06-29 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Korea,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Students Battle Police, Demand to Attend Youth Festival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of radical students battled
riot police with firebombs, rocks and clubs today to demand they be
allowed to attend a youth festival in communist North Korea. At
least 13 people, including a policeman, were reported injured.
   About 1,500 students attacked 3,000 police at Seoul's Hanyang
University after authorities locked the school gates and refused for
the third day to allow anyone inside for protest rallies.
   Waves of students climbed over school walls, throwing rocks and
firebombs and trying to break through police lines so about 1,000
colleagues several blocks away could get inside the campus.
   As the fighting continued, students from other colleges who had
assembled outside the campus raced through the streets and crawled
over broken walls to gain entrance.
   ``Drive out Yankees who block national unification!'' and
``Overthrow Roh Tae-woo!'' the protesters yelled. Radical students
are demanding the withdrawal of 43,000 U.S. troops stationed in
South Korea and the ouster of President Roh Tae-woo.
   Police threw back rocks and tear gas grenades, injuring at least
a dozen students. One policeman was seriously injured when tear gas
exploded inside the armored van he was driving, authorities said.
   The students were protesting a government ban on attending the
July 1-8 World Youth Festival in North Korea's capital, Pyongyang.
``Let's march to Pyongyang!'' they shouted.
   In downtown Seoul, hundreds of students throwing firebombs and
rocks fought riot police, forcing shoppers to race for shelter.
Traffic came to a halt and tear gas wafted through the air.
   Yonhap, the South Korean news agency, said the downtown fighting
started when about 700 students from three schools marched to the
city center.
   The Seoul government has accused North Korea of using the
festival to stir up dissent in South Korea.
   North Korea invited South Korean students to attend the youth
festival, an athletic and cultural festival mainly featuring
non-aligned and communist nations.
   The two Koreas have been bitter rivals since the peninsula was
divided into the communist North and the capitalist South at the end
of World War II. The North invaded the South to begin the 1950-53
Korean War.
</TEXT>
