<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-MiGCrash     06-29 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-MiG Crash,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet MiG Crashed at Air Show Because of Bird, Panel Concludes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet MiG-29 jet fighter that crashed in flames
at the Paris Air Show went down because a small bird was sucked into
its engine, a commission has concluded.
   Specialists found feathers sticking to the wrecked engine's
blades, the newspaper Socialist Industry said today, quoting the
head of the French-Soviet panel's Soviet contingent, Donat
Ogorodnikov.
   The commission's findings absolved the organizers of the June air
show of all blame, the newspaper said.
   Some reports had said another plane taxiing near the low-flying
MiG-29 might have kicked up a stone from the runway that flew into
the MiG's engine.
   ``That assumption threw a shadow on the organizers of the show,
who were justifiably humiliated,'' newspaper said.
   The fighter crashed June 8 as it was making its final pass over
the Le Bourget airfield north of Paris. Its pilot, Anatoly Kvochur,
survived after ejecting from the low-flying jet and plummeting to
the ground with his parachute only partly opened.
   Days later, he and a Soviet aviation designer speculated that a
bird caused the crash.
   The MiG-29, a twin-engine combat aircraft, has been in operation
since 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
