<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0818EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-ShoeProtest     06-29 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shoe Protest,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes Outside Bata Shop, 2 Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded today outside a shoe
store where shoes considered offensive to Islam are sold, and two
people were wounded, police said.
   No one claimed responsibility for the blast, which ripped open
the steel doors of the closed shop in the resort town of Cox's
Bazar, said a police official in Dhaka, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Cox's Bazar, on the Bay of Bengal, is 185 miles south of Dhaka.
   The targeted shoe store is owned by the Canadian-based Bata
company. Bata closed its shops in Bangladesh last week, fearing
violence by Moslem fundamentalists who say the design on one of its
slippers is offensive.
   The Moslems contend the design, which the company says is three
interwined bells, resembles the Arabic characters for Allah.
   One person was killed and 50 were wounded Sunday when police
opened fire on a mob that tried to raid a Bata store near Dhaka.
   About 90 percent of Bangladesh's 110 million people are Moslem.
   The country was the scene of violent protests earlier this year
by Moslems who considered Salman Rushdie's book, ``The Satanic
Verses,'' offensive to Islam.
</TEXT>
