<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0480,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egypt, Lebanon Resume Diplomatic Ties</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds one graf after last, ``At the ...'' to UPDATE with Egyptians
saying Moslem and Christian Lebanese leaders approved the move. No Pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt and Lebanon today announced the
resumption of diplomatic ties, severed 10 years ago after Egypt
signed a peace treaty with Israel.
   The resumption of diplomatic relations left Syria and Libya as
the only Arab states that have not restored links with Egypt after a
1987 Arab League summit in Amman, Jordan, gave the go-ahead for
members to do so.
   Cairo's relations with both Syria and Libya improved considerably
after last month's Arab summit in Casablanca, Morocco, which saw
Egypt's return to its League seat after a 10-year suspension.
   President Hosni Mubarak had separate reconciliation meetings with
Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi and President Hafez Assad of Syria on
the sidelines of the Casablanca summit.
   The Libyan-Egyptian border, closed since 1977, has since been
re-opened and air traffic between the two countries resumed.
Egyptian officials expect diplomatic ties with Libya and Syria to be
restored in the near future.
   A joint statement issued simultaneously in Cairo and Beirut said:
``Egypt and Lebanon have decided to resume full diplomatic relations
starting today, Thursday.''
   Lebanon was among 17 Arab countries that severed diplomatic ties
with Egypt in 1979 to protest its treaty with Israel. Egypt's
membership in the Arab League also was frozen.
   At the Casablanca summit, Egypt joined Kuwait and Jordan in
drafting a proposal to end the 14-year civil war in Lebanon. A final
seven-point plan on Lebanon, stressing the country's unity and
territorial integrity, was based on that proposal.
   Today's statement did not mention Lebanon's divided government.
But Egyptian officials said both the Moslem Cabinet of acting Prime
Minister Salim Hoss and the rival Christian Cabinet of Army Gen.
Michel Aoun approved the move.
</TEXT>
