<HEAD>Airliner Crash-lands In Fog, Killing Three</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YAOUNDE, Cameroon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine plane carrying 43
passengers and four crew members crash-landed in fog at Yaounde
airport, killing three people, authorities said today.
   The Hawker Siddley HS748-2B, of the state airline Camair, crashed
Wednesday night at the airport in Cameroon's capital after a flight
from the coastal city of Douala, 120 miles west, said Transport
Minister Paul Tessa.
   French pilot Blaise Arnaud made three passes at the fogged-in
airport, then landed about midway down the runway, smashed into a
tree past the end of the tarmac and plunged into a ravine, Tessa
said.
   Arnaud died along with co-pilot, Nendah James, of Cameroon,
according to airline officials. The did not identify the third
victim.
   Two other people had broken bones and were taken to a nearby
hospital, officials said.
