<FIRST>u a PM-CalifFires     06-29 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Calif Fires,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wildfires Blacken More Than 10,000 Acres, Imperil Homes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters today worked to protect lakeside
homes from the fiercer of two fickle fires that have blackened
10,000 acres of Southern California brush, forced thousands to flee
and destroyed nine structures.
   ``The fire made a pretty good run toward the homes and actually
came into the structure area, but no buildings were lost,'' Capt.
Will Donaldson of the California Department of Forestry said early
today.
   More than 200 families living on the Lake Elsinore shore and in
the mountains nearby were evacuated because of the 6,500-acre fire
that started Tuesday in the Cleveland National Forest, 60 miles
southeast of Los Angeles.
   The fire destroyed six structures and forced the evacuation of a
youth correctional facility, a nudist colony and many homes and
cabins. It threatened an undisclosed number of homes on the lake and
in the mountains.
   Three firefighters suffered back injuries. More than 750 battled
the blaze, which jumped two fire lines.
   ``I'm nervous, I'm shaking,'' said Cynthia Hayes, who was
evacuated to a high school with her two children. ``I understand I'm
in brush country, but this makes me think twice. You think it's
never going to happen to you.''
   About 300 firefighters in the Antelope Valley 45 miles north of
Los Angeles battled a 3,700-acre blaze that destroyed a ranch house
and its two barns and forced 2,500 residents to flee. The fire began
Wednesday.
   Nearly all the evacuees were back home by early today, said
firefighter Al Smith.
   ``The fire is laying down at this time, but we do expect it to
stand up and take off when the sun rises,'' he said. ``Where it goes
during the day is anyone's guess.''
   ``There was smoke everywhere,'' said Chuck Lamb, who fled from
his Antelope Valley home. ``The flames must have jumped a couple of
hundred yards, and then of course everything got very very dark,
very very smoky, and there was a brief time when I didn't know
whether I lost my house or not.''
   He later discovered his home was safe but said that when he fled,
``I grabbed all sorts of bizarre stuff. I just cleaned out stuff out
of my wife's closet. I don't even know to this minute what I've got
in the suitcase in the back of my car.''
</TEXT>
