<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0905EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-PalmeTrial     06-29 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palme Trial,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Hear Conspiracy Theory In Palme Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CECILIA LONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Swedish court refused today to hear
testimony that an international conspiracy may have been behind the
1986 slaying of Prime Minister Olof Palme.
   Stockholm District Court ruled that allegations Kurdish
separatists plotted the assassination are irrelevant to the trial of
Christer Pettersson, who denies killing Palme.
   Palme, who dominated Swedish politics for more than a decade, was
gunned down while walking home from a movie with his wife, Lisbeth.
   Judge Carl Anton Spak rejected a defense request to call former
intelligence agent Jan Henrik Barrling to recount his investigation
of the militant Kurdish Workers Party. The group was the focus of a
yearlong police investigation into the killing. The investigation
was closed for lack of evidence.
   Barrling's testimony ``lacks relevance to the case,'' Spak said.
   The Kurdish group was suspected because the Palme government held
several of its members under house arrest as suspected terrorists
and denied refugee status to one of its leaders.
   The prosecution today called a 34-year-old music teacher to the
stand. He appeared to be the only witness to see the shooting from
beginning to end.
   Inge Morelius said he saw a man standing by a shop window as
Palme and his wife walked past. Morelius said the man, whom he could
not identify, went up behind the couple, put his left hand on
Palme's left shoulder and his right hand in Palme's back.
   Asked if he saw a weapon, Morelius said, ``Its difficult to say
about that, reconstructing it afterward. But I saw clearly and
distinctly two flashes. He pulled off two shots at once. It was
bang, bang, maybe one or 1{ seconds between them.
   ``It was slaughter. It was an execution. It was nothing done in
the heat of the moment,'' Morelius said.
   He said he saw Lisbeth Palme look twice at the gunman. Mrs. Palme
identified Pettersson in court last week as the man she saw lean
over her husband when he fell to the ground. She said she did not
see him shoot Palme or see any gun.
   Morelius said the man took a few steps, then circled around and
looked at Mrs. Palme again while she knelt beside her dying husband.
The man then turned, trotted up a side street and was lost in the
darkness, the witness said.
   Earlier witnesses identified Pettersson as the man who appeared
to wait outside the movie theater for the Palmes to emerge, then
followed them down the street.
</TEXT>
