<FIRST>r i PM-France-Libya     06-29 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Libya,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>France Shipping Non-Lethal Military Equipment to Libya</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France is allowing shipment of spare parts for
non-lethal military equipment to Libya, the Defense Ministry
announced. It said this will not violate a 1986 European embargo.
   French news commentaries said today the action appears to be a
response to apparent moderation in recent statements and actions by
Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi.
   ``France has simply taken note of a certain number of
demonstrations of appeasement on the part of Col. Gadhafi,'' the
conservative Le Figaro said in a front-page editorial.
   A Defense Ministry statement Wednesday said the exports were
approved by the Interministerial Commission for Export of War
Materiel. It denied that Crotale surface-to-air missiles were
involved and said France will permit no new weapons sales to Libya.
   Reports by Le Figaro, Agence France-Presse and other French news
organizations quoted unidentified officials as saying the parts will
be used to repair radar systems.
   The European Economic Community banned arms sales to Libya in
April 1986 amid reports linking Gadhafi's government to terrorist
attacks. At about the same time, the United States bombed the Libyan
capital, Tripoli, and Benghazi, citing alleged terrorist links.
</TEXT>
