<FIRST>r a PM-LastTemptation     06-29 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Last Temptation,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Video Arrives in Some Stores, But Without Fanfare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Last Temptation of Christ,''
the subject of one of the most virulent protests in Hollywood
history, is being released today on home video with as little
fanfare as possible.
   Fearful of encouraging more demonstrations and boycotts, MCA Home
Video distributed ``The Last Temptation'' without store displays,
promotional posters or advertising. Some stores refused to carry the
film.
   ``We were conscious of provoking a new controversy, which was
clearly not in anybody's interest,'' said Robert Blattner, president
of MCA Home Video, a company affiliated with ``Last Temptation''
producer Universal Pictures.
   ``On the other hand, we're not willing to keep it on the shelf.
We think it's important that this title be made available in the
marketplace.''
   Many fundamentalist Christian organizations attacked ``The Last
Temptation'' before its debut in theaters last August. Most objected
to director Martin Scorsese's depiction of Jesus, played by Willem
Dafoe, as a doubting messiah with human frailties and sexual
fantasies.
   A secretary for the Rev. Donald Wildmon, a fundamentalist who led
those attacks, said Wednesday that Wildmon planned no protests
against the videocassette debut, as he had threatened to do last
year.
   Blockbuster Video, the nation's largest video-store chain with
343 company-owned outlets, has refused to carry ``The Last
Temptation'' video, which has a suggested retail price of $89.95.
   ``It's certainly unusual, but it was a corporate decision
considering all that went on with the film,'' said Wally Knief, a
spokesman for the Fort Lauderdale-based chain. It is the chain's
first such action against a major studio release, Knief said.
   Nearly 80 percent of Blockbuster's 387 franchise locations also
have indicated they won't carry the video, Knief said.
   Numerous independent stores also will not carry the film. John
Clark, owner of The Video Center in Gilroy, Calif., said that
although the store carries X-rated videos that could be considered
controversial, he would not bring in ``The Last Temptation.''
   ``I just don't need the potential of the community being upset,''
Clark said.
   He said he has a separate room for the sexually explicit movies
and that he was not willing to build another room just for ``The
Last Temptation.''
   Employees of national video retailer Music Plus, which will carry
``The Last Temptation,'' have been instructed to tell patrons that
the chain does not censor its product line because that would not
serve customer needs.
   In New York this morning, clerks at RKO Warner Theater Video and
Tower Video outlets said ``The Last Temptation'' was available for
rental today.
   Although several major theater chains declined to show ``The Last
Temptation,'' it has grossed $8.2 million to date, according to
Exhibitor Relations Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
