<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia     06-29 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trains Stoned in Ethnic Unrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two trains carrying Serbs from a
nationalist rally in an ethnically troubled province were stoned,
allegedly by ethnic Albanians, Tanjug state news agency reported
today.
   It said two passengers suffered ``severe cuts'' and several
windows were broken when the trains were hit ``by a hail of stones''
Wednesday night as they traveled from the city of Pristina, in
Kosovo, toward mainland Serbia.
   Kosovo is a province within the republic of Serbia.
   The attackers were not caught but are believed to be ethnic
Albanian nationalists, Tanjug said.
   Almost a million Serbs gathered in Kosovo on Wednesday to mark
the 600th anniversary of a legendary battle in which the Ottomon
Turks defeat the Serbs. The defeat started a centuries-long struggle
to keep the Serbian Orthodox Christian faith alive under Islam.
   The majority of people living in Kosovo are Moslem ethnic
Albanians. Serbs are trying to gain more control over the province,
saying it is necessary to prevent harassment by the ethnic Albanians.
   The Serbian campaign has led to ethnic clashes. In March, at
least 25 people were killed in clashes with security forces.
</TEXT>
