<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru a0502 06-29 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0502,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Declines, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with today's trading. Also moved on financial
wire.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar sagged in European trading today
after West Germany, followed by several other countries, announced
higher interest rates.
   The Bundesbank, West Germany's central bank, raised its discount
rate half a percentage point to 5 percent and its Lombard rate by
half a point to 7 percent; both rates are at their highest levels
since the early 1980s. The Lombard is the rate at which the
Bundesbank lends short-term funds using securities as collateral.
   The Swiss National Bank followed by raising its discount rate to
5.5 percent from 4.5 percent, while France added half a point to its
rates, boosting the money market intervention rate to 8.75 percent.
   Austria and the Netherlands also announced interest rate hikes.
   Following the announcements, the dollar dropped to 1.9545 West
German marks, down from 1.9630 late Wednesday. The dollar fell to
1.6715 Swiss francs compared to 1.6870 late Wednesday, and to 6.6060
French francs from 6.6645 late Wednesday.
   The British pound regained ground lost earlier in the session,
moving to $1.5615, compared with $1.5613 late Wednesday.
   In earlier trading in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 142.90 yen,
down from 143.55 on Wednesday. Later in London, the dollar traded at
142.70 yen.
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday's
prices, included: 2.2045 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2125; 1,420.70
Italian lire, up from 1,421.50; and 1.1955 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1950.
   Gold opened in London at $374.95, down from $375.25 late
Wednesday. At mid-morning, the city's five major bullion dealers
fixed a recommended price of $376.30.
   Gold traded in Zurich at $375.90 this morning compared to
Wednesday's late price of $373.75.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $376.89, up $2.80 from
Wednesday's close.
   Silver bullion traded in London at $5.30 a troy ounce, unchanged
from late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
