<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Cookware     06-29 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Cookware,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Limits Free-Speech Protections When Commercial Expression Involved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today placed new limits on
the Constitution's free-speech protections when commercial
expression is involved.
   By a 6-3 vote in a case involving the sale of cookware on State
University of New York campuses, the court said government officials
are not required to adopt the ``least restrictive'' regulations
possible to limit commercial speech.
   Instead, Justice Antonin Scalia said for the court, officials
need only adopt ``reasonable'' _ not ``perfect'' _ rules for
limiting the commercial activity.
   ``Within those bounds we leave it to government decision makers
to judge what manner of regulation may best be employed,'' he said.
   The ``least-restrictive'' test rejected by the court today still
applies to non-commercial speech _ such as political expression.
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice Harry A. Blackmun said the court
was turning its back on important court precedents.
   ``The majority holds that `least-restrictive means' analysis does
not apply to commercial speech cases, a holding it is able to reach
only by recasting a good bit of contrary language in our past
cases,'' Blackmun said.
   He was joined by Justices William J. Brennan and Thurgood
Marshall.
   Scalia said today's ruling is in line with a 1986 ruling that
upheld Puerto Rico's ban on promotional advertising of casino
gambling aimed at Puerto Rican residents.
   In today's case, the justices ordered further lower court
hearings to determine whether a New York state university ban on
commercial activities violates the Constitution because it is too
broad. The court did not answer that question today.
   But the dissenters said the ban does go too far. They said, for
example, it could prevent a student from meeting his doctor or
lawyer in his dorm room if the doctor or lawyer is paid for the
visit.
   It could even prevent a student from paying a music teacher or a
speech therapist to come to the dorm room for tutoring, Blackmun
said.
   Today's case has attracted widespread interest among educators.
   The State University of New York (SUNY) appealed to the court to
revive the university's ban on commercial activities in the dorm _
an appeal supported by university officials in 10 states and groups
representing thousands of college administraors nationwide.
   The SUNY board of trustees adopted a rule in 1966 to prohibit
most commercial enterprises from operating on state university
campuses.
   The ban was challenged by American Future Systems Inc., a
housewares company in Bryn Mawr, Pa., after one of its
representatives was arrested in 1982 at the state university campus
in Cortland, N.Y., for refusing to leave a dormitory.
   The housewares company attracts customers by offering free
Florida vacations to students who arrange sales demonstrations in
their dormitory rooms for groups of their friends.
   A federal judge upheld the SUNY ban. But the 2nd U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals overturned the judge's ruling last year.
   The appeals court ordered further hearings to determine whether
there may be less restrictive rules to accomplish the university's
purpose.
   In a friend-of-the-court legal brief, officials from 10 states
said, ``The fundamental right of state colleges and universities to
control the use of their premises is at issue.''
   The officials are from state universities in California,
Connecticut, Florida, Michigan, Illinois, Ohio, South Carolina,
Rhode Island, New Jersey and Vermont.
   Other groups that supported the SUNY appeal were the American
Council on Education, the American Association of State Colleges and
Universities, the National Association of State Universities and
Land Grant Colleges and the National Association of Student
Personnel Administrators.
   The case is State University of New York vs. Fox, 87-2013.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890629-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Indians     06-29 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Indians,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Limits Indian Tribes' Power to Control Land Use</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today limited the power of
Indian tribes to control, through tribal zoning laws, the use of
land owned by non-Indians within a reservation's boundaries.
   In a case of significance to any state in which an Indian
reservation is located, the court said tribes may be forced to share
the zoning power with state or county officials.
   The justices, in splintered voting that yielded no one majority
opinion, ruled that the Confederated Tribes and Bands of the Yakima
Indian Nation has the authority to regulate _ and may zone _ ``fee''
or privately owned land on about 800,000 acres of its reservation in
Washington state.
   But the court said the tribe has no such power to regulate land
parcels owned by non-Indians on some 500,000 acres of the
reservation.
   The Yakima reservation encompasses 1.3 million acres of land,
most of it within Yakima County. About 5,000 tribal members and
about 20,000 non-members live on the reservation.
   About 800,000 acres, including some 740,000 in Yakima County,
fall within the reservation's ``closed area'' in which the tribe's
zoning ordinance allows no permanent structures.
   Philip Brendale, who owns 160 acres of land within the closed
area, was barred by the tribal ordinance from selling his land for
residential development.
   Stanley Wilkinson, who owns about 100 acres just within the
reservation's northern boundary in the reservation's ``open area,''
was barred from subdividing a portion of his land.
   Neither man is a member of the Yakima tribe. They, along with
Yakima County officials, contended that the tribe lacks the legal
authority to control the use of their land.
   Today, the Supreme Court ruled against Brendale but for Wilkinson
_ drawing a distinction between the ``closed area'' and ``open
area'' lands.
   The closed area is one in which only a very small percentage of
land is held in fee _ by private owners and not the tribe. About
half the land in the open area is privately owned.
   Almost all of the reservation's residents live in the open area.
   The controlling opinion in today's decision was written by
Justice John Paul Stevens, who was joined by Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor.
   He said the difference between the closed and open areas ``is of
critical importance and requires a different disposition'' of the
appeals filed by Brendale and Wilkinson.
   Four court members _ Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Byron R. White, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy _
would have disallowed tribal regulation of private land throughout
the reservation.
   Justices Harry A. Blackmun, William J. Brennan and Thurgood
Marshall voted to allow tribal regulation of privately owned land
throughout the reservation.
   Thus, the vote allowing the tribe to regulate private land in the
reservation's closed area was 5-4. The vote barring the tribe from
regulating private land owned by non-Indians in the open area was
6-3.
   Writing for himself, Brennan and Marshall, Blackmun said,
``Splitting tribal authority over non-Indian fee lands between the
so-called open and closed areas ... is Solomonic in appearance
only.''
   He added, ``Our past decisions and common sense compel a finding
that the tribe has zoning authority over all lands within its
reservation.''
   The efforts to limit tribal control of land use were supported in
friend-of-the-court briefs submitted by the National Association of
Counties, the National League of Cities, the National Governors'
Association and 11 states.
   They are Washington, Arizona, Idaho, Michigan, Montana, Nevada,
New Mexico, North Dakota, South Dakota, Utah and Wyoming.
   Numerous Indian tribes filed friend-of-the-court briefs
supporting the Yakimas.
   The cases are Brendale vs. Confederated Tribes, 87-1622;
Wilkinson vs. Confederated Tribes, 87-1697; and Yakima County vs.
Confederated Tribes, 87-1711.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
