<FIRST>r a PM-FamilySlayings     06-29 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Slayings,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspect in 1971 Slayings Waives Extradition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An accountant arrested on a TV viewer's tip
June 1 in the slayings of five family members 18 years ago waived
extradition today and left jail for New Jersey.
   Robert P. Clark, who authorities said is actually John E. List,
was escorted by New Jersey sheriff's deputies.
   ``He's gone and we're happy,'' said State Police Major M.H. Bruce.
   Clark was arrested June 1 at the Richmond accounting firm where
he had worked for a year and a half. FBI agents had been tipped off
by a viewer of the program ``America's Most Wanted,'' which 11 days
earlier ran a segment on List.
   The program showed an artist's bust depicting how the
straitlaced, churchgoing List might look today.
   Authorities said List, 63, murdered his mother, wife and three
children in 1971 in Westfield, N.J., then vanished, taking on a new
identity.
   Clark has not admitted he is List, but authorities have
identified him by fingerprints and physical markings. He signed the
extradition papers today as Clark, authorities said.
   Investigators said List had fled to Colorado, then Virginia, and
had built a new life without changing his appearance or profession.
</TEXT>
