<FIRST>u a PM-TrialRe-creation 1stLd-Writethru a0553 06-29 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trial Re-creation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0553,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Newspaper Can Question Trial Participants</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to ADD comments on whether re-creation is
unprecedented; PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `Experts couldn't ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ruled that The Boston Globe may
question participants in a police officer's drug trial under oath
because a court clerk erased the tape recording of the case.
   U.S. District Judge Joseph L. Tauro's ruling Wednesday allows the
newspaper's lawyers to subpoena and take depositions from
participants in the 1987 cocaine possession trial in state court,
the Globe said today.
   Experts couldn't say whether such a re-creation had been allowed
before, but David Sellers, spokesman for the Administrative Office
of U.S. Courts in Washington, said, ``It's certainly something that
sounds highly unusual.''
   The Globe has said its aim is to check out a tip that Salvador
Aponte, who no longer is on the police force, had been found guilty,
but then was acquitted after a defense lawyer told the judge the
officer would be fired if convicted.
   The newspaper sued in federal court 18 months ago to get the tape.
   Last year, Tauro ruled that a law sealing from the public court
records in criminal cases that did not end in convictions was
unconstitutional.
   But the clerk's office later found that the tape recording of the
trial had been erased, James Mannering, assistant clerk, told The
Associated Press today.
   Lawyers for the Globe reported to Tauro that court clerks said
they ran short of tapes and erased the Aponte trial despite a
February 1988 order to keep tapes for at least 2{ years. The
newspaper said the attorney general's office did not tell anyone in
the clerk's office that the Aponte trial was the subject of a
federal lawsuit and had to be preserved.
</TEXT>
