<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-Yeltsin     06-29 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Yeltsin,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Says Poverty Will Spark Soviet Revolution In Two Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet legislator Boris N. Yeltsin said
in an interview shown today that poor living standards will lead to
a revolution in the Soviet Union within two years.
   ``Forty-eight million people live under the poverty line, which
means that we are on the brim of a precipice,'' the maverick
Communist told Hungarian state television in an interview Wednesday
night. The official MTI news agency carried excerpts from the
interview today.
   ``I think patience won't last longer than one or two more years.
That's the maximum. And then the people will take their destiny into
their own hands. The revolution from above will turn into a
grass-roots, spontaneous revolution,'' said Yeltsin, who last month
was named to the new Supreme Soviet.
   He said perestroika, Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's program
to reform the economy, ``should not have been introduced in so many
fields.''
   ``We should carry out a political reform, this should be the
starting point. Then the scope of perestroika should be narrowed,''
Yeltsin said.
   ``We should postpone the space program, cut defense expenditure
and slash industrial investment costs by 30 percent,'' he said
without elaborating.
   ``If we had done this from the beginning, we could have raised
the living standards of the people over the last four years.''
   Yeltsin was dismissed as Communist Party chief for Moscow in 1987
after he said Gorbachev's changes were not proceeding fast enough.
   When he won a congress seat, he achieved one of the most stunning
political comebacks in Soviet history. He won the seat only after
another legislator stepped down and gave his spot to Yeltsin.
</TEXT>
