<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-CourtScene     06-29 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Court Scene,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anticipation Becomes Letdown Outside Supreme Court Building</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Scotus-Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The scene was set, the demonstrators in place,
the banners unfurled, but no drama occurred on the sun-splashed
plaza outside the U.S. Supreme Court building today.
   The court's long-awaited decision on abortion was postponed once
again, perhaps until Monday, perhaps later.
   The effect was like air escaping from a well-filled balloon.
   ``What a letdown,'' said a young Capitol Hill intern who said she
had waited in line for a seat in the courtroom since 4 a.m.
   Disappointed spectators streamed out of the court shortly after
10 a.m., filing down the marble steps toward the hundred
demonstrators gathered on the broad sidewalk.
   They were almost equally divided between the forces opposing
abortion and those advocating a woman's right to choose.
   On the left were yellow banners with black letters: ``The Child
Killing Must Be Stopped.''
   On the right were purple banners with white letters: ``Keep
Abortion Legal.''
   In between were the large color photographs of bleeding fetuses
that have been seen at anti-abortion demonstrations across the
country.
   In the center, a kneeling, bearded man in the robes of a monk
said his rosary while frowning at pro-choice placards three feet
away.
   Earlier, a line of hundreds of people had snaked around the court
in hopes of a seat inside.
   At its head was Michael Carrier, who identified himself as a
student at Yale University.
   ``I've been here since 6:30 last night,'' he said. ``I've been
sleeping on concrete. I've been not sleeping on concrete.''
   ``I'm here because I feel this is such an important decision,''
Carrier said. ``I just had to be here when it came down.''
   He was not the only person to have spent the night at the court.
Not the only one to be disappointed.
   A woman who was No. 5 in the line had been there since 9:30 p.m.
Wednesday night.
   ``We spent most of the night talking, speculating on what would
happen,'' said another woman. ``You get pretty chummy in a situation
like that.''
   Nearby, other signs. A small girl holds a placard larger than she
is: ``My Mother Chose Life.''
   Another girl holds a sign reading, ``Why Do My Future Playmates
Have to Die.''
   But there was no decision.
   And the commentators, poised to comment, commented anyway.
   The old and emotional arguments, for and against. The speculation
on what the postponement meant.
   But one central figure had nothing to add.
   Frank Sussman, the attorney who argued the case before the court
for pro-choice advocates, was asked to comment.
   He threw up his hands.
   ``There's nothing new,'' he said. ``Nothing happened.''
   ``We've got a paper to put out,'' a reporter shouted.
   ``I've got a paper to read,'' Sussman replied. ``I'll read
another part.''
   Then, referring to the manager of the Cincinnati Reds baseball
team under investigation for gambling, Sussman added:
   ``Go talk to Pete Rose.''
</TEXT>
