<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Havel     06-29 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Havel,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czech Police Warn Havel He Can Be Jailed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vaclav Havel, the banned playwright who
has become a symbol of dissent in Czechoslovakia, has been warned by
the secret police that he can be jailed again, his brother said
today.
   ``They did not give an explanation for their warning,'' Ivan
Havel said in a telephone interview from Prague.
   Havel, who was freed on probation May 17 midway through an
eight-month jail sentence that drew protest at home and abroad, was
summoned Tuesday to police headquarters in Trutnov. It is 75 miles
northeast of Prague and near Hradecek village where the playwright
was staying.
   Two security officials from Prague met Havel and warned him his
activities could be qualified as incitement to rebellion, Ivan Havel
said. They said the playwright could go back to jail, he said.
   The police did not elaborate on their charges and Havel was
allowed to return to his summer retreat, his brother said.
   Hungarian television Wednesday night broadcast an interview with
Havel in which he criticized the Czechoslovak leadership's
reluctance to embrace reform.
   Havel's interview likely was watched by many of the more than
500,000 ethnic Hungarians living in the Czech border province of
Slovakia.
   Havel was sentenced to eight months in jail for incitement
connected to anti-government protests marking the anniversary of the
suicide of Jan Palach, a Czech student who burned himself to death
in January 1969 to protest the crushing of reforms after the 1968
Soviet-led invasion.
   After being freed for good behavior, Havel spoke out for
political reform and urged those who campaigned for his release not
to forget other political prisoners.
   He noted that Czechoslovak leaders, while adopting the language
of reform, had yet to emulate what he called astonishing changes in
Hungary, Poland and Moscow.
   ``I don't see anything threatening in the Hungarian
developments,'' Havel reportedly told Budapest television. ``Of
course, everything that is happening in Hungary, Poland and the
Soviet Union is a threat to our ruling clique.''
   The Czechoslovak leadership already has expressed concern over
fast-moving political and economic reforms in Hungary, which plans
democratic elections next year.
   ``Eventually (Soviet leader Mikhail S.) Gorbachev will have to
deal with the 1968 invasion ... He knows that as soon as they
(Soviets) review their 1968 move, it will leave this (Prague)
leadership no option but to depart from the scene,'' Havel
reportedly told Hungarian television.
</TEXT>
