<FIRST>r i AM-Lefebvre     06-29 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lefebvre,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Archbishop Attends Ordination of Eight New Priests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ECONE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebel archbishop Marcel Lefebvre
attended the ordinations of eight new traditionalist priests
Thursday, one year after he was excommunicated from the Roman
Catholic church.
   The ceremony was conducted by Bernard Tissier de Mallerais, one
of the four new bishops Lefebvre consecrated in 1988 in defiance of
papal orders, creating what the Vatican said was a historic split in
the church.
   The ordinations raised to 222 the number of traditionalist
priests in Lefebvre's St. Pius X Fraternity, according to the Rev.
Franz Schmidberger, the German priest who succeeded the archbishop
in 1984 as the fraternity's Superior General.
   He said 16 priests and 19 seminarians have left the movement
since Pope John Paul II took the action against Lefebvre and warned
his followers they also would be excommunicated unless they break
with him.
   In the same period, 34 new priests were ordained by the four new
bishops, Schmidberger said. Attendance at the Fraternity's six
theological schools in Switzerland, Australia, the United States,
France and West Germany totals more than 250, he added.
   Despite his ranking as titular head of the Fraternity,
Schmidberger was not consecrated last year and thus escaped
automatic excommunication.
   Lefebvre, 83, watched Thursday's ceremonies from a chair near the
altar in a tent set up on a meadow below the first traditionalist
seminary, opened 19 years ago.
   The Mass was celebrated in the Latin, 16th century rite that was
replaced by the Mass in vernacular under the 1962-65 Vatican Council
reforms, chief target of traditionalist criticism.
</TEXT>
