<FIRST>u w PM-HUDRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0438 06-29 0984</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0438,930</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Met With Former Housing Official's Attorneys</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOPS with 13 grafs to update with Bush testimony and postponement
of Cushing appearance; edits thruout to conform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a congressional panel investigating
abuse and mismanagement in a federal low-income housing program
today allowed one witness scheduled to appear before them to
postpone his testimony while another witness sought to clarify
previous statements he had made.
   Hunter Cushing, former deputy assistant secretary for
multi-family housing at the Department of Housing and Urban
Development, asked congressional investigators to give him more time
to review documents and prepare to answer their questions.
   ``I've only recently been retained and not had adequate
opportunity to review the facts in this case,'' said Jamie Gorelick,
an attorney who accompanied the former HUD official.
   Gorelick said Cushing, a deputy assistant secretary at the
Commerce Department, would appear voluntarily before the House
subcommittee on employment and housing after Congress' July 4th
recess.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., the subcommittee chairman, excused
Cushing and said he would be recalled.
   The subcommittee's hearings resumed today with a second
appearance by Fred Bush, a 1988 fund-raiser for George Bush's
presidential effort who sought ``to make a few clarifying statements
of my earlier testimony.'' Bush, who is not related to the
president, previously testified on May 25.
   Bush earned $268,000 as a consultant on a project in Puerto Rico
funded under the HUD's moderate rehabilitation program and $253,000
on a technical assistance grant to another project on the island.
   Bush, the ambassador-designate to Luxembourg, originally told the
subcommittee he contacted Deborah Gore Dean, former executive
assistant to then-HUD Secretary Samuel, after finding her name in a
federal executive telephone directory.
   Bush said today, however, that one of his former colleagues at
Bush &amp; Co. reminded him they had contacted Ms. Dean after Cushing
and the colleague spoke at a social gathering.
   ``They have told me of their best recollection. Sometime in late
1984 or early 1985 one of my colleagues met Hunter Cushing at a
social gathering and learned that he worked at HUD,'' said Bush.
   ``My colleague's recollection is that Mr. Cushing taold him we
should talk to Deborah Gore Dean,'' he said, adding that the
colleague asked Bush if he knew Ms. Dean.
   Bush said he didn't and it was then that he consulted the
directory ``to see who Ms. Dean was.''
   Members of the panel have met with lawyers for Dean, who won't
testify about influence-peddling for federal money, but neither side
will say whether they are working on a deal.
   Dean, the former official at the center of the dispute, said she
spent Wednesday sifting through a box of documents from her tenure
at the HUD.
   That was about all she would say.
   ``Please don't do this to me,'' Dean said during a brief
telephone conversation. ``I'm very bad at hanging up on people. I
think it's rude, and I always get stuck.''
   One of Ms. Dean's attorneys, Charles Leeper, acknowledged the
meeting with congressional investigators.
   ``Our client has asserted the Fifth Amendment privilege, and
we're not under any obligation, as things stand now, to appear again
before the subcommittee, but we're continuing discussions with
them,'' Leeper said.
   Meanwhile, an auditor's report released Wednesday showed that HUD
gave millions of dollars to private apartment projects around the
country in 1987 and 1988 although they did not qualify under the
agency's own guidelines.
   The funds came from a HUD discretionary fund intended to help
financially ailing projects which were insured by the Federal
Housing Administration, said the report released by Rep. Bill Green,
R-N.Y.
   Green said the audit of awards to 25 projects indicated that $30
million of $35 million granted ``went to undeserving or low-need
projects.''
   Ms. Dean, who appeared before the subcommittee last month, has
invoked her constitutional right against self-incrimination in
refusing to testify about her role in awarding HUD money.
   The panel is investigating allegations that millions of dollars
were steered to developers who were either former HUD employees or
hired top Republicans, such as former Interior Secretary James Watt,
who sold their services as consultants for six-figure fees.
   The New York Times reported today that one prominent Republican
who received a consulting fee to help a project win federal housing
funds was Fred Brown, a New York businessman and chairman of the
National Black Republican Council.
   A 1987 audit by HUD investigators questioned Brown's $50,000 fee
for consulting work on behalf of New Haven, Conn., in its successful
bid for a $10 million federal Urban Development Action Grant.
   Asked if he has discussed a deal with Ms. Dean's attorneys under
which she could be granted immunity for her testimony before the
panelLantos replied: ``I can confirm that I have met with them, but
I am not at liberty to discuss what they talked to me about and what
I talked to them about.''
   A parade of witnesses identified Ms. Dean as the HUD official
whose support was crucial in getting scarce housing funds from the
department. Ms. Dean was executive assistant to Housing Secretary
Samuel Pierce Jr.
   After more than a month of hearings, Rep. Christopher Shays,
R-Conn., said in an interview Wednesday that some contradictions
have emerged, but he refused to specify what they were or who made
them.
   ``I think there are some persons who are dangerously close to
perjuring themselves,'' Shays said. ``We have some conflicting
testimony.''
   Shays, a member of the Government Operations subcommittee, has
been outspoken in his criticism of the management of HUD during the
eight years of the Reagan administration.
   He said some of the conflicts among witnesses also may be due to
poor memory or misunderstanding the questions.
   But Lantos, while not disagreeing with Shays, said he will wait
until the hearings are nearly over before saying whether any of the
witnesses have lied.
</TEXT>
