<DOCNO> AP890629-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1252EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PigWater     06-29 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pig Water,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Reservoir Is Bathtub For Pigs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city-owned watershed is teeming with wild
pigs, which splash around in city drinking water, root up the land
and may create a health threat.
   ``They reproduce like crazy, and there are no predators to get
rid of them,'' said Arthur Jenson, Water Department deputy manager.
   The department hopes to trap and sell the animals as pork. The
animals are descendants of farm animals that either escaped or were
abandoned.
   City water managers fear the feral swine could spread livestock
diseases such as cholera and hoof-and-mouth. They are also concerned
the pigs' rooting up the ground on hillsides in search of food may
promote erosion of the watershed area.
   Jenson said about 250 pigs are roaming San Francisco's
37,000-acre watershed containing the Calaveras and San Antonio
reservoirs near the dividing line of Alameda and Santa Clara
counties.
   The city' Public Utilities Commission on Tuesday unanimously
approved the Water Department's plan to conduct a ``swine damage
survey,'' to determine the pig population and study ways to
eliminate, or at least control, the animals.
   But because the state Fish and Game Department lists feral swine
as a game species, the city will need a permit to kill the pigs.
   And under state law, the pigs cannot be killed and disposed of or
sold as dog food, but must be sold for human consumption or given to
a soup kitchen or shelter. ``We are trying to avoid wanton waste,''
said Jim Swanson of the state Department of Fish and Game.
   As a result, the U.S. Department of Agriculture must inspect and
certify the meat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
