<FIRST>u i PM-Cuba-Minister 1stLd-Writethru   06-29 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuba-Minister, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0568,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuba Replaces Interior Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS 2 grafs of background at end on new interior minister.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Cuba-Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba replaced its interior minister today and
said the new minister will conduct ``a deep analysis'' into how
officials became involved in drug trafficking, the Cuban news agency
Prensa Latina said.
   A brief communique from the Communist Party's political bureau
signed by President Fidel Castro said Gen. Abelardo Colome Ibarra
had been appointed to replace Gen. Jose Abrantes, according to the
agency, monitored in Mexico City.
   The change was made ``considering the great deficiency which
occurred in the main office of the interior ministry in relation to
the conduct of a group of officials who for 2{ years, with impunity
and without being discovered, conducted drug trafficking
operations,'' Prensa Latina quoted the statement as saying.
   Cuba said it arrested nine military officers this month in
connection with drug trafficking. A military tribunal has
recommended a court-martial for one of them, Maj. Gen. Arnaldo
Ochoa, and said he should be executed by a firing squad if convicted.
   The communique said the new minister should ``adopt all measures
that make repetition of the deficiency impossible,'' Prensa Latina
said.
   U.S. officials have questioned the sincerity of Cuba's new war on
drugs, partly because of continued reports of smuggling through Cuba.
   Colome Ibarra, born in 1939, is the third highest military
officer in Cuba after Castro and his brother, Defense Minister Gen.
Raul Castro, Prensa Latina said. Since Dec. 31, 1988, he has been
the only three-star general in the armed forces and holds the
highest military honors the country awards, including the title Hero
of the Revolution, it said.
   He has been a member of the Communist Party's Central Committee
since 1965 and a member of the politburo since 1980, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
