<FIRST>r a PM-StutteringSuit     06-29 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stuttering Suit,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ad Exec Charges In $7.5 Million Suit That He Was Fired For Stuttering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An advertising executive is suing his former
agency for $7.5 million, claiming he was fired because he stutters.
   In the suit filed Wednesday, David C. Lehmkuhl, 42, said he was
dismissed by Ammirati Puris Inc. following four months in the
$125,000-a-year job after being told by the president, ``We can't
have you getting any closer to the clients.''
   Lehmkuhl is seeking $5 million in compensatory damages and $2.5
million in punitive damages.
   The company's president, Edward Vick, said Lehmkuhl, who was
senior vice president and director of media services, was fired
``for not performing.'' He would not comment on Lehmkuhl's
stuttering.
   ``The whole case is so far off base and so without merit, there
is almost no point in getting into a discussion of the specifics,''
Vick said.
   Lehmkuhl's attorney, Barry R. Fischer, said his client, because
of his stutter, often had subordinates make presentations.
   ``But there was no evidence that it held him back in any way,''
Fischer said. ``His career speaks for itself, that he has come a
tremendous way despite his disability.''
   In a 1987 issue of Marketing &amp; Media Decisions, a media trade
journal, Lehmkuhl was described as one of the ad industry's ``most
influential authorities on print media.''
   He worked for 18 years at another agency, N W Ayer Inc., rising
to senior vice president, before being recruited by Vick, who knew
he stuttered, the suit said.
   The suit said that just after Lehmkuhl began at Ammirati Puris,
new-job jitters made his stutter worse. Lehmkuhl signed up for
speech-therapy classes and a public-speaking course, but on March
15, he was fired, the suit said.
   Fischer said his client is now a self-employed consultant making
a fraction of what he used to earn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
