<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1326EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru   06-29 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0583,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians, Christians Clash Despite Truce Call, 6 Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 6 grafs to update casualties; Pickup 7th graf, `A
hospital...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shells exploded in Beirut's Moslem and
Christian sectors today as Syrian and Christian gunners fought
despite a call by Arab leaders for a truce. Six people were killed
and 26 wounded, police said.
   The whooshing sound of outgoing rockets and the thuds of
exploding shells rocked the city. Smoke and dust billowed from
several targeted areas.
   By police count, 380 people have been killed and 1,497 wounded
since March 8, when the current round of violence broke out pitting
Christian Army Cmdr. Gen. Michel Aoun's troops against Syrian and
allied militia forces.
   A police spokesman said today's fatalities included two civilians
killed in Moslem west Beirut when a shell crashed on their car. The
two were driving on a seaside boulevard where the Syrians have
several artillery batteries firing on Christian districts.
   A civilian also was killed at west Beirut's Barbir hospital, near
the capital's dividing Green Line, when the facility took several
direct rounds from Christian gunners, said the spokesman who could
not be named in line with standing regulations.
   He said the three other civilians were killed in Christian east
Beirut.
   A hospital official, speaking on condition he not be named, said
the man killed at the hospital had taken refuge there after shelling
started while he was in the street.
   Syrian artillery batteries also shelled the Christian coastline
north of the city to maintain a blockade of the enclave, home to
about 1 million Christians.
   Christian radio stations interrupted their programs to flash
reports of the renewed Syrian shelling and urge the population to
take the needed precautions.
   ``This is the way the Syrians responded to the cease-fire called
by the tripartite Arab committee,'' the Voice of Lebanon radio said.
   The truce was requested Tuesday by King Hassan II of Morocco,
King Fahd of Saudi Arabia and President Chadli Bendjedid of Algeria.
   The three leaders, concluding talks in Oran, Algeria, also called
for lifting the siege of the Christian enclave. It invited Lebanon's
Parliament to meet outside the country to forge a settlement to the
14-year-old civil war.
   An Arab League leaders' summit in Morocco last month asked the
three heads of state to find a settlement to the civil war by
November.
   Christian and Moslem leaders have welcomed the call by the three
Arab leaders for an end to ``violence in all its forms,'' but
differed on whether Lebanon's Parliament should meet overseas.
   Christian parliament members in general have opposed meeting
outside Lebanon, saying if the siege were lifted and crossing
gateways re-opened there would be no need to travel.
   Shafiq Badr was the only Christian deputy who expressed readiness
Wednesday to ``go anywhere to discuss an end to the war.''
   The independent daily paper An-Nahar said Aoun, a Maronite,
expressed reservations over parliament's meeting abroad because it
``contradicts Lebanon's sovereignty.''
   ``However, it is up to the deputies to decide,'' the paper quoted
the 54-year-old general as saying.
   Syria's 40,000 troops in Lebanon besieged the Christian enclave
early in March to retaliate for a blockade imposed by Aoun against
illegal ports run by Syrian-backed militias south of Beirut.
   Aoun and other Christian leaders accuse the Syrians of failing to
achieve a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the 22-nation Arab League
by siding with the Moslems against the Christians in the Lebanese
civil war.
   Pro-Syrian Moslem and leftist factions say Syrian troops should
remain in Lebanon until the Christians agree to reform the 45-year
political system in a way that guarantees equal shares to the
various sects in running the nation's affairs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
