<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1400EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Baker-China 1stLd-Writethru a0603 06-29 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker-China, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0603,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Says Policy Can't Be Guided Only by Human Rights Concerns</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with House action, inserting 2 grafs after 5th graf,
Therefore</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III,
disapproving of moves in Congress for further sanctions against
China, said Thursday that U.S. foreign policy cannot be guided
entirely by human rights considerations.
   He urged Congress to work out a compromise with the White House
that would preserve President Bush's flexibility in framing a U.S.
response to the crackdown on pro-democracy forces and permit the
United States to speak with one voice on the subject.
   Baker said Bush, who headed the U.S. liaison office in Beijing
from 1974 to 1975, knows as much about China as any elected
official. ``We do recognize the desire of elected officials to speak
to this and to vote on this issue,'' Baker said at a White House
news conference.
   ``But we really and firmly believe that the leadership in this
instance must come from the executive branch and it should come from
the president of the United States as commander-in-chief and as one
who is thoroughly and completely versed in the affairs of China.''
   Therefore, Baker said, the Bush administration could not endorse
the package of sanctions being put together on Capitol Hill to
register congressional concern over a wave of arrests and executions
and to try to moderate the Chinese leadership.
   Within hours of his comments, the House voted 418-0 for the
package, which endorses previous Bush moves but would add suspension
of trade and development programs, a ban on the sale of police
equipment and a limit on transfer of high-technology and nuclear
materials or components.
   The House provision is part of a foreign aid bill that has not
yet been debated in the Senate.
   Even though Bush and Baker have expressed outrage over
developments in China, including the attack by the military on
students in Tiananmen Square June 3-4, several members of Congress
have exhorted them to take stronger action and make more damning
statements.
   But Baker said ``we will not use inflammatory rhetoric.''
   He said U.S.-Chinese relations served a variety of purposes and
should not be jettisoned as a response to the crackdown.
   ``The principle of human rights has to be a major foundation
principle for our foreign policy,'' Baker said. ``It has been, it
continues to be, and in my view it will continue to be well into the
future. That is a very, very important principle.''
   But, he said, ``it is not the only principle which determines our
foreign policy. And it is not, and cannot be, the sole and only
principle which determines the extent and scope and degree of the
response of the United States in a situation such as this.
   ``When we say the relationship is important, and that we ought to
try and preserve the relationship, we do not suggest that we do so
at all cost. And we are not suggesting that it is important solely
from an economic basis.
   ``It is important economically, yes, but it is important as well
from a geopolitical and geostrategic standpoint.''
   Baker did not elaborate on the point. But U.S. relations with the
Communist government in Beijing, built up over the last two dozen
years, has sometimes been used as leverage in dealing with the
Soviet Union.
   The sanctions imposed by Bush suspended military sales to China
and prohibited visits by senior U.S. military and civilian officials.
   The congressional package, an amendment to a two-year $23 billion
foreign aid bill, would put these executive actions into law,
suspend trade and development programs, ban the sale of
police-related weapons and limit transfer of high technology and
nuclear materials or components.
   The amendment also included some harsh rhetoric condemning the
``unprovoked, brutal and indiscriminate assault'' on peaceful
demonstrators that left at least 700 dead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
