<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1406EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-DefenseBudget 1stLd-Writethru a0459 06-29 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defense Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Restores Funds for Osprey and Tomcat Fighter</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: TOP 9 grafs new with Cheney comment; picks up 5th graf pvs,
The bill.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said today he was
``generally pleased'' with the House Armed Services Committee's
action on the defense budget, but he questioned Congress' desire to
cut spending without canceling weapons systems.
   The House panel on Wednesday restored funds for the Marine Corps
V-22 Osprey aircraft and F-14D Tomcat fighter _ two programs Cheney
wants to eliminate. Against the advice of its chairman, the
Democratic-controlled committee rejected an amendment to accept
Cheney's $64 billion procurement budget without additions or
deletions.
   Cheney, in a statement released at the Pentagon, said he was
``generally pleased'' with the committee's decision. But he added:
``The problem is, that while Congress wants to cut defense spending,
some don't want to cancel any systems or close any bases.''
   ``We must not preserve the fiction that we can keep all the
weapons and bases everyone wants and still spend less money,'' he
said.
   Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams said Cheney ``clearly wished''
the Armed Services Committee had accepted the budget proposal
without change ``but understands that's the way the process works.''
   Republicans on the panel warned that restoring funds for the V-22
and F-14D by amending Cheney's proposal for the fiscal year starting
Oct. 1 will lead to chaos on the House floor when the legislation is
debated.
   But Democrats who changed the package and also cut funds for the
B-2 stealth bomber said their efforts indicate they won't ``roll
over and play dead.''
   By virtue of a 26-26 tie _ the result of last-minute ``no'' votes
from Reps. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., and Ron Dellums, D-Calif. _
the committee defeated a proposal to accept Cheney's procurement
budget without changes.
   This let the panel approve 44-5 a budget that includes funds for
the Osprey and Tomcat planes.
   The bill goes to the full House. The overall defense budget is
$295 billion.
   Under the individual amendments approved earlier by the panel,
the Bell-Boeing Osprey, which is built in Fort Worth, Texas, would
receive $157 million in fiscal 1990 beginning Oct. 1.
   The Tomcat, manufactured by Grumman Corp., on Long Island, would
get about $1 billion.
   The National Guard and reserves would receive about $1 billion,
half of which had been earmarked for the B-2 bomber while the other
half had been appropriated for spare parts.
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
panel, urged his colleagues to accept Cheney's procurement budget
without revision.
   Rep. Herbert Bateman, R-Va., added that breaking Cheney's plan
``breaks a logjam that will bring total chaos.''
   But others on the panel were not deterred.
   Rep. Marvin Leath, D-Texas, said that after 11 years of hard work
he will not ``roll over and play dead.''
   Dellums introduced an amendment to cancel the B-2 bomber, which
at $500 million to $650 million each is considered the most
expensive plane in history.
   ``It's time to cut ... loose from the monument to misallocated
money,'' Dellums argued. ``We've obligated ourselves to $22 billion
without knowing whether this plane can fly.''
   Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, who backed the amendment, said that
every week the Air Force changes the mission for the radar-evading
plane.
   But Aspin argued that a vote on the B-2 will take place on the
House floor and ``total termination at this point is wrong.''
   Dellums' amendment lost 36-16, but a handful of members responded
``no for now,'' indicating that when the question comes up on the
House floor they may oppose funds for the costly radar-evading plane.
   The panel also rejected Dellums' amendment to delete $164 million
requested by the Pentagon to move 50 MX missiles from silos to
railroad cars.
   The panel did approve language that transferred money from B-2
purchasing to research and development on the stealth bomber. A day
earlier, the panel rejected an amendment to restore $351 million for
the bomber that the research and development subcommittee voted to
spend on the Osprey.
   That vote left $2.7 billion in purchasing funds for the B-2 and
cut the proposed $1.8 billion for research and development to about
$1.5 billion.
   The budget vote came one day after the panel slashed $1.1 billion
from Star Wars, formally known as the Strategic Defense Initiative.
By voice vote, the committee approved a $3.5 billion budget for SDI,
considerably less than the $4.6 billion Bush proposed for the
program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
