<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1422EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Zaire 2ndLd-Writethru a0586 06-29 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Zaire, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0586,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mobuto, Bush Promise Closer Economic Ties</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 10 grafs new to reflect end of meeting; picks up 7th graf
pvs, Mobutu won</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zaire President Mobutu Sese Seko and President
Bush promised closer economic ties between the two nations after two
hours of private talks today at the White House.
   Bush, calling Mobutu ``one of our most valued friends'' in
Africa, said he and the African leader exchanged paperwork for a
treaty to encourage greater U.S. investment there.
   He also said the United States supports Zaire's efforts to win
new loans from the International Monetary Fund and praised its
commitment to reform its economy.
   In a departure ceremony outside the White House, Bush also
praised Mobutu for his role in bringing about the recent cease-fire
in the bordering nation of Angola, where civil war has raged for 14
years.
   Bush said that ``the total withdrawal of Cuban troops from
Angola'' remained a joint U.S.-Zaire goal.
   Mobutu, the first African head-of-state invited by Bush to the
White House, thanked the president for giving U.S. support to
efforts to strengthen his nation's economy.
   Speaking in French, Mobutu also said he told Bush of recent
human-rights improvements in Zaire.
   Mobutu has long supported U.S. policy goals in Africa while
compiling a human rights record widely regarded as one of the worst
on the continent.
   ``Zaire can be ranked among those countries which observe the
rule of law, not to be confused or mistaken with any incidental
mishaps that are attributable to an administration or to
individuals,'' Mobutu said.
   The two leaders made their formal remarks in public at the end of
their two-hour meeting and lunch.
   Mobutu won plaudits from U.S. diplomats last week for the key
role he played in helping arrange the Angolan cease-fire, which was
agreed upon at an 18-nation African summit meeting hosted by Mobutu.
   Mobutu brushed aside questions Wednesday about his human rights
performance, saying he has no reason to repress any Zairean because
``100 percent'' of his subjects support him.
   The United States and Zaire have enjoyed close ties for most of
the 24 years Mobutu has ruled his country. Zaire has received
substantial U.S. assistance over the years while serving as a
transit point for U.S. military supplies destined for anti-communist
rebels in neighboring Angola.
   But concern on Capitol Hill over the rights situation in Zaire is
expected to lead to a cut in the administration's Zaire military aid
request from $9 million to $3 million in fiscal 1990. Mobutu's
schedule today included an afternoon meeting with members of the
House Foreign Affairs Committee.
   Freedom House, a New York-based group which promotes democracy
around the world, ranks Zaire with the worst human rights violators
in Africa.
   The annual State Department human rights report, released in
February, said that among the human rights abuses in Zaire are
torture and other forms of physical mistreatment of detainees.
   State Department deputy spokesman Richard Boucher said Wednesday
that Mobutu recently has taken a number of steps to correct abuses.
He added, however, that ``human rights problems and deficiencies are
part of our ongoing dialogue with Zaire.''
   There also have been allegations about widespread corruption in
Zaire. A State Department document cited in a New York Times article
two years ago estimated Mobutu's wealth at more than $5 billion.
   Among Mobutu's assets are a number of castles and palaces in
Zaire and in Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890629-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1430EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-US     06-29 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-US,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Ambassador of Dirty Words' Takes Up Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Language in 8th graf, ``Among the ...'' may offend some readers.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter Secchia, dubbed the ``ambassador of dirty
words'' by the Italian press, arrived in Rome on Thursday to take up
the U.S. ambassador's post, and he defended his ability to handle it.
   U.S. Senate confirmation of his nomination was blocked for a
month by a dispute over the nomination process of President Bush's
administration, a controversy unrelated to Secchia's qualifications.
But some senators also expressed concern about Secchia's tendency to
make vulgar remarks.
   Secchia was confirmed last week by the Senate.
   ``I'm delighted to be here at last,'' said Secchia's wife, Joan,
when the ambassador presented his family to journalists.
   ``La famiglia,'' (the family), Secchia said in Italian, gesturing
to his wife, two sons and one of his two daughters.
   Secchia, a Michigan businessman and a leading Bush backer in the
1988 presidential campaign, is the grandson of Italian immigrants.
   He was asked if he was confident he could successfully be the
chief U.S. diplomat in Italy with the negative coverage of his
nomination in the Italian press.
   Among the widely reported incidents was one in which Secchia
reportedly called a female delegate to the 1988 Republican National
Convention a ``bitch'' in front of other party members. He has
repeatedly said he was misquoted.
   ``I'm very confident I can carry out the role my president has
given me. I've done it before,'' Secchia said.
   He said of reports about him in the Italian press, ``I'm a pretty
strong person. I can handle that,'' adding ``I'm very proud of my
accomplishments.''
   Asked again about questions over whether he was fit to serve in
the post, he replied, ``That's behind me. I'm not here to win the
Italian press,'' although he promised the reporters he would meet
with them regularly.
   Secchia announced that as of late July, Italian tourists and
business people will be able to enter the United States without a
visa. Bush announced the change in a visit to Rome in May but no
date had been announced when it would go into effect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890629-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1431EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica 3rdLd-Writethru a0552 06-29 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0552,0795</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Leader Says Plan for Black Vote Will End Nation's Isolation</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS grafs 3-4, `The plan...the plan' to update with approval.
Pickup 5th, `Party leader...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the governing
National Party said today the party's plan to eventually give blacks
a direct vote in national affairs will end South Africa's isolation.
   Anti-apartheid activists and conservatives reacted with
skepticism to the proposal, which envisions blacks having a vote in
national affairs within five years. Anglican Archbishop Desmond
Tutu, who won the 1984 Nobel Peace Prize for his fight against
apartheid, rejected the plan outright.
   The plan is part of the party's new election platform, which also
holds out the possibility of giving the black majority a voice in
writing a new constitution.
   The party held a one-day congress in Pretoria today and accepted
the platform. No vote was held _ the congress simply adjourned with
no delegates voicing objections to the plan.
   Party leader F.W. de Klerk, designated to replace retiring
President P.W. Botha after the Sept. 6 parliamentary elections,
opened the meeting by saying the party could lead the country back
into the international community, which has condemned South Africa's
system of racial separation.
   ``Our cause is just and the doors must open. We will not have to
go crawling back, we will walk in proudly and with our heads high,''
said de Klerk, who wept when the 1,500 delegates greeted him with a
standing ovation in Pretoria City Hall.
   A less enthusiastic ovation followed his brief tribute to Botha,
who did not attend the meeting. The two have had strained relations
since March, when party leaders indicated they wanted Botha to
resign so de Klerk could take over.
   An editorial in the anti-apartheid Cape Times of Cape Town
complained that the proposal provided for a bill of rights only as a
``possible option'' and failed to say how blacks would be
incorporated into the government.
   ``Whatever its vote-winning merits for the NP, as a plan to
resolve the South African crisis it is much too tentative,'' the
newspaper said.
   Tutu said the platform it was designed to make apartheid more
comfortable rather than dismantle it.
   ``We are not interested in reform. We want to see apartheid
abolished,'' Tutue said today in Hilleroed, Denmark, where he was
attending a festival of the Danish national church.
   Ferdi Hartzenberg, deputy leader of the pro-apartheid
Conservative Party, said the plan would lead to majority rule by
South Africa's 28 million blacks and deprive the 5 million whites of
influence in the writing of a new constitution.
   Political analysts say the Conservative Party may gain some seats
in the national legislature as a result of the National Party reform
proposals.
   South Africa's apartheid system denies blacks a voice in
government and relegates them to separate housing, schools and
health care facilities. Whites also control the nation's economy.
   Many foreign governments have imposed economic sanctions and
other limitations on dealing with South Africa in efforts to force
an end to apartheid.
   Much of the National Party's platform represents a softening of
policies designed to maintain white control, and is seen as
reflecting the views of de Klerk.
   The five-year program includes removal of criminal penalties for
residential apartheid violations, more government subsidies for
multiracial schools, removal of race as the major criterion for
identifying political groups, a bill of rights, and negotiating a
new constitution with black leaders.
   In London, a leader of the outlawed African National Congress
guerrilla group called the platform an advance, but from a wrong
position.
   ``It's a step forward to the extent that the National Party
recognizes that South Africa cannot be ruled on the basis of
exclusive power for the white minority,'' Thabo Mbeki, secretary for
international affairs, said Wednesday en route to the ANC's base in
Lusaka, Zambia.
   ``But the position is wrong because it continues to define people
as black and white and not as the people of South Africa. The period
of transition must emerge from negotiations.''
   Clive Derby-Lewis, spokesman for the Conservative Party, likened
the plan to ``the sales talk of an unscrupulous car dealer'' and
said the National Party was hiding plans to go further in reducing
racial laws.
   ``It is completely different from what they really intend to do.
It is real skulduggery,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``It
will generate further distrust in the Nationalists by the
electorate.''
   Beeld, the leading Afrikaans-language newspaper, pro-government
but generally moderate in its views, said the party's plan ``has the
potential to create a new South Africa'' if carried out with vigor.
</TEXT>
