<FIRST>r w AM-ChemicalWeapons 370   06-29 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical Weapons, 370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Says Chemical Weapons Residue Should Be Buried in U.S. Landfills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The non-toxic waste produced when chemical
weapons stored on a Pacific island are destroyed should be buried in
U.S. landfills, the Army said Thursday.
   The Army had hoped to dump some of the waste from Johnston Atoll
into the ocean, but said in a statement that it decided against
asking Congress for an exception to a law that bans such disposal.
   Landfills that might be used in the project weren't named in
Thursday's environmental impact study. Sites won't be known until
the project is approved and bids solicited from private companies,
said Army spokesman Lt. Col. John Chapla.
   The disposal cannot proceed until public comments are reviewed
and the Army's impact statement approved.
   The impact study deals with the first part of a long-term program
to destroy thousands of rounds of aging chemical weapons stored at
various Army depots.
   The Johnston Atoll depot was used by the Army to test and develop
an incineration process to destroy the weapons. The environmental
impact studies for that depot are farther along than for those
inside the United States.
   The incineration process will destroy the toxic chemical gases.
However, it produces three types of waste: liquid brine; solid waste
that can be sold for scrap; and solid waste without value.
   The Army said the liquid brine should be dried and shipped to
landfills in the United States.
   ``This alternative will be used unless other considerations _
cost, logistics impact or political factors _ make it not viable,''
the Army said. ``No significant adverse environmental impacts are
expected.''
   If the plan isn't approved, the brine likely would be stored in
drums on the island.
   The Army refuses to disclose the size of its chemical stockpile.
However, published estimates range from 25,000 tons to 40,000 tons.
   The Army's existing chemical stocks average more than 25 years
old. Within the United States, they are stored at depots in Utah,
Alabama, Maryland, Indiana, Kentucky, Oregon, Colorado and Arkansas.
   Congress, in approving the production of new chemical weapons
during the Reagan administration, specified the Army would have to
proceed simultaneously with the destruction of existing stocks.
</TEXT>
