<FIRST>u w PM-OilBan     06-29 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Ban,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Votes to Ban Oil Exploration in Alaskan Bay, Elsewhere</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   By H. JOSEF HEBERT=
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Appropriations Committee, citing
concerns about a possible oil spill, approved legislation today
imposing a year-long moratorium on oil or gas exploration in
Alaska's Bristol Bay, one of the nation's premier fishing areas.
   The legislation also would extend existing prohibitions against
oil or gas exploration along vast stretches off the coasts of
California, Florida and New England, and impose a new moratorium on
leases along a coastal stretch from Rhode Island to Maryland.
   The curbs, which would deal a sharp blow to the petroleum
industry if they prevail in final legislation, were included in an
$11.6 billion fiscal 1990 appropriation bill for the Interior
Department, which oversees the leasing of offshore oil exporation
rights.
   It prohibits Interior from using any funds during the fiscal year
beginning Oct. 1 on oil leases in Bristol Bay.
   An amendment that would have allowed exploration to proceed in
the bay off southwestern Alaska was defeated by a vote of 29-22. Its
sponsor, Rep. Ralph Regula, R-Ohio, argued development of the bay's
oil reserves is badly needed to meet the country's energy needs.
   But Rep. Sydney Yates, D-Ill., chairman of the appropriations
subcommittee that had recommended the moratorium, cited the
devastation left by the oil spill from the tanker Exxon Valdez in
Alaska's Prince William Sound last March 24.
   ``We've seen what's happened in Prince William Sound,'' Yates
declared and began reciting details of the environmental and
economic chaos left by the spill. He said the $1 billion fishing
industry in Bristol Bay is ``is probably 50 times as significant.''
   The Alaska state government has said the fishing industry in
Bristol Bay could be even more vulnerable to a major oil spill as in
the area of Prince William Sound. The oil from Bristol Bay would
likely be transported by tanker.
   In Juneau, Alaska Gov. Steve Cowper called the committee action
clear evidence that ``our views are being heard in Washington.'' The
Alaska congressional delegation had sought the moratorium on Bristol
Bay exploration.
   The Interior Department last year sold exploratory leases for a
half-dozen sites in Bristol Bay for $95 million. The legislation
would call for repurchasing those leases.
   In addition to the curbs on oil exploration in Bristol Bay, the
legislation also calls for a moratorium on exploration in three
areas off the California coast; in the Gulf of Mexico off the
southern Florida coast; in the Georges Banks off the New England
coast, and along a coastal buffer from Rhode Island to southern
Maryland.
   The Bush administration already has postponed issuing leases in
southern and northern California, pending further environmental
review. The House bill would extend the moratorium to leases off the
central California coast as well. The leases off southern Florida
also have been put on hold by the administration.
   A moratorium also has been in effect previously for the leases in
the Georges Bank.
</TEXT>
