<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-Scene     06-29 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Scene,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Watch on the Supreme Court Steps: A Countdown to Nothing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus-Abortion, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By the hundreds they waited in line, some all
night long, for the abortion decision. What they got, those few who
actually made it into the Supreme Court Thursday, were decisions
affecting Indian reservations and Tupperware sales.
   People who have waited for a space shot that eventually is
postponed would know how that feels.
   Disappointing is too weak a word. Frustrating doesn't make it.
Neither does thwarted, letdown or dissatisfied. Thursday's failure
to deliver a decision in the abortion case was like a countdown to
nothing. A scrub. No go.
   Molly Yard, president of the National Organization of Women
likened the wait to a Chinese water torture.
   ``I have to say that I think in my fantasizing that there must be
an argument going on,'' she said. ``We've always believed that
Sandra Day O'Connor was the swing vote, and I hope and pray that she
will join with our four friends on the Supreme Court who are for the
right of a woman to control her reproductive life under the privacy
interpretation of the Constitution.''
   Randall Terry, national director of Operation Rescue said it was
``a little frustrating to keep coming again and again and again and
again,'' and added: ``Frankly, I just think they want to get the
decision and get out of town. I mean, if I was a Supreme Court
justice, I would throw the decision off the airplane as I was
leaving the country.''
   Olivia Gans, director of Victims of Abortion, a right-to-life
group, acknowledged it was hard to wait ``but we're optimistic.''
   When the word came out that the only decisions Thursday were in
the cookware and Indian reservation cases, the cameras and
microphones were dismantled, but the demonstrators got into a little
dialogue of their own.
   ``Not the church, not the state, women must decide our fate,''
chanted the pro-choice side.
   ``What about the babies' fate?'' was a chant in response.
   Two male demonstrators faced off:
   ``Do you have the right to decide the choice of someone else?''
   ``No, neither does the woman. She doesn't have the right to. ...''
   ``But it's her body.''
   ``Oh, come on, man, a fetus is not a woman's body.''
   ``You can't tell her what to do with her body.''
   ``Then she can't tell the baby that baby's got no right to live.''
   ``It's her body and you don't have the right to make that choice
for her.''
   ``A fetus is not her body.''
   ``It's inside her body.''
   ``A tapeworm's inside you. Does that make a tapeworm your body?''
   A young woman, holding up a placard of the National Organization
of Women, told an older woman ``I don't believe it is human until it
is born.'' The response: ``You don't believe it is human til it is
born? You had better study science, honey.''
   Of the line of people stretching around one side of the building,
only about 50 got in for the brief session. First in line was
Michael Carrier, a student at Yale University, who said he had
waited since 6:30 p.m. Wednesday.
   ``I'm here because I feel this is such an important decision,''
Carrier said. ``I just had to be here when it came down.''
   In front of the meditative female statue on one side of the
entrance stairs of the Supreme Court, the forces opposing abortion
were arrayed, holding yellow banners with black letters: ``The Child
Killing Must Be Stopped.''
   On the right, in front of the vigilant male statue that typifies
execution of the laws were the pro-choice demonstrators, holding
purple banners with white letters: ``Keep Abortion Legal.''
   A kneeling, bearded man in the robes of a monk said his rosary
while frowning at pro-choice placards. One small girl held a placard
larger than herself: ``My Mother Chose Life,'' another's read ``Why
Do My Future Playmates Have to Die?'' There were the usual people
displaying large color photographs of bleeding fetuses, a staple of
anti-abortion demonstrations.
   In space lingo, a launch scrub is followed by a turnaround _
readying the ship for its next try. For the court, the
demonstrators, the cameramen and the tourists caught up in a
headline making activity on a fine summer day, the turnaround aims
for another try on Monday.
</TEXT>
