<FIRST>r i AM-Nazi     06-29 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nazi,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Begin Search for Convicted Nazi Murderer Who Escaped</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have begun an
international manhunt for a convicted Nazi murderer who fled to
avoid arrest, a state prosecutor said Thursday.
   Wuppertal prosecutor Friedhelm Gabriel did not rule out the
possibility that an underground group may have aided the escape of
former Nazi death camp guard Gottfried Weise.
   Weise, 69, was convicted Jan. 28, 1988, of killing at least five
prisoners in 1944 at the Auschwitz concentration camp. Weise
disappeared after a federal court upheld his conviction and life
sentence.
   Gabriel said Weise was allowed to remain at his home near
Wuppertal pending appeal to care for his sick wife after officials
confiscated his passport and Weise mortgaged his house to post a
$150,000 bond.
   But when police went to arrest him on April 20 to begin serving
his prison term, Weise had disappeared.
   Asked about speculation that an underground organization similar
to one described in Frederick Forsyth's 1972 novel, ``The Odessa
File,'' could have helped Weise escape, Gabriel said: ``There are
suspicions that groups like Odessa exist, but we don't have concrete
evidence.''
   ``Such an organization would have to be very secretive,'' Gabrial
said in an interview from Wuppertal, about 210 miles northwest of
Frankfurt.
   The novel is about a ruthless group of Nazi sympathizers who help
smuggle war criminals to safety in South America and other parts of
the world.
   ``But Weise had to have some sort of help, he had to get new
identity papers somewhere, because we have his passport. He also
doesn't have much money; he was on a pension,'' Gabriel said.
   He said Weise's wife, Ursula, 62, subsequently disappeared.
   ``She suddenly left, we think on June 22, and her relatives
refuse to tell us where she's gone. We believe she's trying to join
her husband,'' the prosecutor said.
   Police issued an international arrest warrant for Weise.
   Alfred Streim, who runs the federal Nazi Document Center in
Ludwigsburg, said it was possible Weise was helped to escape ``but
there has never been proof that an Odessa-type organization exists.''
   Streim's office is responsible for tracking fugitive war
criminals in West Germany.
   ``There were some people in Italy who helped in escapes after the
war, but they were not as organized as Odessa,'' Streim said.
   During Weise's 15-month trial he became known as the ``William
Tell of Auschwitz'' when witnesses testified that he killed an
8-year-old boy and a 17-year-old girl by forcing them to balance tin
cans on their heads, which he used for target practice.
   He was convicted in their deaths and of killing two male
prisoners who tried to escape by hiding in a supply truck. Weise
also was convicted of killing an inmate because he responded too
slowly to orders.
</TEXT>
