<FIRST>r i AM-China-EEC     06-29 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-EEC,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Criticizes EEC for Denouncing Crackdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China on Thursday said the European Economic
Community was presumptuous in denouncing the suppression of the
pro-democracy movement and that its actions could harm relations
with Beijing.
   ``Before finding out the truth concerning the quelling of the
counterrevolutionary rebellion in China, the European Council worked
so fast as to rashly issue a statement ... making presumptuous
accusations against China,'' said Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Li
Jinhua.
   ``The Chinese government cannot but express deep regret over this
unreasonable act,'' she said.
   The leaders of the 12-nation EEC Tuesday condemned ``the brutal
repression taking place in China.''
   They also called for an embargo on arm sales to China and urged
the World Bank to postpone new loans to Beijing. The United States,
Australia, Japan and Canada have taken similar steps.
   The crackdown on the movement for a freer society began on June 3
when the army drove student protesters from Tiananmen Square in
Beijing. Since then, the government has arrested more than 1,800
people and announced the executions of 27.
   The EEC urged the Chinese government to halt the executions,
respect human rights and ``take into account the hopes for freedom
and democracy deeply felt by the population.''
   Ms. Li said China put down the ``rebellion'' in accordance with
the Chinese constitution and that the European countries had
``unilaterally adopted decisions jeopardizing the bilateral
relations.''
   ``All attempts by all foreign governments or organizations to
bring pressures to bear on the Chinese government or interfere in
China's internal affairs in this or that manner are unwise and
futile,'' she said.
   Ms. Li said the government hoped Eurepean leaders, after learning
the ``truth,'' would ``treasure our friendly relations established
after years of efforts.''
   The government says a small group of people instigated the seven
weeks of demonstrations leading up to the crackdown.
   It also says only 200 to 300 people, most of them soldiers, were
killed in the clashes in Beijing. Chinese witnesses and Western
intelligence reports say the death toll could be as high as 3,000
and that most victims were unarmed civilians.
</TEXT>
