<FIRST>u a PM-ForcedHeirs 1stLd-Writethru a0600 06-29 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Forced Heirs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0600,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislature Amends Louisiana's Forced Heirship Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to grafs to CLARIFY that offspring can inherit
after just one parent dies; PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, ``By that ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Legislature has voted to relax a
Napoleonic-era law that forces parents to leave a portion of their
estate to their children.
   The legislation amending Louisiana's unique ``forced heirship''
law would guarantee an inheritance only to offspring who are under
23 when a parent dies.
   ``By that time, the parents have raised and educated their
children,'' the bill's sponsor, Rep. Sydney Nelson, said Wednesday.
   Critics of the law complained it deprives people of the right to
dispose of their estates as they see fit, such as withholding an
inheritance from a wayward son or daughter.
   Louisiana adheres to a civil code first adopted by France,
including forced heirship, which requires parents with one child to
leave that child at least one-fourth of the estate. Parents with two
or more children must leave 50 percent to them.
   On Tuesday, the House placed routine amendments on the bill and
gave it 65-36 passage. The Senate on Wednesday concurred in the
amendments 26-10.
   The bill was sent to Gov. Buddy Roemer, who is expected to sign
it, Nelson said.
   ``If we concur, we will be wipping out 181 years of history.
We'll be wiping out equality among children,'' warned Sen. Oswald
Decuir. He said parents could pick out a favored child and leave the
others with nothing.
   ``Forced heirship. The key word is `force,''' Rep. Randy Roach
said during the debate. ``What right has the state to tell parents
they've got to leave a certain portion of their estate to adult
children they've already raised and educated?''
</TEXT>
