<SECOND>AM-Korea,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Battle Police to Go to North Korean Youth Festival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police and radical students
battled with tear gas, steel bars and rocks Thursday as students
demanded the government lift a ban barring them from a youth
festival in North Korea.
   President Roh Tae-woo said leftists threaten democracy in South
Korea, and Unification Minister Lee Hong-koo said the government may
postpone planned talks with Pyongyang's communist government.
   About 1,500 students fought riot troopers around Seoul's Hanyang
University after 3,000 police sealed off the campus to stop other
college students joining the protest.
   Waves of students poured over the school walls, throwing rocks
and firebombs. Small groups wielding metal pipes charged through
broken walls and attacked police.
   Riot police fought back, firing volleys of tear gas from armored
vans and rifles and hurling tear gas grenades and rocks across the
walls and locked gates.
   A dozen students were seen injured. One policeman was injured
seriously when tear gas shells exploded inside an armored van.
   In downtown Seoul, about 700 students wanting to get into Hanyang
campus occupied a major intersection. They fought riot police with
firebombs and rocks, forcing shoppers to race for shelter.
   ``Drive out Yankees who block national unification!'' the
protesters screamed. ``Overthrow Roh Tae-woo!''
   Radicals back North Korea's calls for the Seoul government to
expel 43,000 U.S. troops whose presence they say hinders dialogue on
unification. Roh says the troops deter the north from invading again.
   ``Let's march to Pyongyang!'' the students shouted, demanding the
government allow them to attend a July 1-8 youth festival in North
Korea.
   Seoul says Pyongyang is using the festival to stir up radical
movements. North Korea denies the charges about the sports and
cultural event that is attended mainly by non-aligned and communist
nations.
   Meanwhile, Roh pledged today he will maintain a ``strong''
government against illegal acts and leftists who he claimed threaten
democracy.
   Roh said individual contacts with North Korea undermine his
government's efforts to advance national unification.
   He was referring to Wednesday's surprise arrest of opposition
legislator Suh Kyung-won for a secret trip to North Korea and talks
with its leader, Kim Il Sung.
   Suh's arrest stunned South Koreans and prosecutors moved quickly
to broaden their investigations. The lawmaker visited Pyongyang in
August after contacting North Korean agents in West Germany.
   Security officials said Suh, already charged with violating the
National Security Law forbidding contacts with ``anti-state''
bodies, also could be accused of espionage if it is found he worked
with North Korean agents.
</TEXT>
