<FIRST>r i AM-Greece     06-29 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communists Press for Coalition; Mandate Running Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greece's communist alliance, with a day
left to form a government, Thursday continued to press for a
coalition of all parties despite continuous rejections from the main
conservative and socialist parties.
   Harilaos Florakis, leader of the Coalition of the Left and
Progress, met with ailing caretaker Premier Andreas Papandreou at
Athens' General State Hospital and with conservative party leader
Constantine Mitsotakis.
   More such meetings are planned before the Coalition on Friday
stands to lose its mandate to negotiate a governing alliance.
   After a 55-minute meeting with Papandreou, Florakis said the
coalition ``will assess the results of today's talks.''
   The Coalition's proposals for a ``national unity government'' to
include all political parties has run up against strong opposition,
mainly because of its insistence that a Coalition politician lead
the government.
   The impasse follows inconclusive June 18 elections at which the
Coalition, made up of the pro-Moscow Greek Communist Party and the
Eurocommunist Greek Left, won 28 seats after receiving 13 percent of
the vote and emerged as a power broker.
   President Christos Sartzetakis gave the Coalition a three-day
exploratory mandate after the dominant conservatives and socialists
failed to negotiate alliances. It was the first such mandate
received by the communists since the party was recognized officially
in 1974.
   Their proposal has been turned down both by Mitsotakis'
center-right New Democracy Party and Papandreou's Panhellenic
Socialist Movement.
   The stumbling point is the Coalition's insistence that neither
Mitsotakis nor Papandreou head a coalition.
   ``We believe that the demand to place certain persons above the
possibility to find a solution is very wrong,'' said Eurocommunist
leader Leonidas Kyrkos.
   ``The premier of the new government should be able to reflect a
greater deal of trust,'' Kyrkos said.
   Papandreou failed to win a third term in office because his
government has been rocked by a series of scandals for the last 10
months.
   Mitsotakis, whose party racked up 44 percent of the vote and 145
seats in the 300-member Parliament, said the Coalition demand is
``impossible.''
   ``How is it possible for 13 percent of the people to impose their
will on the 44 percent?'' Mitsotakis said.
   Papandreou, who received 39 percent and 125 seats, also refused.
   ``We consider this term unacceptable because, for us, Papandreou
is our leader,'' said acting government spokesman Sotiris
Kostopoulos.
   The socialist leader was hospitalized one week ago suffering from
kidney failure and heart problems. His condition is gradually
improving.
   If the coalition does not form a government by Friday,
Sartzetakis will ask the three parties to try to resolve their
differences and form a coalition.
   If that fails, then Sartzetakis must appoint a caretaker
government of high court judges and call early elections.
</TEXT>
