<FIRST>r i AM-Hostages     06-29 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colleagues of British Hostage Appeal For His Release</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colleagues and friends of John McCarthy
appealed to his kidnappers Thursday to free the British television
journalist before his mother dies of cancer.
   Their statement was written in Arabic and issued in Beirut.
   It was addressed to the captors and said: ``We plead with you in
the name of humanity for which Islam is known to release our
colleague John out of mercy for his dying mother, whose only wish
now is to see him before she passes away.''
   The Beirut office of London-based Worldwide Television News
handled the appeal's distribution. McCarthy, 32, worked for the
organization when he was kidnapped April 17, 1986, on the way to the
Beirut airport.
   It was the third appeal in 10 days. McCarthy's father, Pat,
pleaded for his release June 20, saying the captive's mother,
Sheila, was ``gravely ill in hospital.''
   ``The doctors have told us she is dying,'' the senior McCarthy
said.
   On the next day, Dr. Terrance Wheeler, the physician treating
Mrs. McCarthy for cancer in London, said she ``has at best a few
days to live.''
   ``It would be the kindest of humanitarian gestures on the part of
those holding John McCarthy to release John in the final moments of
his mother's life,'' Wheeler said.
   McCarthy is among 14 foreigners missing in Lebanon and presumed
to be hostages, including nine Americans. Held longest is Terry A.
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press,
who was abducted March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
