<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1527EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-Speech     06-29 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Speech,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Gives Officials More Power to Ban Ads</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus-Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court issued a free-speech ruling
Thursday that gives public officials more power to ban advertising
and sales pitches _ including the peddling of cookware in college
dormitories.
   Justice Antonin Scalia, writing for the court in a 6-3 decision,
said government restrictions on commercial speech may be valid even
if they ``go beyond the least restrictive means to achieve the
desired end.''
   As long as the rules are ``reasonable (and) narrowly tailored to
achieve the desired objective ... we leave it to governmental
decision makers to judge what manner of regulation may best be
employed,'' Scalia said.
   By contrast, the least-restrictive test remains in force for
other forms of expression _ particularly political speech.
   The court acted in the case of a ban on cookware sales on
campuses of the State University of New York, SUNY.
   While the justices said university officials may place some
restrictions on commerical activity on campus, they left unanswered
another issue raised by the case _ whether the univeristy's ban is
too broad because it also limits non-commercial speech.
   The justices said a lower court should study that issue.
   The three dissenters, Justices Harry A. Blackmun, William J.
Brennan and Thurgood Marshall, said the rules involving
non-commercial speech do go too far.
   Blackmun said the ban could prevent a student from meeting his
doctor or lawyer in his dorm room if the doctor or lawyer is paid
for the visit. It could even prevent a student from paying a music
teacher or a speech therapist to come to the dorm room for tutoring,
Blackmun said.
   The court, he said, is turning its back on its own free-speech
precedents.
   ``The majority holds that `least-restrictive means' analysis does
not apply to commercial speech cases, a holding it is able to reach
only by recasting a good bit of contrary language in our past
cases,'' Blackmun said.
   However, Scalia said Thursday's ruling was in line with a 1986
decision that allowed Puerto Rico to ban advertising promoting
casino gambling that was aimed at Puerto Rican residents.
   Scalia also cited a week-old ruling in which the court made it
easier for communities to turn down the volume at rock concerts. In
that decision, the court upheld a New York City rule that
rock-concert sponsors use a sound system operated by a
city-designated engineer.
   The SUNY board of trustees adopted a rule in 1966 to prohibit
most commercial enterprises from operating on campuses.
   The ban was challenged by American Future Systems Inc., a
housewares company in Bryn Mawr, Pa., after one of its
representatives was arrested in 1982 at the campus in Cortland,
N.Y., for refusing to leave a dorm.
   The housewares company attracts customers by offering free
Florida vacations to students who arrange sales demonstrations in
their dormi rooms for groups of their friends.
   A federal judge upheld the SUNY ban, but the 2nd U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals overturned the ruling last year. The appeals court
ordered further hearings to determine whether there might be less
restrictive rules to accomplish the university's purpose.
   SUNY's appeal was supported by university officials in 10 states
and groups representing thousands of college administrators
nationwide.
   ``The fundamental right of state colleges and universities to
control the use of their premises is at issue,'' said a
friend-of-the-court brief filed by the university officials from
California, Connecticut, Florida, Michigan, Illinois, Ohio, South
Carolina, Rhode Island, New Jersey and Vermont.
   The appeal also was supported by the American Council on
Education, the American Association of State Colleges and
Universities, the National Association of State Universities and
Land Grant Colleges and the National Association of Student
Personnel Administrators.
   Also Thursday, the court ruled in a case from Washington state,
limiting the power of Indian tribes to use zoning laws to control
land owned by non-Indians within a reservation's boundaries.
   The court said tribes may be forced to share the zoning power
with state or county officials.
</TEXT>
