<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Newhouse     06-29 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Newhouse,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitzi Newhouse, Widow of Publisher, Dies at 87</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY33</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mitzi Newhouse, widow of newspaper and
magazine publisher S.I. Newhouse and a longtime patron of the arts,
died at home Thursday after a brief illness. She was 87.
   Mrs. Newhouse donated $1 million in 1973 to help establish the
Mitzi Newhouse Theater at Lincoln Center, which was a key to
allowing Joseph Papp's New York Shakespeare Festival to become a
part of the performing arts center.
   Papp praised her Thursday.
   ``Mitzi had no airs about her, a very down-to-earth woman, who
was very supportive of the arts and the work of the New York
Shakespeare Festival,'' he said.
   Mrs. Newhouse was also a contributor to the Parsons School Of
Design, where she studied as a young woman, and to the Manhattan
School of Music.
   Within the Newhouse enterprises, she was active as a corporate
officer and took a special interest in Vogue magazine, one of the
Conde Nast group publications bought by her husband in 1959.
   The Newhouse family holdings also include 26 newspapers in 22
cities; the Random House book publishing group; Parade, a Sunday
newspaper supplement; and cable television systems serving a million
homes.
   Mrs. Newhouse grew up on Manhattan's west side, the daughter of
Judith and Sam Epstein, who operated a clothing business. She met
Newhouse on a blind date in the fall of 1923 and they married eight
months later.
   Newhouse once said in an unpublished memoir that his gregarious
wife opened a new way of life for him.
   ``Mitzi was a born New Yorker,'' he said. ``I acquired the
taste.''
   In 1979 the couple moved to Palm Beach were Newhouse died later
that year. After his death, Mrs. Newhouse became active in Palm
Beach cultural affairs.
   Survivors include her two sons, Donald and S.I. Newhouse Jr., six
grandchildren, four great grandchildren and a brother, Walter Evans
of St. Louis and Florida.
   Services were set for Wednesday at Temple Emanu-el in New York
City.
</TEXT>
