<SECOND>AM-Girdle Bust, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0630,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Customs: Second Woman Arrested Smuggling Cocaine in Girdles</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT spelling of Guatemala.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colombian woman has been arrested and accused of
attempting to smuggle cocaine inside four girdles, the second such
arrest within three days, the U.S. Customs Service said.
   Customs spokesman Charles Conroy said the 32-year-old woman, who
arrived Wednesday at Houston Intercontinental Airport on a Taca
Airlines flight from Guatemala, was detained after Customs
inspectors became suspicious of her behavior and dress.
   A search revealed 16 pounds of cocaine hidden inside her girdles.
   The seizure was almost identical to Monday's arrest of Blanca
Nellie Dominguez Toloza, 38, of Colombia, who faces charges of
smuggling more than 5 kilograms or 11 pounds of cocaine in girdles
she was wearing.
   In both cases, the women were stopping in Houston en route to
European destinations and were traveling on altered passports, said
Candace Vice, chief Customs inspector at the airport.
   Ms. Vice speculated that the women were transporting cocaine to
Europe because the drug's value is about three times higher there
than in the United States.
   Ms. Vice said the cocaine seized Wednesday was divided into
square packets and concealed in pouches inside the woman's four
girdles.
   The name of the woman arrested Wednesday was not released pending
formal charges.
</TEXT>
