<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Mobutu     06-29 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Mobutu,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Meets With and Praises Zaire President Mobutu</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Thursday praised Zaire
President Mobutu Sese Seko for ``setting the stage for national
reconciliation'' in neighboring Angola and vowed closer U.S.-Zaire
economic ties.
   Bush agreed to encourage more U.S. investment in Zaire and lent
his support to new loans it is seeking from the International
Monetary Fund, the two leaders said after a two-hour White House
session.
   It was the president's first White House meeting with an African
head-of-state.
   Mobutu, speaking in French at the outdoor ceremony, said his
meeting and lunch with Bush had been one of ``warmth and
friendship.''
   He also sought to defend his regime's human rights record.
   ``Zaire can be ranked among those countries which observe the
rule of law, not to be confused or mistaken with any incidental
mishaps that are attributable to an administration or an
individual,'' he said.
   Mobutu has long supported U.S. policy goals in Africa. However,
his regime has been criticized by Amnesty International of
widespread human-rights abuses.
   Still, Mobutu noted that the UN Commission Human Rights had
withdrawn his country from the list of nations it monitors for human
rights.
   ``I informed the president of the arrangements and measures of
protection (for human rights) which have been set up in Zaire for
some years now,'' Mobutu said.
   Bush is the sixth U.S. president to work with Mobutu, Bush
himself observed in his remarks. ``The strong ties of friendship
between Zaire and the United States endure and prosper.''
   He called Mobutu ``one of our most valued friends'' in Africa.
   Mobutu, who has also met with other administration officials and
with congressional leaders, was to meet on Friday with Vice
President Dan Quayle.
   Bush warmly praised Mobutu for his role in bringing about the
recent cease-fire in Angola, where civil war has raged for 14 years.
   ``Just last week, he brought together, for the first time, in the
presence of 18 African chiefs of state, the leadership of Angola's
warring factions, setting the stage for national reconciliation in
that country,'' Bush said.
   The president said the cease-fire was the first step toward
``long elusive'' peace in southwestern Africa, and toward ``the
total withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola,'' which he called a
joint U.S.-Zaire goal.
   The two leaders exchanged paperwork for a treaty to encourage
greater U.S. investment there. Bush also said the United States
supports Zaire's three-year program to restructure its economy as
part of a package for getting new IMF loans.
   Mobutu's last meeting with a U.S. president was a 1986 session
with then-president Reagan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
