<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0613 06-29 1077</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0613,1102</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party's `Monopoly' Over, Polish Leader Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf with state news agency report
on party candidate; INSERTS 1 graf after 6th graf pvs, ``Jaruzelski, party
...'' with setting for interview.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski says the Communist
Party's automatic leading role in Poland ``already is history'' and
it will never return to the monopoly rule of the past.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Jaruzelski also
praised Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and said Poland would seek
``friendly American support'' but not ``charity'' during the July
9-11 visit of President Bush.
   As to his own political plans, he said he would seriously
consider the opposition's stance before deciding whether to accept
the new office of president, to be decided by the National Assembly
before Bush's visit. Solidarity legislators who are a minority in
the assembly have said they'll vote against Jaruzelski if, as
expected, he is nominated by the party.
   The state news agency reported Thursday a Central Committee
plenum, at which the party was expected to name its candidate, would
take place Friday.
   ``I am not striving for this office the way known and typical in
the West. ... I will not crawl to this post,'' Jaruzelski said.
   He said political and economic changes in Poland put it in the
vanguard of East bloc reform but the opportunity for change could be
lost if society rejects economic steps that are ``painful _ like
every surgery that is expected to bring health.''
   Jaruzelski, party leader and president of the Council of State,
discussed his eight years in power from the martial-law period to
the historic reforms of recent months in an interview Wednesday in a
reception room near his office in the Council of Ministers building.
He also answered other questions in writing.
   The Polish leader, who wore a gray business suit and his familiar
dark glasses, spoke in soft tones as he sat on a green velvet settee
beneath a huge oil painting of a winter scene by 19th century Polish
artist Julian Falat.
   He said the communists did poorly in the June 4 and June 18
elections, losing 99 of the 100 seats in the freely contested
Senate, because voters had not yet realized the extent to which the
party has changed its program in favor of democracy and reforms.
   ``That is why I think that if the party will honestly ...
implement its program, then it will have a chance to rebuild its
influence in society,'' he said.
   But he added the party's influence could never again be ``on the
basis of monopoly.''
   ``We have become convinced that monopoly is a very unhealthy
thing, not only in the economy, but also in political life,'' he
said.
   On the party's ``leading role'' _ by which the party in the
constitution claims an automatic right to rule _ Jaruzelski replied
in writing: ``The leading role of the party, understood in a
mechanical way, already is history. Today the party, like other
political forces, seeks social confidence and support.''
   When there was no challenge to party rule, he said later, it
actually lost support because it became bureaucratic, grew used to
not having to compete for popular support, and was blamed for
economic failures.
   ``What was supposed to be a strength turned out to be a
weakness,'' he said.
   Jaruzelski, who imposed martial law to suppress Solidarity in
1981 and then led his party to restore the independent union this
year, made clear during the interview that he remained fully
committed to both decisions.
   Imposing martial-law was ``personally very painful,'' he said.
   ``Looking at it from a certain distance today, I don't want to
blame the opposition alone. We were somehow not mature. ... There
was a lot of distrust on both sides,'' he said.
   He also blamed a rise in East-West tensions in the early 1980s
and ``the situation in the East'' _ a reference to pressures from
the Soviet Union under Leonid Brezhnev.
   ``Internal and external conditions formed such a knot that it is
difficult to say today whether another course of events was
possible,'' he said.
   Of the tumultuous January party plenum in which the key decisions
were taken to open talks with the Solidarity-led opposition, and at
which Jaruzelski emerged victorious from a vote of confidence, he
said: ``I really threw everything onto the scale, my destiny and my
dignity. ...
   ``It would be the greatest drama for me if history one day said
these decisions were wrong. That's why I wish so much that the
agreement, that this pluralism, passes the test in real life.''
   Jaruzelski, who turns 66 on July 6, demurred when asked if he
would take the presidency, a decision he will likely have to make
within the next week.
   ``I haven't gone to confession in a very long time and I can see
that you want me to confess,'' joked the communist who grew up in a
Roman Catholic family. ``But I used to go, I used to go.''
   He said his candidacy would depend on ``democratic''
consultations within the party and could not be decided by him alone.
   ``I will also seriously consider the stand of the opposition,
understanding that the president, especially in our conditions when
we have to unite the nation's efforts and build platforms of accord,
should have at least a minimum of support'' from all sides, he said.
   ``I am a soldier, so I have a deep-rooted feeling of duty _ but
also of honor. I will not crawl to this post,'' he said.
   Turning to Walesa, Jaruzelski said:
   ``I must appreciate Lech Walesa's realism. Especially today, when
I see him as a man who has developed his political possibilities
very much.''
   Of Bush, he said: ``I am very happy that Mr. George Bush is
president ... . Of course it is not interfering in U.S. internal
affairs to express such an opinion, especially since the next
elections are in four years. ... He sees world problems, European
problems, including Polish ones, in a friendly way. ``We don't want
gifts or some kind of charity,'' he said, but called attention to
the U.S. voice in international lending organizations, with which
Poland desperately wants to reschedule its $39 billion debt.
   ``Many of the problems mired today may move much more quickly
with friendly American support,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890629-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 2017EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SexistShirts     06-29 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sexist Shirts,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students May Lose Their Sexist Shirts Under New Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at Tufts University can wear T-shirts with
raunchy messages in dorm rooms and on campus lawns, but not in
classrooms under a new policy that officials said Thursday tries to
balance free speech with decorum.
   ``We feel it's our obligation to say that there are no
constituencies that are fair game,'' said Dean of Students Bobbie
Knable.
   The T-shirt zones were created after a male student marketed 200
T-shirts that gave 15 reasons ``Why Beer is Better than Women at
Tufts,'' all disparaging to women. One of the more printable lines
was ``Hangovers go away.''
   ``There were complaints about it,'' Knable said. The T-shirt
dealer was placed on probation and sentenced to 50 hours of
community service, which was later revoked. Officials of the private
liberal arts school then decided to draft a policy curtailing the
bodily display of hostile or derogatory slogans.
   The new rules, which take effect this fall, could involve some
fast changing. For instance, a student might wear a risque T-shirt
in his own room, then cover up the offending portion on his walk
through the dormitory common area before reaching the campus lawn, a
free area.
   But Knable says the circuitous policy stems from efforts to
comply with free speech rights.
   Students in classrooms or dormitory common areas can't escape
looking at the offending message, so the T-shirts are banned, she
said. But dormitory rooms are private and general campus grounds
can't be controlled.
   ``We didn't expect that we could protect our students from all of
the manifestations of bigotry or prejudice,'' Knable said.
   The writing of the policy stirred lively debate on campus. The
final decision on what constitutes a derogatory slogan will be made
on a case-by-case basis, she said.
   ``We really tried to narrow the definition (of offensive) to
derogatory and demeaning,'' Knable said. ``There are a lot of ideas
that people will encounter on campuses in a diverse community that
will be offensive to them and we are not trying to protect people
from ideas,'' she said.
   Knable said the policy is intended to be more of a deterrent than
a disciplinary tool. If complaints are lodged with the dean of
students, the matter will be taken to a panel of faculty and
students. Possible penalties might be probation or community service.
   Knable said officials at Tufts, known for its foreign policy
department, don't expect to have to enforce their penalty frequently
this fall.
   ``It's not as if we are a campus in which we expect the most
virulent kind of things will happen and happen frequently, it's just
that we are still a part of the world,'' she said.
</TEXT>
