<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0670 to restore cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Defeats Measure To Cut Aid For Philippines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House of Representatives voted Thursday to
uphold $1 billion in U.S. aid for an international effort to help
the Philippines, defeating a motion to cut the money by 60 percent.
   The action was taken during debate of a $23 billion, two-year
foreign aid bill, but its future was uncertain in light of delays by
the Senate in crafting its version of the foreign aid authorization.
   An amendment by Rep. Toby Roth, R-Wis., _ defeated 233-185 _
urged the House to limit the U.S. commitment to the Multinational
Aid Initiative (AID) to $400 million over two years, rather than $1
billion for an indefinite period as requested by the Bush
administration.
   Japan is expected to be the largest donor to the international
effort _ a project designed to ease the economic straits of Corazon
Aquino's fragile democratic government.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III will represent the United
States at an international conference on Philippines economy in
Tokyo next week.
   ``If the Roth amendment is adopted, Secretary Baker will be
humiliated before all the other countries,'' said Rep. Stephen
Solarz, D-N.Y., a supporter of the aid plan.
   A cut in the U.S. commitment ``would pull the rug out from under
our efforts to get other countries'' on board the project, Solarz
added. It would also endanger democracy in the Philippines, where
Communist rebels are waging a guerrilla war to unseat the
government, he said.
   Roth argued that a large sum for the Philippines was
inappropriate at a time when U.S. domestic spending was being
reduced and the U.S. national debt was at a record high.
</TEXT>
