<HEAD>Blaha Named to Shuttle Crew; Replaces Astronaut Killed in Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air Force Col. John E. Blaha, who made his
first space flight last March, was named Thursday to be in the crew
of a secret military shuttle mission scheduled for November. He
replaces S. David Griggs, who was killed in Arkansas while stunt
flying.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration said Blaha, 46,
will be the pilot in the four-man, one-woman crew commanded by Air
force Col. Frederick D. Gregory. The others have been training since
November last year.
   Griggs, a rear admiral in the Navy reserve, was killed June 17
when his plane crashed while he was flying aerobatics.
   Blaha had previously been assigned to be the pilot for an August
1990 science mission. He will be replaced on that crew by Air Force
Maj. Sidney M. Gutierrez, who has not been in space before.
