<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle-StarWars     06-29 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle-Star Wars,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Says SDI Will Help, Not Hurt Missile Reduction Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle said Thursday the
Strategic Defense Initiative will help, not hinder, U.S.-Soviet
efforts to curb long-range offensive missiles.
   Quayle criticized as ``misguided'' the House Armed Services
Committee's recommendation for a $1.1 billion cut in President
Bush's requested $4.6 billion budget for SDI.
   Quayle said the U.S. space-based defense shield could help the
two sides make progress toward a START treaty in Geneva ``and
facilitate its ratification by the Senate.''
   Quayle, in a speech to the American Defense Preparedness
Association, said the proliferation of ballistic missile launching
capability among smaller, less stable nations also makes it all the
more essential for the United States to develop and deploy strategic
defenses.
   ``The more progress we make toward offensive reductions, th more
we will need to rely on SDI to help us deter, or deal with, possible
Soviet cheating or breakout,'' Quayle said.
   ``SDI is an insurance policy for START,'' the vice president said.
   And it ``provides the American people with much-needed insurance
against an acidental or inadvertent attack or against a deliberate
launch by an irrational government,'' he said.
</TEXT>
