<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 2316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-HongKong     06-29 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Hong Kong,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Wants Chinese Troops Out of Central Hong Kong After 1997</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain will argue vigorously that China should
keep its army out of central Hong Kong after the colony reverts to
Chinese sovereignty in 1997, a British official said Thursday.
   The senior official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, briefed
reporters as Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe prepared to travel
to Hong Kong on Saturday to reaffirm Britain's commitment to the
colony.
   Howe's schedule during his three-day visit includes meetings with
officials and residents.
   Concern among Hong Kong's population of 5.7 million about life
under Chinese rule has increased since June 3, when the Chinese
government ordered thousands of troops into Beijing to crush the
seven-week pro-democracy movement.
   ``We shall be arguing very strongly that it would be very
misguided of China to put their troops in the center of Hong Kong,''
the British official said.
   Under the 1984 Joint Declaration, the British pact with China
that guarantees at least 50 years of autonomy for Hong Kong under
Chinese rule, authorities in Hong Kong are responsible for public
order.
   ``This is not the responsibility of people in khaki uniforms.
That is what we have to underline in thick, thick ink,'' the
official said.
   Chinese troops stationed in Hong Kong have to abide by Hong Kong
law, the official added.
   He said the questions of how many Chinese troops would be allowed
in Hong Kong and where they would be stationed are still subject to
negotiation.
   Britain will raise the issues during the next round of talks on
Hong Kong. Britain postponed the July meeting because of the
crackdown on the pro-democracy movement.
   ``No decision has been made on when the meetings will be resumed
but I would think certainly before the end of the year, maybe in the
autumn,'' the official said.
   Under the Joint Declaration, meetings are to be held three times
a year and Britain plans to stick ``to the letter of the agreement,
if we want China to do the same,'' the official said.
   Since the crackdown began, some Hong Kong residents have called
for the Joint Declaration to be torn up.
   The official said Britain has no intention of doing that but
wants to change a few things in a draft constitution under which
China will govern capitalist Hong Kong as a ``special administrative
region'' after the British withdraw.
   The Times of London quoted a report by the powerful House of
Commons foreign affairs committee as saying the British government
should mobilize an international effort to resettle Hong Kong
residents should China violate the Joint Declaration.
   The committee recommends that limited categories of residents be
given the right to settle in Britain, but rejects such rights for
all 3.25 million British passport holders, the newspaper said.
   The report, to be published Friday, also calls for an
acceleration of the timetable for introducing democracy in the
colony so it is firmly established before 1997, The Times said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890629-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush Bjt   06-29 0984</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, Bjt,980</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says He'll Work to Raise Congress' Pay, Revamp Campaign Financing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, reviving a topic buried by
public outcry four months ago, promised Thursday to work with
Congress to get members a pay raise. He didn't say how big the raise
should be.
   In a speech focused on another prickly issue _ campaign finance
reform _ the president mentioned the pay-hike question only briefly.
   He said he would send Congress legislation in a few days seeking
to ban the outside income senators and representatives earn from
speaking engagements, a restriction many have said they would accept
only if accompanied by higher salaries.
   Bush said he would ``work with Congress on the development of
details for increasing the pay of those in Congress as well as other
senior employees of the executive branch.''
   He already has endorsed a 25 percent pay increase for judges, and
the legislation he sends to Capitol Hill on outside income will
include a specific increase amount for senior officials, White House
counsel Boyden Gray said. He refused to disclose the amount.
   Bush described his campaign finance package _ which includes
provisions to abolish most political action committees _ as an
effort to cut special interest influence in politics and make
campaigns more fair by decreasing the significant advantages of
incumbents.
   Since a majority of incumbents are Democratic, however, the
proposals have the effect of helping the Republican Party's chances
to improve its standing.
   ``We need reforms that curtail special interest influence,
enhance the role of the individual and strengthen the parties,''
Bush said to an audience of congressional interns. ``We must do more
to truly clean up the system.''
   His proposals also include curtailing congressional franking
privileges, which he said ``pay for mass mailings that amount to
political advertising,'' and doing away with gerrymandering, the
drawing of crazy-quilt congressional districts to help certain
candidates.
   The president declined to endorse public financing of
congressional campaigns or overall spending limits, which have been
urged by Democratic officials as well as private groups.
   Democratic National Committee Chairman Ronald H. Brown said that
in failing to call for spending limits, ``the president's campaign
finance bill ought to be labeled the Fat Cat Protection Act of 1989.
He wants to make it easier to give Republican candidates access to
big money contributors.''
   Bob Dreyfuss, spokesman for the advocacy group Public Citizen,
said that in dismissing public financing and spending limits, Bush
``tends to really allow the people with money to have undue
influence in politics.''
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., has already promised the
House will produce an ethics and campaign reform package this
session, and he said Bush was joining the bandwagon late.
   ``I want to say this as kindly as I can: We welcome the
president's involvement, but he is not leading this matter. He is
joining an issue which the Democrats and the congressional
Republicans ... have been participating in, and actively, since the
first of the year,'' he said.
   Bush said public financing would exclude individuals from the
political process by denying them the opportunity to contribute, and
spending limits would discourage them from contributing.
   Congress has repeatedly rejected proposals for campaign finance
changes. But Republican supporters from Capitol Hill said they hoped
Bush's leadership and heightened public opinion on the issue would
change that this time around.
   Bush proposed to bar corporations, unions and trade associations
from financially sponsoring political action committees, effectively
abolishing most of the PACs that contributed more than $151 million
to congressional candidates in the 1987-88 election cycle.
   That move, Bush said, would help ``free our electoral system from
the grip of special interests.''
   He also proposed:
   _Reducing the per-candidate contribution limit for the remaining
PACs from the current $5,000 to $2,500.
   _Banning a practice known as ``bundling'' in which a group
gathers individuals' contributions and delivers them to candidates,
rather than having the individual donate directly.
   _Requiring full disclosure of ``soft money'' contributions and
spending.
   ``Soft money'' refers generally to corporate and labor money that
is barred for federal candidates but finds its want into the system
when the funds are contributed to political parties, which then help
the candidates.
   Touching on an area that has bedeviled the Federal Election
Commission for three years with no resolution, Bush called for
guidelines on how to differentiate between such money and funds
raised within federal standards for generic activity such as voter
registration and get-out-the-vote efforts that benefit both federal
and non-federal candidates.
   Bush would decrease the advantage of incumbents by:
   _Restricting franking privileges, which allow members of Congress
to send mail to their constituents free. Blanket constituency
mailings and newsletters, for instance, would be banned.
   _Curtailing gerrymandering methods of drawing political district
lines to benefit one political party or group over another. The
districts would have to be drawn according to geographical and
community boundaries, said a senior administration official.
   ``No single factor is more important in restoring competitive
elections,'' Bush said, than doing away with the crazy quilt
district maps that have been drawn in some states to group voters in
a blocks that benefit one party.
   The redistricting is controlled by state legislatures, 28 of
which are controlled by Democrats to eight by Republicans. Thirteen
are split, and Nebraska has a nonpartisan one-chamber legislature.
   _More than doubling the amount of money that political parties
are allowed to give to their candidates for House and Senate. For
Senate races, the amount currently ranges from $92,000 to some $1.5
million, depending on state population. Since incumbents are able to
attract far more money than challengers in private contributions;
this provision would mean more to the cash-strapped GOP challengers.
   _Banning carrying over campaign funds from one election to the
next, thus requiring congressional candidates to return leftover
funds to the contributors or give the money to the political parties
or the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
