<SECOND>AM-Blood Fraud,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Doctor Sentenced for $3.7 Million Medicaid Scam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former doctor convicted in a $3.7 million
Medicaid fraud has been sentenced to five to 10 years in prison.
   Surinder Singh Panshi also was ordered to pay $300,000 in
restitution by the trial judge, Supreme Court Justice Herbert A.
Posner, at the sentencing Wednesday. He pleaded guilty in March to
127 felony counts.
   Panshi and his father, Gurdial Singh Panshi, along with eight
other people and three medical laboratories controlled by Panshi,
were indicted in August.
   Panshi, 40, set up companies that collected blood from the
down-and-out for $10 a pint and used each pint to generate as much
as $2,000 in Medicaid billings for expensive but unnecessary, said
Edward J. Kuriansky, the state's special prosecutor for Medicaid
fraud.
   Three salesmen had entered guilty pleas before Panshi and
received sentences ranging from five years on probation to as much
as 4{ years in prison, plus a total of $495,000 in restitution.
   Panshi's father and five other defendants are fugitives,
Kuriansky said.
