<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 2321EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     06-29 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Asks That Indian Troops Stop Fighting Tamil Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa, unable
to get India to withdraw its peacekeeping troops, now has asked that
they stop fighting Tamil rebels.
   Premadasa made the appeal the day after his government and the
Tamil Tigers, the main rebel group, agreed to stop fighting.
   At least 40,000 Indian soldiers are stationed in the
Tamil-dominated north and east under a civil war peace plan India
worked out in 1987 with the last president, Junius Jayewardene.
   Continued deployment of the Indian troos has become a contentious
issue between Colombo and New Delhi.
   Last month, Premadasa asked India to withdraw by the end of July,
but India refused. Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's government said a
hasty withdrawal could lead to even more ethnic violence.
   A government statement issued Thursday said: ``The president of
Sri Lanka has ... requested the prime minister of India to ensure''
that the Indian peacekeeping force ``does not take any action
against the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam.''
   Other militant Tamil groups, who gave up the fight for a separate
state in exchange for limited autonomy, support the Indian presence.
   Arthur Ranasinghe, deputy information minister, told reporters:
``If Indian troops refuse to leave by the end of next month, we will
send them back. India might bomb us or destroy all of us, but we
will fight back to the last man.
   ``If India tries to be here by force, without our consent and the
consent of our people, we will not tolerate it.''
   Tamils, nearly all of whom are Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people and claim discrimination by the majority
Sinhalese, most of whom are Buddhists.
   Militants began fighting in 1083 for an independent Tamil
homeland called Eelam in the north and east. More than 10,000 people
have been killed in the civil war and in violance by Sinhalese
extremists who want no concessions to Tamils.
   India became involved because it is the major power in the
region, is overwhelmingly Hindu and has a Tamil population of 60
million concentrated across the Palk Strait from Sri Lanka.
   The soldiers were deployed in July 1987 to accept the surrender
of arms by the rebels, but the Tamil Tigers refused to go along with
the peace plan.
   Talks between the Tigers and the government began last month
after Premadasa offered amnesty to Tamil rebels who gave up their
weapons.
   On Wednesday, the rebels and government announced an agreement to
stop fighting and settle their differences by negotiation.
</TEXT>
