<DOCNO> AP890629-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1720EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-OilBan     06-29 0868</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Ban,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Committee Approves Moratorium on Coastal Oil Exploration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation calling for a year-long moratorium
on oil exploration along vast stretches off America's coast _
including New England and Alaska _ won approval Thursday from a key
House committee where members repeatedly cited concern about
possible oil spills.
   The Bush administration immediately promised to fight the curbs,
probably in the Senate, saying mandatory prohibitions on off-shore
oil exploration would stifle badly needed domestic petroleum
development.
   ``We believe they (congressionally-imposed bans) are a delaying
tactic,'' said Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan.
   The action by the House Appropriations Committee on a fiscal 1990
spending bill for the Interior Department would put a temporary halt
to oil exploration in Alaska's Bristol Bay, one of the nation's
premier fishing centers, where the government already has sold a
half dozen exploratory leases for $94 million.
   The legislation also would extend or impose prohibitions on oil
or gas exploration off California, off the Everglades of
southwestern Florida, in the Georges Bank off New England, and along
a 50-mile wide coastal strip that stretches from Rhode Island to
Maryland.
   ``This is a critical victory at a critical time,'' said Rep. Leon
Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the House Budget Committee. ``The
message is clear. We will not tolerate more tragic oil spills.''
   An exploratory drilling moratorium already has been in effect on
leases in many of those areas, but the ban would be extended to the
center coast of California and to the mid-Atlantic region under the
legislation. It also would ensure that no exploratory activity is
taken before October 1990, the end of the next fiscal year.
   The $11.6 billion Interior money bill, which prohibits any money
being spent on oil lease in the areas cited, cleared the House
committee by a voice vote after two amendments aimed at softening
the impact of the oil exploration moratorium were defeated by votes
of 29-22 and 28-22.
   The first amendment would have deleted reference to Bristol Bay,
while the second would have allowed a variety of ``pre-lease''
activities off the California coast, although actual exploratory
drilling would still have been put on hold.
   Opponents of the Bristol Bay drilling ban argued that oil
development in the pristine Alaska waters _ home for a $1 billion
fishing industry _ is needed to keep America free of having to
depend increasingly on oil imports.
   ``What we're doing in the name of the environment is cutting off
our energy sources ... We're going to have brown-outs and then there
will be black-outs,'' argued Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La.
   Rep. Ralph Regula, R-Ohio, maintained that the danger from oil
spills was not from off-shore drilling, but from tanker traffic,
prompting Rep. Sidney Yates, D-Ill., to point out that tankers
likely will transport the oil that would come from Bristol Bay.
   Yates, chairman of the Interior subcommittee that had recommended
the moratorium, cited the devastation left by the Exxon Valdez oil
spill last March.
   ``We've seen what's happend in Prince William Sound,'' declared
Yates, adding that the same potential for damage is present in other
coastal areas.
   Rep. Silvio Conte, R-Mass., described having on numerous
occasions gone fishing off the southern Alaska coast and said the
oil damage from the Exxon spill ``brings tears to my eyes.''
   ``We've got to wait,'' declared Conte in arguing for a moratrium
on further off-shore oil exploration.
   Alaska's congressional delegation and its governor have strongly
urged for a temporary halt in oil exploration in Bristol Bay in
light of the Exxon spill until greater assurances can be made that
the environment will be protected.
   ``If the Exxon Valdez oil spill proved one thing, it's that the
current ability to respond to spills in open seas is inadequate at
best,'' said Alaska Gov. Steve Cowper in praising the House
committee action.
   ``I'm not willing to roll the dice on development in Bristol Bay
and threaten the livelihood of hundrds of Alaskans and the resources
on which they depend,'' the governor said in a statement issued in
Juneau.
   The Interior Deparment sold exploratory leases for a half dozen
sites in Bristol Bay last year. The legislation would call for
repurchasing those leases. The bay is considered by experts to be
even more vulnerable to pollution from an oil spill than Prince
William Sound.
   ``This is no less than a major victory for the environment,''
said Lisa Speer of the Natural Resources Defense Counsel, a private
environmental group, reacting to the House committee action.
   But Interior's Lujan maintained that the moratorium on offshore
drilling does little ``to address the real issue'' which is tanker
safety, while it could stifle domestic oil development.
   An Interior spokesman, Steve Goldstein, said that Lujan intends
to personally campaign to overturn the moratorium provisions in the
House bill in the coming weeks.
   President Bush earlier this year ordered lease sales off Southern
and Northern California as well as off southwestern Florida
postponed, pending an environmental review. A report on that review
is to be issued to the president by the end of the year.
   After that, oil exploration would be free to continue if given
the goahead by Interior, unless Congress determines otherwise.
</TEXT>
