<FIRST>u w AM-HUD-Buffalo 1stLd-Writethru   06-29 0851</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Buffalo, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0661,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Probe: Buffalo Broker Kept Thousands</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, ``Richard Tyksinski,'' with 2 grafs bgng: ``But
Joseph,'' to UPDATE with comment from manager of Buffalo HUD office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A onetime broker for the Department of Housing
and Urban Development in Buffalo, N.Y., withheld payments,
overbilled and paid himself advances, so when he died in 1987 he
owed the department almost $73,000, according to a federal audit.
   After Bernard A. Brady died, his widow continued to withdraw
money from his HUD escrow account, according to the audit, obtained
under the Freedom of Information Act.
   Brady had been a closing agent on the sale of single-family HUD
homes and manager of at least one HUD rental property, said the
audit by HUD's office of inspector general. He died May 10, 1987,
but while the audit was being conducted, his widow, Maureen, somehow
withdrew $20,100 from the HUD account in her husband's name, said A.
Paul Kane, HUD's regional inspector general for audit, who oversaw
the probe.
   ``We don't know whether she was forging the checks ... or whether
they had a book of pre-signed checks,'' Kane said in an interview
from HUD's Region II office in New York City.
   Brady had comingled personal and HUD funds in the account, Kane
said Thursday. No criminal charges against Mrs. Brady are
anticipated since she recently agreed through her lawyer to pay the
$24,832 HUD says she and her husband's estate owe, Kane said.
   ``We expect to get it all back,'' he said.
   The escrow account was eventually frozen, but HUD has been unable
to get at the money, believed to be $48,139, according to Kane. The
audit was completed Jan. 19 and covered the period from Jan. 1,
1985, to Dec. 31, 1987.
   ``We've been trying to find out from the field office whether or
not the money has been turned over. We haven't been able to get an
answer,'' Kane said.
   But Joseph B. Lynch, manager of the Buffalo field office, said
Thursday the bank has finally agreed to turn over the money,
although it is not clear when.
   ``The auditors ... had some difficulty in getting the bank
initially to release the accounts and canceled checks and finally we
had to resort to a subpoena,'' he said. ``The reason became apparent
later on. When this Mr. Brady died, a death certificate was
submitted to the bank and his widow continued to draw down on that
account, apparently forging his name on some checks. So there was
some liability on the part of th bank, that's our feeling.''
   Kane blamed the field office for not keeping closer tabs on what
Brady was doing, and said it was the lawyer for the Brady estate,
Harold Fein, who brought the bank account problems to the local
office's attention. The field office then called in the inspector
general, Kane said.
   ``The amount of activity involved with Brady was not that great
so it was not likely for us to look at him if it had not been
brought to our attention,'' Kane said.
   Fein did not immediately return a phone call Thursday.
   Brady was not alone in using HUD money as if it were his own
during the laissez-faire administration of housing Secretary Samuel
Pierce. Cases are turning up almost daily where HUD accountants,
brokers and others apparently misused or stole millions of dollars
from the department.
   Bernard A. Brady, a lifelong Buffalo resident, had been in
business for himself for 32 years, as a fee appraiser for the
Federal Housing Administration, an expert witness for the courts, an
apartment manager for a HUD-owned property and from 1974 to 1981, a
HUD management agent, according to his obituary in The Buffalo News.
He was 58 when he died.
   Brady also appraised real estate for the state Department of
Transportation, a bank, Surrogates Court and the city of Buffalo. He
attended the University of Buffalo law school.
   As a HUD closing agent and broker, according to the federal
audit, Brady:
   _Did not turn over $97,371 from the sale of six HUD-owned
single-family houses.
   _Did not forward to HUD $12,407 in rental income collected from
tenants in a HUD-owned property.
   _Overcharged HUD $2,460 for wire transfers, sometimes
triple-billing the agency for wires never sent.
   _Wrote checks from the HUD account either to himself or his wife
totaling almost $44,000.
   According to the audit, 18 checks totaling $20,100 and payable to
Mrs. Brady were drawn from the account after Brady's death, the
investigation found.
   For the 18 months from April 1985 to September 1986, Brady did
not submit a single monthly accounting report to the department, as
required under his contract.
   At the same time as he was shortchanging HUD, Brady was not paid
some $26,000 in monthly management fees from the department, the
audit found. He also wired the same $12,500 in net sales proceeds
twice to the U.S. Treasury. And he overpaid HUD several hundred
dollars in other cases.
   Subtracting what HUD owed Brady, the auditors concluded that
Brady owed the department $72,970.66.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
