<FIRST>r w AM-Woods 1stLd-Writethru a0675 06-29 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Woods, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>AID Administrator Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 6th graf bgng, Woods, whose xxx, to CORRECT time when Woods
served as aide to governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alan Woods, administrator of the Agency for
International Development (AID) in the Reagan and Bush
administrations and a strong advocate of linking U.S. assistance to
economic reform, died Thursday of cancer at the age of 43.
   He was also a former deputy U.S. trade representative and a
proponent of open trade policies.
   In one of his last appearances, Woods on May 12 argued for
concentrating U.S. aid assistance on what he called ``sustainable
development.'' Instead of being given away, Woods said, aid should
be a temporary bridge to private support and ``self-sustained
growth.''
   In the trade post, which Woods held from 1985 to 1987, he was the
Reagan administration's chief strategist in dealing with Congress on
trade legislation and the lead negotiator with Canada on lumber and
also on U.S. market access to Portugal and Spain.
   Then at AID, beginning in 1987, Woods promoted market-oriented
economic policies, believing they and open trade held the key to
progress, in developed and undeveloping countries alike.
   Woods, whose first name was Michael, was a native of Mexico, Mo.,
and served in 1973-74 as chief of staff for Christopher Bond, then
the governor of Missouri and now a U.S. senator.
   In the Nixon administration Woods was the deputy director of the
office of presidential personnel and later become assistant press
secretary. In the Ford administration he was a Pentagon spokesman
and an adviser on the budget.
   His wife, Cameron, and two young daugters, Alexandra and
Caroline, survive him, as well as his parents, Donald and Darlene
Woods of Mexico, Mo.
</TEXT>
