<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1746EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Legislature     06-29 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Legislature,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislators Grill Cabinet Nominees About Pollution, Shortages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cabinet nominees, who used to need only Kremlin
approval, were quizzed and harangued by the rambunctious new Soviet
legislature Thursday on matters ranging from the toilet paper and
soap shortages to pollution.
   After questioning and debate, the 542-member Supreme Soviet
approved Alexandra P. Biryukova as a deputy premier in charge of the
government social agency and Vladimir K. Gusev as a deputy premier
overseeing chemicals and timber. Both were incumbents.
   Ms. Biryukova, head of the Bureau for Social Development since
October, faced questions about why women so often are given
physically demanding jobs and put on the night shift.
   Women fill many menial jobs in the Soviet Union, from shoveling
asphalt for road repairs to clearing the snow from Red Square in
winter.
   Lawmakers also complained about a shortage of furniture and
school supplies.
   Ms. Biryukova, the only woman in the top leadership, proposed
government aid to families with many children and said it was
necessary to get 3 million women off night shifts in various
industries.
   She said production of such basic consumer goods as soap and
toothpaste would be increased dramatically.
   ``Still, this is insufficient,'' she declared. ``We must return
again and again to the issue of increasing production of consumer
goods.''
   A shortage of disposable needles made headlines last year when
several dozen children were infected with AIDS in a hospital that
used unsterilized, non-disposable syringes. Ms. Biryukova said
production of disposable needles is being increased and they also
are being purchased abroad.
   Gusev, head of the Bureau for the Chemical and Timber Complex
since May 1988, was grilled for 1{ hours about why those industries
have not met production goals and are polluting the environment.
   ``I am not satisfied with my work,'' Gusev told the legislators.
``There are too many problems in the country due to our
deficiencies.''
   He said 85 percent of his agency's investment budget for
1990-1995 would be be used to modernize chemical factories and paper
mills and install anti-pollution devices. He said 47 percent of the
investment budget now goes for those purposes.
   Pollution and poor social conditions have been leading targets of
public complaint under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of
glasnost, or openness.
   Officials have said 50 million people, nearly one-fifth of the
population, live in cities in which air pollution exceeds acceptable
levels.
   Lawmakers also questioned Gusev about a paper shortage that
prevents the Soviet Union from publishing enough books or meeting
the demand for toilet paper.
   He said the paper industry lacks the equipment to increase
production, but is trying to expand capacity.
   Valentina S. Shevchenko, a legislator from the Ukraine, told
Gusev she had heard promises before and admonished: ``You must show
more character and be more demanding.''
   In defense of his nominee, Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov declared:
``The question isn't Gusev, it's chemicals (the agency). No matter
who we put in the job, the problems will remain.''
   Earlier this week, Ryzhkov withdrew seven Cabinet nominees the
Supreme Soviet found unacceptable.
   On Thursday, he asked legislators to focus less on personalities
and more on balancing the need for the chemical industry's products
with the environmental harm it causes.
   The Supreme Soviet, which replaced the old rubber-stamp
legislature this year, has approved six Cabinet nominees and is to
review more than 50 others during a session scheduled to run through
Aug. 4.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
