<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     06-29 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists Demand that Czechoslovakia Release Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prominent Czechoslovak rights activists
are demanding that their country release all political prisoners,
allow peaceful demonstrations and reassess the 1968 Soviet-led
invasion, emigre sources said Thursday.
   A source in Vienna said about 1,800 intellectuals, actors and
artists and many blue-collar workers signed an appeal urging the
Prague government to open a dialogue with people outside the
communist establishment.
   The document was issued in the name of four activists, including
banned playwright Vaclav Havel and Sasa Vondra, spokesman for the
Charter 77 human rights manifesto, according to the London-based
Palach Press newsletter and other sources.
   Havel was warned by secret police this week that he may be jailed
again for his activities, his brother Ivan Havel said Thursday in a
telephone interview from Prague. Ivan Havel said two security
officials warned his brother his activities could be construed as
incitement to rebellion.
   In an interview Havel gave to Hungarian television, broadcast
Wednesday night, the playwright criticized Prague's reluctance to
embrace reform.
   Havel was freed on probation May 17 midway through an eight-month
jail sentence that drew protests at home and abroad.
   In Prague, Czechoslovakia's official CTK news agency reported
Thursday that police arrested four people, accusing them of
organizing terrorism, arson and murder and having ``close relations
with independent initiatives.''
   CTK identified the four only as being ``in their 40s'' and said
they reportedly directed and organized a group of youngsters,
allegedly ``setting several industrial targets on fire on Czech
territory since 1986 and killing a 17-year old person in connection
with this criminal activity.''
   The appeal signed by the activists demanded ``a free discussion
... to review not only the 1950s but also the Prague Spring, the
invasion of Czechoslovakia by the five armies of the Warsaw Pact,
and the process of `normalization'' which followed.''
   The Czechoslovak leadership, still suspicious of Kremlin-style
political reforms, has refused to re-examine the 1968 reforms
introduced in the ``Prague Spring'' and the Soviet-led invasion that
crushed the reforms. The invasion is officially still described as a
necessary action to defend socialism.
   The sponsors also proposed that ``1. all political prisoners be
released immediately, 2. that restrictions on freedom of assembly be
lifted'' and that the government stop persecution of independent
initiatives, according to the text released in London and Vienna.
   It demanded an end to political manipulation and censorship in
the news media and religious freedom.
   It urged authorities to submit to expert and public review all
projects ``which are designed to change permanently the environment
of our country and are thus likely to condition the lives of future
generations.''
   This was an apparent reference to the huge hydropower project
near Gabcikovo in Czechoslovakia nearing completion. Prague refuses
to discuss the issue with independent critics and environmentalists.
</TEXT>
