<SECOND>AM-Obit-Bialkowski,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rector of Warsaw University Grzegorz Bialkowski Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grzegorz Bialkowski, rector of Warsaw
University and a Solidarity-backed senator in the National Assembly,
died Thursday, state media reported. He was 56.
   State television said he died of a heart attack.
   Bialkowski, a respected physicist and poet, studied at Warsaw
University and spent his entire working career there.
   Active in opposition causes despite his position as the top
academic official at the state-run institution, he maintained good
relations with the banned pro-Solidarity Independent Students
Association and offered university facilities for such events as an
Independent Culture Forum last spring.
   On June 4, he was elected to the Poland's new Senate in the East
bloc's first fully democratic election since World War II,
representing the central province of Piotrkow. However, he never was
sworn in as a senator.
   The senate, in which 99 of the 100 members elected were backed by
Solidarity, is expected to convene for the first time next week.
   He also was a participant in the historic negotiations that led
to the legalization of Solidarity after a seven-year ban and the
holding of the elections.
   Solidarity deputies and senators have been meeting on the
university grounds in recent weeks to prepare for the upcoming
session of the legislature.
