<FIRST>u w AM-Democrats-CampaignReform 540   06-29 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats-Campaign Reform, 540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Campaign Finance Proposal PR, Democrats Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats charged Thursday that President
Bush's campaign finance proposals were designed for public relations
and would do more to help Republican candidates than accomplish
meaningful reform.
   ``The president's campaign finance bill ought to be labeled the
Fat Cat Protection Act of 1989,'' said Democratic National Committee
Chairman Ronald H. Brown, referring to the lack of campaign spending
limits in the proposal.
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., also criticized Bush.
   ``While I welcome the president's willingness to join our ongoing
reform efforts, I regret that he has chosen to submit proposals that
blatantly favor the Republican Party and jeopardize bipartisan
(reform) efforts already under way,'' Foley said.
   Bush said in a speech Thursday that he was proposing a plan to
``clean up the system'' of congressional elections, with
restrictions on political action committees and benefits enjoyed by
incumbent members of Congress.
   Because a majority of incumbents are Democratic, the proposals
have the effect of helping the Republican Party's chances to improve
its standing.
   Democrats, while welcoming what they called a tardy interest in
the issue by the top man in the GOP, charged that Bush's plan was a
transparent attempt to hurt the Democrats who control Congress by
skewing the political finance system toward Republican fund-raising
strengths.
   ``A totally partisan package has been set forward,'' said Rep.
Beryl Anthony, D-Ark., chairman of the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee.
   Anthony called it ``a P.R. effort on the part of the president''
that ``appears to have been written by (Republican national
chairman) Lee Atwater and (GOP House campaign chief) Ed Rollins.''
   However, Anthony said some elements in the president's package
would find favor with Democrats, such as rules requiring fairness in
redistricting of House seats and more disclosure of ``soft money'' _
corporate and labor contributions given to candidate through back
channel loopholes in the law.
   Bush proposed restricting political action committees, but
Democrats said that only the type of PACs that tend to help
Democrats would be curtailed.
   The president also suggested more money would be channeled
through the political parties _ a move away from public disclosure
of campaign contributions.
   ``This really just sets up another `hide-and-go-seek' game,''
said Rep. Al Swift, D-Wash., co-chairman of the House task force
that has been studying campaign reform proposals.
   But Swift said Bush's participation might help increase chances
of action on a campaign reform bill.
   Democrats repeatedly pointed out that it was Senate Republicans
who killed chances for a campaign reform bill in the last Congress.
   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., sponsor of last year's reform package,
said he hoped the president's proposals would ``break the stalemate
in the Senate on this important issue.''
   But, Boren said in his statement, Bush's proposal was deficient
because it did nothing to limit the amount of money that could be
spent on an election campaign.
   ``We cannot have real reform unless we address the runaway costs
of congressional elections,'' he said.
   ``Without spending limits, all you do is turn elections into
auctions,'' said Rep. David Obey, D-Wis. ``I think what the
president is doing is posing for political holy pictures on this
issue.''
</TEXT>
