<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Cyprus     06-29 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Cyprus,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cyprus Reunification Talks End without Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the Greek and Turkish ethnic
communities on Cyprus ended a fourth round of unsuccessful
reunification talks Thursday and agreed to prepare a draft
settlement before another try in September.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, who acted as mediator,
issued a statement saying new ideas had ``offered a real possibility
of bridging the positions of the two sides and made a just and
lasting agreement possible. ... This effort could be brought to an
early and successful conclusion.''
   He invited President George Vassiliou of Cyprus and the Turkish
Cypriot leader, Rauf Denktash, to meet with him again in September
``to consider the completed outline and to launch the negotiation of
an overall agreement.''
   Perez de Cuellar said the two leaders pledged their cooperation
in completing the outline of a draft agreement before the next
meeting.
   Vassiliou and Denktash spent nearly four hours with the U.N.
chief executive, and both described the talks as productive.
   Little progress has been made since negotiations began last
August. The outline agreement now due in September originally was
intended to be ready for this meeting.
   The purpose is to form a federated state on the eastern
Mediterranean island. Cyprus was divided when Turkey invaded in July
1974, with the stated purpose of protecting the ethnic Turkish
minority, after a short-lived coup against the late President
Makarios led by Greek army officers.
   Denktash has declared an independent state in the northern 37
percent of the island occupied by Turkish troops. The state,
recognized only by Turkey, has only 120,000 people, about 18 percent
of the island's total.
</TEXT>
