<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 2324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Stars&amp;Stripes 320   06-29 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stars &amp; Stripes, 320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Washington Post Editor Named Stars &amp; Stripes Ombudsman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former foreign editor for the Washington Post
was named Thursday as ombudsman for the Stars &amp; Stripes military
newspapers, a post created in response to allegations of censorship.
   Philip M. Foisie was executive editor of the International Herald
Tribune after spending 26 years at the Washington Post, including a
long stint as foreign editor.
   He is credited with originating the ombudsman position at the
Post.
   Foisie's job will be to monitor the journalistic performance of
the newspapers and to argue with military brass over news coverage
and decisions on behalf of reporters and editors.
   He also will be able to write a column, spotlighting errors or
discussing the manner in which news judgments are made. Foisie will
be paid about $70,000 a year, the Pentagon said.
   Stars and Stripes is published in two separate editions by
largely autonomous bureaus in West Germany and Japan. Designed to
serve as the ``hometown paper'' for American servicemen overseas,
the papers have a history that dates to World War I.
   The papers are staffed by military and civilian journalists, but
both are led by an officer who holds the title of commander and
editor-in-chief. Those officers answer to the heads of the European
and Pacific Commands.
   The Pentagon describes the papers as ``authorized, but unofficial
publications.'' Both operate under a charter to provide ``a free
flow of news and information ... without censorship or news
management.''
   However, reporters who have worked for the papers say they must
walk a tightrope between reporting the news and satisfying military
commanders who are worried about sensitivities in the host country.
   General Accounting Office officials testified before a House
subcommittee in February on an investigation of the two newspapers,
saying they had found that military commanders and their
representatives ``have attempted to influence the reporting of
news.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890629-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 2101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Shoreham-Congress     06-29 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shoreham-Congress,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Committee Passes Amendment That Would Block Shoreham Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Energy and Commerce Committee passed
an amendment Thursday aimed at blocking the closure of a new but
unused nuclear power plant on Long Island.
   The amendment, introduced by Rep. Don Ritter, R-Pa., was approved
23-19 and attached to a bill renewing the basic legal authority of
the Nuclear Regulatory Commission. The legislation must still be
passed by the full House and the Senate.
   Ritter's provision would ban the planned transfer of the
operating license of the plant to a new local agency, the Long
Island Power Authority.
   Ritter said after the vote, ``LIPA was brought into being for the
express purpose of shutting down the Shoreham plant, which has been
judged to be safe by the Nuclear Regulatory Commission, and the
authority is totally unqualified to engage in the decommissioning of
a nuclear plant.''
   However, the license could be transferred to ``a competent
authority,'' such as the New York Power Authority, according to John
Hambel, a committee spokesman.
   But the amendment forbids the NRC from spending funds to
decommission the plant unless the plant is certified unsafe, he said.
   ``The NRC authorization hasn't made it across the president's
desk in five years,'' said Peter Coogan, a spokesman for Rep. George
Hochbrueckner, D-N.Y., whose district includes Shoreham.
   Hambel said chances are good that the amendment will be picked up
by the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee and attached to
legislation sure to pass.
   Voicing strong support for the House amendment Thursday was Rep.
Norman F. Lent, ranking Republican on the Energy and Commerce
Committee and a longtime Shoreham supporter.
   He said consumers ``would be spared the whopping 63 percent rate
hike proposed by Gov. (Mario) Cuomo that would arise as a direct
result of the decommissioning of Shoreham.''
   The amendment passed one day after shareholders of the Long
Island Lighting Co. approved a deal to close Shoreham. Under the
agreement, the company would sell the unused will unused $5.5
billion reactor to New York state for $1 in exchange for a decade of
5 percent annual rate increases. Shoreham's license would be
transferred to the new Long Island Power Authority, which would then
contract with the New York Power Authority, operator of other
nuclear plants, to decommission Shoreham.
</TEXT>
