<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 2101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BeachJunk     06-29 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beach Junk,375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coastlines are Littered with Plastic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's coastlines are littered with
plastic from cups to trash bags, an environmental group said
Thursday after releasing a report on what volunteers found on more
than 3,000 miles of beaches.
   The Center for Marine Conservation said the assessment, made from
items collected by 47,000 volunteers, demonstrates that America's
beaches, ``once famous for their beauty and biological richness,''
now are often littered with trash.
   In addition to being unsightly, the ocean trash has become deadly
to marine life, the group said.
   ``Thousands of marine mammals, sea turtles, seabirds, and fish
die every year when entangled in debris such as rope, nets, and
fishing line, or from ingesting items like plastic bags and
sheeting, mistaking them for food,'' said the report.
   The group said that in combing more than 3,000 miles of beaches
in 20 states, the volunteers gathered nearly 1,000 tons of debris.
In all, nearly 2 million separate pieces of debris were found and
recorded, the report said.
   Despite the uproar about medical wastes, only a small percentage
of the items were reported in that category. The volunteers recorded
finding 1,718 plastic syringes during their searches, which account
for about 0.09 percent of all the debris found, said the report.
   There were other ``medical'' items found, including caps, gowns,
tubing and even a set of dentures, said Kathryn O'Hara, who
coordinated the project.
   By far the greatest amount of trash involved some sort of plastic
product: 78,025 plastic trash bags, 26,148 milk or water jugs,
19,300 plastic bleach cleaner bottles, 14,721 foam plastic trays,
and 9,526 egg cartons.
   Among the ``dirty dozen'' items, glass beverage bottles ranked
No. 6, with 95,028 bottles littering the beaches. That didn't
include another 65,819 ``glass pieces'' found in the sand and among
the rocks. There were also light bulbs, fluorescent light tubes,
wooden crates, assorted fishing lines, rubber gloves, fishing nets,
and 857 plastic hardhats.
   Some states had more trash than others.
   ``The amount of trash reported per mile of beach was consistently
higher in states bordering the Gulf of Mexico,'' said Ms. O'Hara.
   Here are the states where the most pounds of debris per miles of
beach were located: Georgia (4,000), Texas (3,549), and Louisiana
(2,337).
   The debris was collected in September and October of 1988 by
volunteers over a three-hour period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
