<DOCNO> AP890629-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 2102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Grenada     06-29 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grenada,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Autopsy Shows Diplomat Shot Twice In Back</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISTER HUGHES</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An autopsy found that a U.S.
diplomat killed in a shooting spree at police headquarters was shot
twice in the back, a government spokesman said Thursday.
   In addition to shooting John Butler, the U.S. Embassy's political
officer, on Wednesday, the assailant also killed Grenada's acting
police commissioner, Cosmus Raymond, and wounded two senior police
officials.
   The killer, Grafton Bascombe, acting assistant police
commissioner here, was later found dead in a police cell. Cause of
death was listed as cardiac arrest.
   Bascombe's motive remained unclear, but U.S. and Grenadan
officials said the incident had no political overtones.
   Grenada, a former British colony of about 100,000 people in the
southern Caribbean, has been politically stable since the island was
invaded in October 1983, by U.S. Marines and paratroopers, along
with a small Caribbean force. The invasion toppled a leftist junta
that had seized power in a bloody coup.
   The State Department said Wednesday in Washington that Butler was
shot ``point-blank in the heart'' after trying to subdue Bascombe .
   But Albert Xavier told a news conference Thursday a pathologist's
report showed Butler, 33, of Twentynine Palms, Calif., was struck by
two bullets, both of which entered from the back.
   ``The ... report suggests that Butler could not have been
attempting to restrain Bascombe,'' said Xavier, an adviser to Prime
Minister Herbert Blaize.
   Roy Sullivan, 56, the embassy's administrative officer who was
with Butler at a meeting, said he ``hit the floor'' when shooting
broke out and was unhurt. ``The last thing I remember was John
rising and going toward the guy who was wielding the pistol,''
Sullivan said.
   Butler's body was flown home Thursday.
   Officials said Bascombe killed Raymond and then burst into
another room and killed Butler and wounded Deputy Police
Commissioner Collis Barrow and Assistant Police Superintendent
Daniel Searles.
   They said Bascombe, 45, was previously assistant police
superintendent in neighboring St. Vincent island and was on loan to
Grenada police.
   Xavier said Bascombe's scheduled return to St. Vincent last week
was delayed because he had charge of funds involving a joint police
and military exercise and was to give Raymond an accounting
Wednesday.
   A government source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
about $25,000 was involved and it was not known if any discrepancies
had cropped up.
   Bascombe apparently surrended after the shooting. He later was
prounced dead in a police cell.
   Xavier said pathologist Robert Hannon gave cardiac arrest as
cause of death and said Bascombe also had suffered a concussion, an
unspecified wound above the left eye, and a bruised and cut left
cheek.
   Xavier said cardiac arrest was consistent with an examination
made by Bascombe's personal physician, who said Bascombe suffered
from an enlarged heart and high blood pressure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
