<FIRST>r p AM-CranstonFined     06-29 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cranston Fined,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>FEC Fines Cranston for Campaign Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., has been fined
for violating campaign finance laws in connection with his failed
1984 bid for the Democratic presidential nomination.
   The Federal Election Commission, which also levied fines against
Cranston's campaign and five individuals, said the campaign spent
too much in Iowa, accepted too much money from 77 people and one
political action committee, illegally accepted letters of credit
from six people and one corporation and failed to disclose those on
financial reports.
   In addition, the commission said Cranston put too much of his own
money into the campaign.
   The commission levied a $17,000 fine against Mark Weinberg, who
gave $55,000 to Cranston's campaign. Under federal law, an
individual can give no more than $1,000 to a particular campaign.
   The commission said Weinberg's violations were ``knowing and
willful.''
   The fines were imposed last month, but the files remained sealed
until this week. Under FEC practice, final disposition of a case is
reached when none of the parties involved dispute the facts and all
sides have agreed to the fines.
   The $50,000 fine was to be divided among Cranston, his campaign
and five other individuals.
   ``In the intensity of presidential elections, people working on
campaigns try, but experience shows do not always succeed, in
conforming with all the meticulous regulations of the Federal
Elections Commission,'' Cranston said in a statement Thursday.
   ``Nonetheless, I believe FEC regulations should be followed so
long as they remain in force. I was not involved in the day-to-day
administrative details of my presidential campaign. But as the
candidate, I take full responsibility for the actions of my campaign
and I deeply regret the violations of the rules.''
   Among the commission's findings:
   _The Cranston campaign spent $791,462 in Iowa, $106,924 more than
the legal limit.
   _Cranston spent $117,803 of his own money, while the limit is
$50,000 for candidates who accept matching funds from the federal
Treasury.
   _Cranston's campaign failed to itemize contributions toaling
$20,309 from 60 political action committees.
   _The campaign accepted excessive contributions from 77
individuals. No action was taken against them.
</TEXT>
