<FIRST>r w AM-VAStress     06-29 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-VA Stress,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>VA Expands Treatment Staff for Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Specialized teams to treat post-traumatic
stress disorder are being added at 23 of the VA's medical centers,
the Veterans Affairs Department said Thursday.
   The four-member teams, headed by a psychiatrist, will concentrate
on outpatient treatment, the agency said. Each team will also have
one clerk, with the other two members being chosen by the facility.
   ``This is a supplemental effort,'' said agency spokeswoman Donna
St. John. ``Treatment is available at the hospitals.''
   Post-traumatic stress is the Vietnam-era equivalent of what was
earlier called ``shell shock.'' The department says it affects 15.2
percent of male veterans of the conflict.
   It is characterized by recurrent thoughts of the trauma, reduced
involvement in work or outside interests, hyperalertness, anxiety
and irritability.
   In announcing the new teams, the agency said it gave prime
consideration to areas ``with significant underserved veteran
populations, including those with large rural, black and Hispanic
populations.''
   The units are at Albuquerque, N.M.; Battle Creek, Mich.; Boise,
Idaho; Baltimore; Boston, Canandaigua, N.Y.; Charleston, S.C.;
Chicago (West Side); Dallas; Denver; Gainesville, Fla.; Hines, Ill.;
Jackson, Miss.; Kansas City, Mo.; Los Angeles Outpatient Clinic;
Minneapolis; Mountain Home, Tenn.; New Orleans; Philadelphia; San
Antonio, Texas; San Francisco; San Juan, Puerto Rico; and Seattle.
</TEXT>
