<FIRST>u a AM-FlagRally     06-29 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Rally,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Findlay Residents Rally Around The Flag</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FINDLAY, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patriotism fluttered in shades of red, white
and blue Thursday as citizens of ``Flag City USA'' turned out to
support efforts to make burning the American banner a crime.
   ``We may not be able to do anything about flag burning in Libya
and Iran, but we ought to be able to stop people from burning the
flag in the streets of America,'' said U.S. Rep. Michael Oxley at
the Rally for Flag and Country.
   ``This isn't a protest rally,'' said Oxley, a Republican from
Findlay. ``It's a rally to honor our flag.''
   Nearly 1,000 people turned out to express outrage at a recent
Supreme Court ruling overturning flag desecration laws in the United
States.
   Flags hanging from stores and homes along the narrow streets
leading to this northwestern Ohio city flitted in a light breeze.
Vendors sold T-shirts that read: ``Only a Commie Would Burn the
American Flag.'' Most people held or waved small flags.
   An act of Congress in 1974 designated Findlay as ``Flag City
USA,'' said Marjory Buckingham, manager of the Hancock County
Convention and Visitors Bureau, who coordinated the rally.
   ``I knew the city would support it,'' Buckingham said. ``It's a
patriotic issue and Findlay is a flag-waving, patroitic city.''
   Members of Citizens to Protect Our Flag, who also helped organize
the rally, went through the crowd asking people to sign petitions
stating that the Supreme Court's ruling was ``an affront to the
American People.''
   By the end of the rally, the group had collected about 5,500
signatures on the petitions, which they gave to Oxley. The petition
drive started earlier this week.
   Among those at the rally was Robert Heft, who as a high school
junior in Lancaster, Ohio, submitted the winning design for the
current 50-star U.S. flag as part of a class project in 1958.
   Heft said his first reaction to the Supreme Court ruling was
``disappointment and disbelief.'' Since then, however, ``it has
turned to anger,'' Heft said.
   ``I believe very strongly in freedom of speech when we show
displeasure with government or business or anything else,'' he said.
``But how far do we go with that freedom of speech? Does it apply to
desecration of the flag. I don't think so.''
   The U.S. Senate has passed a resolution condemning the Supreme
Court's decision. In the House, constitutional amendments have been
introduced to overturn the ruling. President Bush has said he would
support such an amendment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
