<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     06-29 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Envoy To Afghan Resistance Pushes Interim Government Despite
Divisions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. envoy to the Afghan
resistance on voiced strong backing Thursday for a new
government-in-exile despite sharp opposition by many of the
insurgents.
   ``We support the Afghan resistance as a whole, but are of the
view that the interim government is the most important manifestation
of the resistance,'' Peter Tomsen told a news conference.
   The U.S. envoy urged patience among guerrilla leaders opposing
the interim government that wants to end a 10-year-old civil war and
replace the Soviet-backed government of President Najib.
   ``It's only 3{ months old,'' he said. ``It is a slow and
laborious process, but our policy is to encourage and assist this
interim government.''
   One of the moderate guerrilla leaders, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said Tomsen's outspoken support for the provisional
government ``is a stupid thing to say.''
   ``This government is the cause of the disintegration of our jihad
(holy war), the cause of dissent and infighting among Afghans,'' he
said.
   The United States eventually wants to funnel its humanitarian and
military assistance to the guerrillas through this government rather
than Pakistan, which has acted as a conduit during the past 10
years, said Tomsen.
   Some of the most vocal critics of this government belong to
so-called moderate guerrilla groups, many of whom support a return
of the former monarch or a neutral transitional Cabinet, which would
eventually oversee elections.
   But even some of the loosely-defined fundamentalists among the
Afghan resistance, such as Jamiat-e-Islami commander Ahmad Shah
Massood, blasted the guerrilla government as unrepresentative, said
members of his party based in the Pakistan capital.
   Abdul Rahim, a Jamiat spokesman, reported: ``Massood said it is
unsuccessful and he is right. ... Up to now this government has done
nothing.''
   So far this government represents only Afghan guerrilla groups
headquartered in Pakistan, where more than 3 million war refugees
live. It does not include the more than 2 million living in Iran,
the majority of whom belong to the Shiite sect of Islam, which is
practiced by most Iranians.
   In pre-war Afghanistan the Shiites represented about 17 percent
of Afghanistan's 15 million people. Most of the rest are Sunni
Moslems.
   Tomsen, who arrived in Pakistan Wednesday, said it is impossible
to meet Afghans in Iran. He met Pakistani Foreign Minister Sahabzada
Yaqub Khan Thursday and is expected to meet Afghan leaders in the
frontier city of Peshawar, about 40 miles from the Afghan border
during the next week.
   In mid-February the Soviet Union finished withdrawing its force
of more than 100,000 troops, in line with a United Nations accord.
The Soviets sent the Red Army into Afghanistan in 1979 to back the
Marxist government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
