<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 2140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-VALoans     06-29 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-VA Loans,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mortgage Bankers Sue VA Over Foreclosure Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's mortgage lenders are suing the
Veterans Affairs Department over a policy they say will increase
already excessive losses on VA defaulted mortgages.
   The lawsuit, filed Wednesday by the 2,200-member Mortgage Bankers
Association, asks the U.S. District Court for the District of
Columbia to block the policy, scheduled to take effect Aug. 1.
   Under the policy, the VA will add borrowing costs to the formula
to determine whether to acquire a foreclosed home at full price or
let the private lender take it over for a loss.
   Lenders say a growing tendency by the VA to cover only a portion
of the losses on defaults and leaving the property in the hands of
lenders is wreaking economic havoc.
   The order covers the cost the VA incurs to borrow money to
acquire and hold foreclosed property until it can be resold. Other
such costs that now might be deducted include repairs, cleanup and
commissions.
   The industry group says the revision will worsen problems in the
VA program caused by economic problems in the Southwest and the
lingering effects of the recession of the early '80s. It says banks
and mortgage companies may have to cut back on the low-interest,
reduced down-payment loans to veterans.
   When the VA doesn't bid on the foreclosure of a VA-guaranteed
home, the lender must acquire and dispose of the property, adding to
its losses, the bankers' group said in a statement accompanying the
lawsuit.
   The VA, in turn, pays only the portion of the loan that it
originally guaranteed, which is 40 percent or 50 percent, up to
$36,000.
   The lenders group, whose members hold 80 percent of VA loans,
says the loss to its members for each piece of property not acquired
by the VA will be $18,000.
   Thomas W. Maher, assistant director for property management at
VA, said the change would increase the numbers of pieces of property
that it will decide not to acquire because the loss would be too
great.
   Maher said the problem of defaults and foreclosures appears to be
abating.
   In the peak month of December 1987, there were 16,200 defaults;
there were 13,600 at the end of May. There were 22,200 foreclosures
as of December 1987, compared with 20,100 in May, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
