<DOCNO> AP890629-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1923EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-CalifFires     06-29 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Calif Fires,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Early Fire Season Blaze May Have Been Work of Arsonist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE ELSINORE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man-made fire destroyed six homes
Thursday, and authorities said most of the houses burned because
owners failed to clear away dry brush before the start of Southern
California's fire season.
   The Riverside County blaze faded under dying winds later
Thursday, along with another that claimed one home and three other
buildings in Los Angeles County's Antelope Valley. Thousands had
been forced to evacuate both areas briefly as the fires burned 9,750
acres of brush.
   The Riverside fire ravaged five mobile homes and one house near
Lake Elsinore, 60 miles southeast of Los Angeles, but no damage
estimate was available, said Riverside County Fire Department
spokesman Barton Ball.
   ``It was man-made _ not caused by lightning or an act of
nature,'' said Ball, who added that there were witnesses but refused
to divulge details. Results of the investigation will determine if
the fire was arson, he said.
   The fire was first reported Tuesday afternoon in the Cleveland
National Forest near here. Ball said 1,000 acres of forest wildland
burned in the blaze, which was fanned by winds.
   ``Most structures that were lost were lost because of failure to
comply with state clearance requirements,'' said Ball. ``Those that
were saved were saved because they did. It's as simple as that.''
   He said depending on conditions, homes are required to have 30
feet to 100 feet of brush cleared around them.
   On Wednesday, authorities evacuated more than 200 families living
on the Lake Elsinore shore and in the nearby mountains, but most had
returned home by Thursday morning.
   `Our last family just left,'' said Red Cross shelter manager
Patti Hanna at Lake Elsinore High School. She said the shelter would
remain open during the day in case authorities called for another
evacuation.
   Ms. Hanna said 126 evacuees had registered at the shelter on
Wednesday, and 48 stayed the night. During its course, the fire also
forced the evacuations of a youth correctional facility, a nudist
colony and many homes and cabins.
   Ball reported 1,910 firefighters on the line, assisted by 12 air
tankers and six water-dropping helicopters. He said the only
significant fires left were burning islands of brush surrounded by
already charred areas.
   ``They have nowhere to go,'' Ball said.
   In the Antelope Valley 45 miles north of Los Angeles, meanwhile,
firefighters were mastering a 2,250-acre blaze that slowed Wednesday
night and was 95 percent contained by Thursday afternoon.
   ``The reason we are doing so well is because the wind has died
down,'' said county Fire Inspector Chris Button. The cause of the
fire was still under investigation, and reports that it was started
by a downed power line had not been confirmed, he said.
   ``It's now looking good,'' said U.S. Forest Service spokesman
Robert Brady. ``There are still lots of coals and embers, but no
massive flame fronts.''
   About 400 firefighters were battling the blaze, along with two
water-dropping helicopters.
   The fire destroyed one home, two barns and one other building and
forced 2,500 residents to flee the communities of Green Valley,
Leona Valley and Elizabeth Lake.
   ``It's hard to look at 25 years of your life, all the pictures,
the things that no amount of money can replace,'' said Velma Majors
as she looked over the remains of her family's home near Lake Hughes.
</TEXT>
