<FIRST>u w AM-North     06-29 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Say There's No Evidence Juror Lied</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors said Thursday a juror in the Oliver
North case gave inaccurate information to the court due to
``inattentiveness, forgetfulness or lack of comprehension,'' but
that there is no evidence she lied.
   The assertions came in a seven-page court filing, the day after
North juror Tara Leigh King testified that she had forgotten that
one of her brothers had served a year in prison for armed robbery.
North's lawyers say his trial was tainted by King's presence on the
jury.
   In connection with the armed robbery investigation of her
brother, Tara King was contacted by a police detective at
Christmastime 1986, was subpoenaed and testified before a grand
jury, it was disclosed at a court hearing Wednesday.
   She responded ``no'' last Feb. 1 when asked on a courtroom
questionnaire whether she or any relatives had been involved in
court proceedings or an investigation.
   On Wednesday, she testified that she shed tears when she found
out her brother had been sent to prison and then forgot about the
episode.
   ``There is absolutely no evidence that Ms. King deliberately
answered'' the questionnaire falsely Feb. 1 when being considered
for the North jury, prosecutors in the North case said.
   ``Ms. King's testimony ... makes clear,'' said the prosecutors,
that ``whether because of inattentiveness, forgetfulness or lack of
comprehension, or a combination of the three,'' the questionnaire
``simply failed to trigger in Ms. King's mind her own involvement
and the involvement of her brother Sam King in the armed robbery
case.''
   There was no decision Thursday from U.S. District Court Judge
Gerhard A. Gesell on whether King's incorrect answer to the court
had tainted the former White House aide's three-month trial.
   Gesell was tied up much of the day on other matters. Gesell said
at the end of a court hearing Wednesday he would issue a ruling
Thursday.
