<FIRST>r a AM-OilHearing     06-29 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Hearing,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Task Force Urged To Rule Out NorCal Offshore Oil Exploration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARCATA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers, businessmen and citizens urged a
presidential task force on Thursday to ban proposed offshore
drilling on the rugged northern California coast.
   ``The north coast simply can't afford the risks of an economic
shutdown that are associated with spills from offshore oil and gas
development,'' said Sen. Pete Wilson, a Republican from California.
   Recent oil spills off Alaska, Rhode Island and elsewhere
demonstrate that there are ``some risks that are not worth taking,''
he said.
   Wilson's comments to the five-member panel came in the second and
last day of hearings to evaluate the environmental effects of
proposed drilling in parts of northern and southern California and
the west coast of Florida.
   The panel is scheduled to make its recommendations to President
Bush in January.
   Numerous local politicians opposed any drilling off the scenic
coast of Humboldt and Mendocino counties, parts of which are
included in the proposed Lease Sale 91 that is under review by the
task force.
   ``We cannot allow northern California to be leased and our
valuable ocean resources blown out the tailpipe of a gas guzzler
when there is no national energy policy,'' said Wesley Chesbro,
chairman of the Humboldt County Board of Supervisors.
   Chesbro and others called for increased conservation efforts and
a policy based on renewable energy sources like wind and solar
power. Oil drilling opponents fear spills could devastate the local
tourism and fishing industries.
   Some likened the prospect of drilling in the region to drilling
in the Grand Canyon, while others threatened to stage a ``seaweed
rebellion'' in the boardroom and court to fight any approved lease
sales.
   Eureka City Councilman James Worthen, however, testified that his
council voted unanimously to support ``orderly and environmentally
safe exploration of oil and gas preserves.''
   Stressing the importance of safety, Worthen said he believes most
transportation problems can be overcome with technology and that
pipelines to shore can avoid many tanker transport risks.
   His was the minority view. At a rainy rally outside the hearings,
about 250 people gathered in support of a national ocean sanctuary.
   ``If there was an oil spill ... it would put me out of work
absolutely,'' said commercial crab fisherman Bill Reid.
   The task force is comprised of members of the departments of the
Interior, Energy, Commerce and the Environmental Protection Agency
and the Office of Management and Budget.
   The first sales of Lease Sale 91 were scheduled for February but
Bush postponed the sales for additional review. As many as 22
drilling platforms could be built on the 1.1 million acre parcel,
according to federal estimates.
   In a related development Thursday, the House of Representatives
approved a moratorium on new offshore oil drilling along the entire
California coast until at least Oct. 1, 1990.
   If approved by Congress, the moratorium would halt preparations
for Lease Sale 91, as well as proposed lease sales in southern and
central California.
</TEXT>
