<FIRST>u i AM-Irish 2ndLd-Writethru a0704 06-29 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0704,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irish Prime Minister Will Try To Form New Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with Haughey's plans to form new
government. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Charles Haughey resigned
Thursday night and set out to form a new government after Parliament
defeated his bid for re-election.
   Facing what he called an unprecedented political crisis, Haughey
was expected to spend the next few days trying to line up more
support before making a new bid for election by the 166-member Dail,
or Parliament.
   He told Irish political correspondents he was sure he could reach
``a policy-based arrangement'' with the six-seat Progressive
Democratic Party that would keep him in office. The only alternative
was a general election, he said.
   Haughey, 63, announced he would stay on as caretaker prime
minister, and not ask President Patrick Hillery to dissolve
Parliament and call an election.
   His resignation was seen as largely a formality enforced by
demands from the left-wing Labor Party that he follow constitutional
procedure.
   Before that, he left no doubt he intended to try to remain prime
minister.
   ``Our paramount task now is to provide a government which can
meet the challenges and the problems facing the country,'' he told
the house.
   The Dail adjourned until Monday, allowing three days for
interparty negotiations.
   The Dail rejected his nomination by 86 votes to 78, underlining
the failure of Haughey's gamble in calling an election June 15 in
hopes of strengthening the parliamentary base of his Fianna Fail
party.
   The Progressive Democrats are a breakaway of the Fianna Fail. The
main opposition is the Fine Gael, which has 55 seats.
   ``The situation which now obtains, where the Dail has failed to
agree on the nomination of a taoiseach (prime minister), is
unprecedented in our history,'' Haughey told the hushed house after
the votes were counted.
   ``I am confident that with a full appreciation of the political
realities, and mindful of the best interests of the country, our
efforts will meet with success,'' he said.
   After the Dail adjourned, Haughey went to offer his resignation
to Hillery, whose post is largely ceremonial. Hillery has the power,
however, to allow Haughey more time to line up support for a new
vote or dissolve Parliament and force a new election.
   Haughey had been governing for more than two years with a
parliamentary minority and called the June 15 election on the
strength of opinion polls that forecast a majority for his party.
   Instead, Fianna Fail slid from 81 seats in the 1987 election to
77, and on Thursday, the Fine Gael and the Progressive Democrats
joined forces with socialist factions and independents to deny him a
majority.
   Only one independent backed Haughey, another abstained, and the
speaker does not vote except to break a tie.
   Other candidates had little hope of winning a majority to form a
government. Fine Gael leader Alan Dukes was defeated 103-61 with one
abstention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
