<FIRST>r a AM-BingoIndictments     06-29 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bingo Indictments,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Charged in Continuing Bingo Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury charged eight people
Thursday with illegally siphoning off proceeds from church bingo
operations, prosecutors said.
   The grand jury indictment, part of a two-year probe of
Tennessee's bingo industry, named H.T. ``Tommy'' Powell, a former
state legislator and union leader, and W.D. ``Donnie'' Walker, a
former lobbyist and state bingo regulator.
   Also charged with mail fraud, obstruction of justice and illegal
gambling, were Ottis Cato, James Thompson, William McBee, James
Long, Jack Roden and Randolph Woody.
   The indictment charges that the Holy Family Miracle Temple and
Fairway Baptist Church, both in Memphis, sponsored bingo games and
illegally skimmed off part of the proceeds.
   The indictment says that Walker was made a silent partner in
bingo operations to prevent detection of illegal gambling.
   Powell introduced the original bill legalizing bingo in the early
1970s and is now president of the West Tennessee chapter of the
AFL-CIO.
   Walker pleaded guilty on Jan. 26 to charges of trying to bribe a
state senator, taking payoffs while working as a bingo inspector and
conspiring to set up fake charity bingo games.
   The U.S. attorney's office said the investigation by the Internal
Revenue Service, FBI and the Tennessee Bureau of Investigation is
continuing.
   All Tennessee bingo licenses were suspended March 9 after the
state Supreme Court ruled the games are lotteries, which are banned
by a section of the Tennessee Constitution.
   Before that, churches and other tax-exempt groups could operate
bingo games for charity as long as they filed necessary paperwork
with the state.
   But Attorney General Michael Cody estimated in 1986 less than 2
percent of the $44 million in bingo proceeds in the state went to
charity.
   Cato, from South Carolina, is involved in bingo halls and bingo
supply operations throughout the southeast, prosecutors said. Long,
from South Pittsburg, Tenn., is a bingo supply distributor and a
former lobbyist, and Woody is a former bingo hall operator who lives
in Chattanooga.
   McBee, from Camden, Tenn., formerly operated a bingo supply
manufacturing plant near Dickson, Tenn. Roden is a Chattanooga
businessman who formerly operated a bingo supply company, and
Thompson was described as a bingo hall operator in Pensacola, Fla.
</TEXT>
