<FIRST>r w AM-Hastings     06-29 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hastings,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Seeks to Block Senate Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for U.S. District Court Judge Alcee
Hastings asked another federal judge Thursday to block a Senate
impeachment trial which could result in his removal from office.
   Hastings, of Miami, faces a trial next month before a Senate
committee on 17 articles of impeachment voted last year by the
House. He is accused of participating in a bribe conspiracy and of
lying about it at a 1983 criminal trial in which he was acquitted.
   The full Senate ultimately would vote on his removal.
   Hastings, who sued the Senate on June 1, is seeking a preliminary
injunction to block the trial scheduled to begin July 10.
   The judge' constitutional rights are being violated because too
much time has elapsed and he essentially faces a second trial on
charges on which he was exonerated, Terence Anderson, one of
Hastings' lawyers, said at a hearing.
   ``Witnesses are dead ... documents have been destroyed ...
memories diminish,'' Anderson told U.S. District Court Judge Gerhard
A. Gesell.
   Anderson also argued that the Senate should pay Hastings' legal
fees and other costs connected with the Senate impeachment trial.
Hastings' net worth is less than $10,000, said Anderson.
   Another of Hastings' lawyers, William Kunstler, said the entire
Senate, not just a committee, must conduct any impeachment trial.
   ``I think they have to really watch the witnesses,'' Kunstler
said.
   Impeachments are not criminal proceedings and Hastings isn't
being tried twice for the same crimes, responded Senate legal
counsel Michael Davidson.
   The Senate ``has the authority to conduct this trial and will do
it,'' said Davidson.
   Davidson said the Senate opposes paying legal expenses for
Hastings: ``They have just never done it,'' said the Senate legal
counsel.
   U.S. District Judge Walter L. Nixon of Jackson, Miss., who is
serving a five-year prison term for perjury, joined Hastings'
lawsuit.
   A 12-member impeachment committee in the Nixon matter is
scheduled to begin a trial Sept. 6.
   One of Nixon's lawyers, David Stewart, also said the full Senate
should conduct the impeachment proceedings.
   ``The Senate cannot evade its constitutional duty to conduct this
trial,'' said Stewart.
</TEXT>
