<DOCNO> AP890629-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 2206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina     06-29 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Menem Expected to Broaden Amnesty for Military</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By OSCAR SERRAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlos Menem was quoted Thursday
as promising action on the military impasse soon after becoming
president July 8. He is expected to offer a broader amnesty for
officers accused of human rights violations.
   ``Now is the time to close the open wounds of Argentine
society,'' the newspaper La Nacion quoted the president-elect as
saying.
   Aides said he favors calling off the trials of 18 generals and
admirals accused of abuses during the ``dirty war'' against leftist
subversion during military rule in 1976-83, and releasing six who
were convicted in 1985 and imprisoned.
   In the interview, Menem did not specifically say he would ask
Congress to widen a 1987 partial amnesty to include the 18 or that
he would pardon the six jailed officers, who were members of ruling
military juntas and include two presidents.
   La Nacion said he conveyed that impression, however, when he
said: ``I can't stand to see even a bird locked in a cage.''
   Leaders of Menem's Peronist Party said privately that Menem views
an end to the trials as a path to national reconciliation.
   The ``military problem,'' as many call it, has plagued the
country since President Raul Alfonsin's civilian government was
installed in December 1983.
   Officers demanding an end to the trials organized three barracks
revolts, in April 1987 and in January and December 1988. All were
nearly bloodless, but Argentines considered them a threat to
democracy.
   Reports after his election May 14 said Menem urged Alfonsin to
resolve the issue by amnesty or pardon, but the president refused.
Alfonsin then announced he would leave office five months early, on
July 8.
   A commission appointed by Alfonsin documented nearly 9,000 cases
of people who disappeared during the anti-leftist campaign and are
presumed dead. Human rights groups put the total at up to 30,000.
   Alfonsin was unable to find a compromise between those who accuse
the military of a campaign of extermination and officers who say
they were merely using unconventional tactics in a war on terrorists.
   Menem rejected an anmesty or pardon during his campaign and has
repeated the position since the election, although nearly always
adding ``for now.''
   His designated defense minister, Italo Luder, signed an order
while acting as provisional president in 1975 that authorized the
military to ``annihilate'' leftists trying to overthrow President
Isabel Peron. The armed forces overthrew her the following year.
   When asked last week whether he favored amnesty, pardon or a
national referendum on the issue, Menem said he opposed a referendum
but left the other two courses open.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
