<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 2218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Budget     06-29 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agencies Ordered to Prepare for Budget Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration on Thursday ordered
domestic agencies to prepare for budget cuts of 5 percent after next
year because current deficit-reduction plans won't meet future
targets.
   ``It will... be necessary to present the president with options
for further spending reductions,'' said Richard Darman, the
president's budget director, in a memo to department heads.
   Fiscal 1991 budgets submitted for White House approval must
include not only the spending levels they'd like to see but also a
freeze and a 5 percent reduction, he said.
   The memo does not cover military spending.
   The required program cut proposals would not include
entitlements, which are ongoing programs that pay benefits to
individuals. However, Darman said such suggestions would be welcomed.
   ``Any such proposals, including reductions in entitlement
programs or increased user fees, may be suggested. If these are
sufficiently attractive,'' he said, agencies could avoid other cuts
or even offset increases in their regular spending.
   The president submits his budget in January for fiscal 1991,
which begins Oct. 1 of next year. The Gramm-Rudman budget law
requires that the plan reduce the federal deficit to $64 billion,
less than half of the projected deficit this year.
   Darman said that simply extending the deficit-reduction
agreements worked out with Congress for fiscal 1990, which begins
this fall, ``will not provide sufficient restraint'' on spending.
   The White House and congressional budget writers have not yet
begun hard bargaining on spending guidelines for fiscal 1991, as
Congress is still trying to enact the accord for fiscal 1990.
However, many lawmakers have said the 1991 deficit targets could not
be met without a tax increase _ something President Bush has said he
won't allow.
   A congressional aide, who spoke on the condition he not be
identified, said Darman's memo indicated the administration was
``having real difficulties meeting the target.''
</TEXT>
