<FIRST>u w AM-TVA-Conservation     06-29 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-TVA-Conservation,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservation No Longer Efficient, TVA Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Write</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy conservation through insulating homes is
no longer cheaper than generating new electricity, the Tennessee
Vally Authority told Congress on Thursday in defense of its decision
to end its residential conservation program.
   Several House members attacked the decision despite the utility's
assertion that continuation of the conservation program would mean
higher electricity rates.
   ``TVA seems to be out of step with most other utilities in
America and to have sacrificed its pioneering reputation in the
field of energy conservation,'' said Rep. Jim Cooper, D-Tenn.
   The government-owned utility announced in early May that on July
1 it would end its 12-year-old home insulation program for
residential customers in the seven-state region it provides power.
   TVA Chairman Marvin Runyon told a hearing convened by Cooper
before the energy and power subcommittee of the Energy and Commerce
Committee that conservation programs ``have reached a point of
market maturity and diminishing returns.''
   ``The benefits of further investments no longer outweigh the
costs,'' he said.
   Initiated during the interim between the oil and related energy
price spikes of 1973-1974 and 1978-1979, the TVA program became a
model for a congressional directive to other utilities to offer
their customers free home energy audits.
   Ironically, that nationwide program, the Residential Conservation
Service, also expires on Saturday _ Congress, like TVA, having
concluded that its benefits no longer outweigh its costs.
   During the life of its own conservation program, TVA provided
free enery audits to some 1.1 million homes in Tennessee, Kentucky,
Georgia, Alabama, Mississippi, Virginia and North Carolina. It made
no-interest or low-interest loans totaling more than $400 million to
install insulation and otherwise seal heat leaks from 600,000 of
them.
   But Runyon said the agency has found that it is now less
expensive to generate a kilowatt-hour of electricity than to save it
through conservation.
   The conservation program was costing 11.4 cents for each
additional kilowatt-hour of electricity it saved, Runyon said. By
comparison, completing six nuclear reactors either under
construction or being refurbished will cost only 7.3 cents to 8.7
cents for each kilowatt-hour of power they generate.
   ``If we didn't have billions of dollars in debt sitting out there
(already invested in those plants) conservation would look a lot
better,'' he said.
   Runyon estimated that a continuation of the program at a cost of
$20 million a year would require annual rate increases of one-half
of 1 percent.
   After averaging rate increases of 6 percent annually for the past
20 years, partly to finance its once-ambitious nuclear power
program, Runyon said he is committed avoiding a rate increase for
three years.
   ``At this particular time, conservation will add to our rates,
and that's true for out to 10 years from now,'' he said. ``I can't
answer that question for 20 years from now.''
   Several congressmen questioned whether if what is good for TVA as
a utility is necessarily good for its customers, but Cooper conceded
that with the expiration of the Residential Conservation Service
law, there is nothing Congress can do to force TVA's program to
continue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890629-0204 </DOCNO>
