<FIRST>r a AM-CoalStrike     06-29 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vacation Period Brings Uneasy Calm In Coal Fields</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vacations for thousands of United Mine
Workers members brought calm to the coal fields after violence that
had accompanied a wildcat strike by coal miners.
   A newspaper reported Thursday that a strike by 1,900 UMW members
against Pittston Coal Group Inc. in West Virginia, Virginia and
Kentucky is endangering two troubled funds that provide health
benefits to more than 100,000 retired miners.
   The broader wildcat strike is in support of the contract dispute
strike against Pittston.
   In southwestern Virginia, striking Pittston employees and wildcat
strikers from Appalachia and the Midwest continued to clog traffic
on coal-hauling roads Thursday.
   In West Virginia, a state judge has cited the UMW for contempt in
picketing two Pittston subsidiaries in Logan County. Judge Eric
O'Briant said he will decide by early next week whether further
restrictions are needed on picketing at mines owned by Elkay Mining
Co. and Buffalo Mining Co.
   Health benefits are a sticking point between the UMW and Pittston
in the strike that began April 5 and since has prompted the wildcat
walkouts involving as many as 46,000 miners in 10 states.
   Industry officials estimate about 37,000 miners remained off the
job late this week, and about half of the nation's UMW coal miners
are on vacation for a two-week period that began last Friday.
   Pittston has refused to contribute to the two health plans and
two related retirement funds since its contract with the UMW expired
in February 1988, court documents show.
   The union and the UMW Health and Retirement Funds have filed
lawsuits against Pittston over the issue. UMW spokesman John Duray
estimates Pittston owes as much as $10 million to the UMW Health and
Benefits Fund, a figure Pittston would't confirm, the Charleston
Daily Mail reported.
   If Pittston is allowed to stop paying into the program, the
miners fear other large companies will follow suit.
   In addition, employers are not required to contribute to the
funds for woerkers on an unauthorized strike. As a result, miners
striking to protect their health plans are creating hardship on the
funds, industry officials say.
   ``That can create a problem,'' Duray said, adding that miners
believe they can't afford to give in to Pittston on such an
important issue.
   Documents show that the two health plans spent more money than
they earned last year.
   The 1950 Benefit Trust, which covers 150,000 miners who retired
before 1976, ended fiscal year 1988 with an $18 million debt, while
the 1974 Benefit Trust, which covers 36,000 miners who have retired
since 1976, lost one-third of its assets and ended with only $22
million in net assets, the annual report on the funds said.
   The Daily Mail reported that both funds continue to lose money
even though coal operators' rates have increased.
   Pittston lawyer John Wood contends Pittston had the right to pull
out of the benefit plans when its UMW contract expired in February
1988.
   The coal fields in southern West Virginia have been mostly quiet
since the vacation period began, said state police Sgt. D.L.
Belcher, although some isolated shooting incidents were reported
earlier in the week.
   On Wednesday, four coal trucks in West Virginia and Virginia were
peppered with bullets and two others were damaged by steel balls
fired from slingshots. No arrests hade been made.
   However, in Virginia, about 1,600 wildcat strikers from a
half-dozen states stayed overnight at a campground near Pittston's
main processing plant. Virginia state police reported that three
trees were cut across three coal-hauling roads Thursday afternoon to
further hinder traffic.
   State police spokesman Charlie Vaughan said traffic was stalled
for about an hour before the trees were cleared.
   Gayla Hoffman, a spokesman for Peabody Coal Corp., which operates
26 mines in states hit by the strike, said Peabody was losing $5
million a day in sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
