<FIRST>u w AM-FlagAmendment     06-29 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Amendment,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republicans Agree on Language</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and congressional Republican
leaders agreed Thursday on their version of a constitutional
amendment to overturn the Supreme Court ruling that allows flag
burning.
   The amendment would read:
   ``The Congress and the states shall have power to prohibit the
physical desecration of the flag of the United States.''
   Bush will endorse the amendment language in a ceremony Friday at
the Iwo Jima Memorial, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.
   It was a continuation of Bush's presidential campaign tactics,
which included appearances at flag factories in an effort to paint
Democrat Michael Dukakis as less patriotic.
   He attacked Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor, for vetoing as
unconstitutional a bill requiring teachers to lead the pledge of
allegiance in schools.
   Friday's ceremony at the statue of the famed Marine flag-raising
in World War II will be held for ``a public endorsement by members
of Congress and the president,'' Fitzwater said.
   House Minority Leader Michel, R-Ill., introduced the resolution
Thursday before the House left for its holiday recess. He said he
expects Senate Republican leader Bob Dole to introduce it there when
that chamber returns from its extended July Fourth holiday, which
began last week.
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., said Thursday the House
Judiciary Committee will begin hearings on the flag issue in July.
   Foley, while condemning flag burning, has urged caution about
amending the Constitution. Michel said he generally agreed, but
believed in this case such action was the only answer.
   ``I just have to assume we're not going to be thwarted,'' he
said, insisting he did not view the issue as a Republican attempt to
paint the Democrats as less patriotic.
   Michel said the amendment avoids specific methods of desecration
because any list might leave one out. He pointed out, however, that
the amendment referred only to physical desecration in order to
avoid hampering free expression.
   Webster's New World Dictionary, Second Collegiate Edition,
defines ``desecrate'' as ``to take away the sacredness of; treat as
not sacred; profane.''
</TEXT>
