<FIRST>u i AM-BeuysAuction     06-29 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beuys Auction,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Prices for Junk Sculptures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strange-looking works by German sculptor Joseph
Beuys, including a felt suit and a ``silent phonograph,'' sold
Thursday for a total of $1.85 million, auctioneers Christie's said.
   Beuys, who died in 1986, became a celebrated figure in the
avant-garde art movements in the 1960s. He held that living itself
was a creative act and his sculptures were mostly made from junk and
materials such as fat, dead hares and old iron.
   A ``backrest'' of rusty iron set an auction record for his work
Thursday when it sold to an anonymous Swiss buyer for $377,500,
Christie's said.
   Of 102 sculptures, drawings and prints offered, 85 were sold,
often far above estimate. One was simply a wood-handled iron shovel
on a stand and another, called a telephone, consisted of two tin
cans linked by string.
   The felt suit went to an unidentified buyer for $81,100 and the
phonograph _made from a cardboard box, an old record and a bone _
was bought by London dealer Sam Fogg for $309,000.
   Fogg also paid $206,000 for a cardboard box with a roll of felt
and a razor on top, and the same sum for a box containing two rough
bronze and wax human-like figures.
   A 7-foot-tall color photo of Beuys, wearing his customary gray
hat, standing in front of a mastodon's skeleton in a Darmstadt
museum and labeled ``Kunst = Kapital'' (art equals money) was
bought for $55,000 by the Fuji TV Gallery in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
