<FIRST>r a AM-DeadBabies     06-29 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dead Babies,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Babies Buried In Potter's Field; Crack And AIDS Are The Killers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MEL2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A potter's field has become the final resting
place of a growing number of babies, many of them the littlest
victims of the city's twin problems of crack addiction and AIDS.
   ``Two years ago. That's when it started. That's when I began
carrying more dead babies,'' said Jose Santiago, a city worker who
drives the tiny pine coffins to the common grave on Hart Island.
   ``Poor little kids. Crack is killing them all, crack and AIDS,''
he told New York Newsday columnist Dennis Duggan, who wrote about
the problem for Thursday's editions.
   In 1986, 1,128 babies were buried at the potter's field. Last
year, 1,489 were buried there, a 32 percent increase, according to
the Department of Health. On Wednesday 42 newborns were buried. The
babies arrived at a City Island pier in a van driven by Santiago.
   The babies had been placed in unmarked shoebox-sized coffins,
with pink slips giving their names and dates of death.
   The coffins were stacked onto a truck and headed toward a common
grave in the middle of the island. There, the babies are buried
1,000 to a grave 15 feet wide by 40 feet long and 6 feet deep.
</TEXT>
