<FIRST>u w AM-Time-FCC     06-29 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time-FCC,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Querries Paramount</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission on
Thursday asked Paramount Communications Inc. to clear up ``apparent
inconsistencies'' in a document that discusses the company's plan to
take over Time Inc. through a temporary transfer of stock to a
trustee.
   In a letter, an FCC official asked Paramount to explain just when
it plans to take control of Time from the trustee, former Defense
Secretary Donald H. Rumsfeld.
   The letter came a day before Time stockholders were to consider
Paramount's $12.2 billion hostile takeover bid.
   Central to the takeover plan is Paramount's receiving a special
temporary authorization from the commission to allow Rumsfeld to
acquire Time stock and operate the company. This authorization would
be issued pending FCC review of Rumsfeld's qualifications to hold
licenses for microwave relay systems operated through Time's cable
TV subsidiary, American Television &amp; Communications Corp.
   The commission has jurisdiction over the transfer of relay
facilities, while local municipal authorities must approve transfers
of the actual cable system franchises.
   Warner Communications Inc., which is being pursued by Time in a
$14 billion friendly takeover, has claimed that if the FCC approves
the authorization, Paramount will transfer stock to Rumsfeld on July
5, without prior approval from local authorities.
   In a letter to Paramount and Rumsfeld on Thursday, Alex Felker,
the chief of the FCC's mass media bureau, said that ``based on
earlier statements made in this proceeding, it had been my
understanding that you intended to await approval of Paramount by
local cable franchising authorities before Time stock would be
transferred from Mr. Rumsfeld to Paramount, but that you did not
intend to await approval of Mr. Rumsfeld by local cable franchising
authorities before he acquired Time stock and took temporary control
of its cable systems.''
   But Felker noted that in its June 26 response to Warner,
Paramount characterized as ``patently false'' Warner's claim that
Paramount would effect an immediate transfer of control of Time to
Rumsfeld without any required local franchise approvals.
   Felker said the Paramount statement ``appears to suggest, in
contradiction to your earlier statements, that stock will not be
paid for and Mr. Rumsfeld will not take control of Time until local
franchising authorities have approved Mr. Rumsfeld's
qualifications.''
   Felker requested a clarification ``in light of these apparent
inconsistencies'' and that the STA process would be held up in the
interim.
   Felker said that in the event Paramount intends to first await
local authorization before transfering control to Rumsfeld, the
company should inform the FCC how long the process will take.
   In a statement Thursday, Paramount said ``The FCC staff has
understandably been misled by Time's repeated mischaracterization of
our position. We have repeatedly and consisently said that our offer
to purchase Time shares is conditioned on obtaining both FCC
approval and material state and local cable approvals.''
   Time and Warner have told the FCC that Paramount's request for
special temporary authorization called for an ``unprecedented
extension'' to the cable TV industry of the FCC's rules. Time and
Warner claim the rules allow expedited transfer of broadcast
licenses, pending FCC approval of the applicant's worthiness to hold
them, but not for cable franchises, which must be transferred by
local authorities.
   Norman Leventhal, a Paramount attorney in Washington, said
``We'll be filing a formal response tomorrow and we're confident
we'll be able to satisify the commission concerns as expressed in
the letter.
   ``We believe our (plan) is fully consistent with commission
precedent,'' Leventhal said, citing three instances in which the FCC
has issued special temporary authorizations for non-broadcast
acquisitions.
</TEXT>
