<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Nuclear     06-29 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Nuclear,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor's Kinnock Says Anti-Nuclear Policy A Loser</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Neil Kinnock on
Thursday attacked Britain's biggest union, the transport workers,
for continuing to support unilateral nuclear disarmament, a
vote-losing policy his Labor Party is giving up.
   ``You voted to meet the change in the world by making no
change,'' Kinnock told a conference of the 1.3 million-member
Transport and General Workers' Union.
   Kinnock is a member of the left-led union, which voted on Tuesday
to keep its anti-nuclear policy.
   Kinnock, a longtime anti-nuclear campaigner, said Labor would
never win power again if it kept the anti-nuclear policy it adopted
in 1981. In a policy overhaul announced in May, Labor dropped
unilateral nuclear disarmament.
   The policy was cited as a key factor in Labor's 1983 and 1987
election defeats by Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservatives.
   Kinnock, 47, joined Britain's Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament as
a teen-ager. He says he changed his mind because superpower nuclear
arms reduction agreements and the possibility of more deals have
altered the circumstances.
</TEXT>
