<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpillRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0709 06-29 0856</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0709,0871</SECOND>
<HEAD>Immunity Questions Stall Coast Guard Hearing into Tanker Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with later testimony that guidelines
on harbor pilots are unclear, immunity granted to helmsman and first mate.
Picks up 8th graf, `The engineer ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Ban, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ships like the tanker that spilled
420,000 gallons of heating oil into Narragansett Bay are given
federal guidelines that contradict state law governing where harbor
pilots should board, according to evidence presented Thursday.
   In addition, the coxswain of a pilot's boat told the Coast
Guard-National Transportation Safety Board inquiry he often dropped
off or picked up pilots nearly inside the bay, miles closer than
where they should have boarded.
   The tanker World Prodigy had no pilot on board when it ran
aground inside the area in which the state requires a pilot.
   In other oil spills that occurred last weekend, a Delaware state
official said 75 percent of the heavy oil leaked into the Delaware
River when a Uruguayan tanker ran aground has been cleaned up.
   In Texas, crews using hand-held skimmers and absorbent pads were
completing the cleanup of the last of about 6,000 barrels of oil
that leaked into the Houston Ship Channel from a barge that collided
with a tanker. A commercial fisherman complained that several
patches of oil patches are passing over oyster reefs miles beyond
where the Coast Guard said the spill peaked.
   In the investigation of the Rhode Island spill, the Justice
Department approved immunity against prosecution for the World
Prodigy's helmsman and chief mate so they could testify.
   World Prodigy captain Iakovos Georgudis, 43, remained confined
aboard ship in lieu of $50,000 bail on misdemeanor charges he
violated the federal Clean Water and Refuse Acts that prohibit
negligent discharge of pollutants or discharge of pollutants without
a permit. He was arrested Wednesday.
   A statewide grand jury is investigating possible violations of a
state law that require a harbor pilot on board vessels inside a line
from Point Judith to Sakkonet Point.
   But the ``United States Coast Pilot,'' a Commerce Department
guide entered as an exhibit at the hearing, says pilots normally
board at the Brenton Reef Light Tower, about 1{ miles inside the
line and in the approximate area where the tanker ran aground.
   Norman Lidstone, coxswain of the boat that brought pilot David
Leonard to the tanker, said that while most pilots meet their ships
up to 1{ miles away from the tower, some ships whose captains are
familiar with the area meet pilots closer to the reef.
   In other testimony, Chief engineer Konstantinos Tzalas, aided by
an interpreter, told the Coast Guard-National Transportation Safety
Board investigating panel he was in the engine room and knew the
ship had grounded ``from the shudder.''
   The engineer, however, said speed was controlled from the bridge
and he could not estimate it from his measure of engine revolutions.
He said Georgudis provided little information about the accident.
   Coast Guard Capt. David H. Whitten said he decided not to attempt
to call the captain or chief mate, Georgios A. Vlahos, after their
lawyer, John McFadden, wrote that they would invoke their right
against self-incrimination.
   U.S. Attorney Lincoln C. Almond said he was trying to obtain
approval for the immunity grants from Washington.
   Testimony by the helmsman, Konstadinos A. Paraskevopulos, also
was delayed by the immunity question. He was granted state immunity
Wednesday and testified before a grand jury investigating whether
state pollution laws or a statute requiring a harbor pilot on board
were violated.
   Coast Guard crews and a private contractor had pumped the last of
the ship's almost 8 million gallons of oil into waiting barges and
were waiting for plans from the owner on where the ship would be
repaired, Lt. Paul Wolf said.
   Little shoreline pollution remained.
   In Delaware, Edwin Clark, secretary of Natural Resources and
Environmental Control, said 99 percent of the oil spilled by the
tanker Presidente Rivera had been cleaned from the shoreline and
about 75 percent total or 75,000 gallons had been cleaned up. Clark
said the state has kept its estimate at more than 100,000 gallons
while the Coast Guard said the tanker spilled 306,684 gallons.
   Tri-State Bird Rescue &amp; Research Inc. has gotten about 100 birds,
mostly mallard ducks and Canada geese, to be cleaned of the thick
oil clogging their feathers. Two ducklings have died at the center,
said spokeswoman Joyce Ponsell.
   A Galveston Bay oysterman said the extent of the Houston Ship
Channel spill may be broader than initially believed because patches
of oil particles are passing over oyster reefs miles away from the
spill.
   ``I had understood the oil was being contained and recovered, so
it was a surprise to me,'' oysterman Joe Nelson of Smith Point said.
``I was not expecting to see anything.''
   The Coast Guard reported Thursday said a light sheen of oil
stretched for about four miles from the cleanup site. ``It might
have been some oil that got out during the storm that we didn't know
about,'' Lt. David Atkinson said.
</TEXT>
