<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 2313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-WrightHomecoming     06-29 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright Homecoming,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wright Supporters Throw Homecoming Party for Resigned Speaker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Jim Wright was welcomed home
Thursday by 3,000 people who jammed a hotel convention center and
cheered when the ousted House speaker thanked them for forgiving his
mistakes.
   ``I want to thank you for being broad-minded enough, tolerant
enough, big-spirited enough to tolerate my problems, my
eccentricities and my mistakes, occasionally,'' Wright said. ``And
you let me do the big and important things.''
   The remarks drew thunderous applause in the Round Up Inn's
cavernous convention center.
   Wright did not specifically mention the allegations of unethical
behavior that forced his resignation, which takes effect Friday, but
he criticized the news media for what he called negative coverage.
   ``I've come home to live among you,'' he said. ``We'll be active
citizens. There are other things we can do. There are other ways we
can serve. Maybe we can help in some ways to create lasting peace in
Latin America _ peace throughout the world.''
   Wright also told the crowd he might be interested in teaching on
the university level.
   After his speech, Wright shed his jacket and sat on the edge of
the stage where he shook hands and accepted personal thanks from
well-wishers.
   Betty Wright, also a target of ethics allegations, sat by her
husband during most of the ceremony and said she too was glad to be
back in Texas.
   ``I think it's wonderful,'' she said. ``It couldn't be better.
It's great.''
   Wright got a loud cheer when he first walked onto the
red-curtained stage that bore a large ``Welcome Home Jim'' sign
beside a 10-foot-tall caricature of himself. He stood smiling, with
his hands up in the air as the crowd applauded for a half-minute.
   Mayor Bob Bolen, a Republican, helped organize the party, which
was free and open to the public.
   ``Jim's support here in the community is bipartisan,'' said
Tarrant County Democratic Chairman Dennis Sheehan, citing a poll the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram published Sunday that showed almost half
the district's Republicans support Wright.
   Wright, facing 69 allegations of House ethics rules, announced
his resignation May 31. A special election will be held Aug. 12 to
fill the vacant seat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
