<FIRST>r a AM-Scouts-Provideniya     06-29 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scouts-Provideniya,0191</SECOND>
<UNK>Nome Cub Scouts Bound for Provideniya</UNK>
<DATELINE>NOME, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty Cub Scouts from Nome plan to spend the
Fourth of July in the Soviet town of Provideniya for a wienie roast
and baseball games with their neighbors across the Bering Strait.
   The group from Pack 98 got visas from the Soviet Union on
Thursday, said Nome businessman Jim Stimpfle, organizer of the trip.
   The Cub Scouts are to cross the Bering Strait by airplane on
Monday for four days in the Provideniya area. Their parents will pay
travel expenses.
   Their hosts will be the Young Pioneers, a Soviet scouting
organization. Plans include a gift exchange, baseball games and
roasting hot dogs and marshmallows.
   The master of Pack 98, Glenn Martin, said the Alaska delegation
will include several Eskimo Cub Scouts and their parents, whose
native language is spoken by some natives of the Soviet Far East.
   The trip, months in the planning, comes about a year after an
Alaska group's ``friendship flight'' to Provideniya. That was the
first of several trips that have taken Soviets to Alaska and
Alaskans to the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
