<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0547EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv30   06-29 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 30,0831</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, June 30, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Scholar's Work Being Revised Because Scrolls Were Inaccessible</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In 1972, Bible scholar Delbert Hillers completed
what was intended as the most thorough, comprehensive volume on the
Old Testament Book of Lamentations.
   Now he has to revise it because he and scholars generally were
unaware that much earlier chapters of Lamentations had been
available for years in the Dead Sea Scrolls, but only a select group
knew about it.
   The particular chapters have finally been issued, but more than
half of the immense trove of ancient manuscripts remains hidden from
public view.
   Furor erupted anew this week over the long delay in releasing
much of the scroll contents. It's been ``a problem'' to get access
to the scroll material, said Theresa Dorsogna, an editor for
Doubleday publishers of the huge Anchor Bible series, expected to
exceed 70 volumes, of which Hillers' book is a part.
   ``It's something that scholars have been fighting for a long
time,'' she said in a telephone interview. ``It works a real
hardship on them.'' Hillers, of Johns Hopkins University, was
expected to have his revision finished by year's end.
   The scrolls contain parts of every book in the Old Testament
l,000 years older than any ever available before, as well as
extensive material on first- century Judaism in which Christianity
arose.
   David Noel Freedman, professor of biblical studies at the
University of Michigan and editor of the Anchor Bible series, said
the scroll team kept their work ``in the dark while a whole
generation has gone by.''
   The delay has ``been almost 40 years, and that's too long to keep
the material from public scrutiny,'' he said. ``It's a serious
matter and long past time for some changes.''
   Less than half of the scrolls have been published, although the
first were discovered in a cave near the Dead Sea in 1947 and many
more were found in 11 caves over the next decade.
   They've been in the hands of a small international team of
scholars since the early 1950s, now overseen by Israel's Department
of Antiquities.
   Their editor-in-chief, John Strugnell, Harvard University
professor of Christian origins, said the work was being speeded up
and hopes were to have all the manuscripts published by 2000.
   ``It's slow business,'' he said. ``We are producing. And we're
getting faster. An immense amount of work is being done.''
   He noted that only three volumes of the scrolls had been produced
in the first 20 years of the project, nine of them since 1976. He
said only a third to half of the material has been published so far.
   Strugnell scoffed at suspicions once voiced that religious
authorities, such as the Vatican, were covering up the materials
because they threatened church teachings. ``Anyone who would believe
that would believe anything,'' he said.
   The notion also was derided in the current bimonthly, Biblical
Archeology Review, which had raised new challenges to the delay in
issuing the scrolls, calling it a ``conspiracy of silence and
obstruction.''
   But the magazine said it had ``tried to scotch these rumors'' of
religious supression, and ``we do not believe there is any credible
evidence'' for such conclusions.
   There also was early speculation linking Jesus to the Qumron
community of ascetics called the Essenes, who produced the Dead Sea
documents, but Strugnell said this has ``virtually been dropped.''
   However, Jesus' movement and the Essenes were contemporary, he
noted. ``The two groups lived in the same century and there must
have been some contact, but it was no closer than that,'' he said.
   Concerning complaints about a still unpublished scroll letter
from the Qumron community leader, the ``Teacher of Righteousness,''
to Jerusalem's high priest, Strugnell said it should be out by
year's end.
   ``That's a top priority,'' he said.
   The high priest, whose leadership the Qumron community had
rejected, was the same one that pushed for the elimination of Jesus.
   Strugnell said while the material on first-century Judaism did
not refer directly to Jesus, ``it relates to the background of
Christianity'' in that period and country.
   Freedman, who alternates teaching at the University of Michigan
and the University of California at San Diego, said that among still
unpublished documents are parts of the two books of Samuel and the
book of Jeremiah.
   Such material ``belongs to the whole scholarly community and
should be released right away,'' he said. He said after such
archeological finds, photographic slides should be generally
available within a year or two.
   The Anchor Bible series issued its first volume in 1965 on the
book of Genesis, and is scheduled to issue its 47th volume this fall
on the book of Amos, with 70 volumes expected to be out by 2000.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs, June 30</NOTE>
