<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0548EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv30   06-29 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 30 ,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, June 30, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What was termed the first
multi-denominational baptism service since the 16th century
Protestant Reformation was held recently at the Roman Catholic
cathedral here before about 1,000 people.
   Taking part in the 90-minute service were bishops of the
Catholic, Episcopal, Armenian Orthodox and Lutheran churches. Four
children were baptized, one from each church, using the same liturgy.
   In a sermon afterward, Kathleen Hurty, National Council of
Churches secretary on local ecumenism, told the children:
   ``As you grow older, you will come to appreciate the richness of
God's gift given you today. And you will remember that we are one
family: Orthodox, Anglican, Roman Catholic and Protestant, with an
extended family of all who believe.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About half the female clergy in the
Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) say they feel they have been
discriminated against, a survey finds.
   Ann Dubois, a church specialist on female employees, said federal
laws banning sex discrimination have brought ``tremendous strides in
the secular workplace'' for women, but the church is ``still
catching up.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American scholar on Soviet religion said
legislation has been proposed by the Soviet Council on Religious
Affairs that would legalize most church activities there.
   Kent Hill, executive director of the Institute on Religion and
Democracy, says copies of the draft Law on Freedom of Conscience has
been provided to the church and is further evidence of a ``genuinely
liberalizing situation.''
   In a telephone interview with Religion News Service, he said the
law would give Christians opportunities to spread faith openly and
provide religious education for children and alternative services by
conscientious objectors to military draft.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Responding to a recent statement by Los Angeles
Archbishop Ropger M. Mahony that Catholic office holders ``have a
postive moral obligation'' to work for repeal of laws permitting
abortion, the American Jewish Committee said:
   ``Public officials owe all citizens _ and not just those who
share their religious views _ a duty to exercise their own best
judgment. ... What no church or synagogue should do is demand that
its adherents holding public office respond in lock step to its
religious teachings.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GENEVA, Switzerland (AP) The general secretary of the World
Council of Churches has expressed ``shock and profound
consternation'' at the Chinese government's violent crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators.
   The Rev. Emilio Castro in a message to Bishop K.H. Ting,
president of the China Christian Council, also assured him that
churches are ``joining with you ... in praying for the people of
China in these days of need.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Already working on a project to help send a
million Bibles to the Soviet Union, the American Bible Society was
jolted by word that Christians there need at least 20 million.
   Terje Hartberg, a publishing consultant, says Russian Orthodox
leaders told him the demand for Bibles ``would not even slow down''
until at least that number were in the hands of the people.
   Bishop Vladimir, deputy head of Russian Orthodoxy's external
affairs department, was quoted as saying that not only believers but
non-believers want Bibles.
   The Rev. Cirilo A. Rigos of Reading, England,, general secretary
of United Bible Societies, which includes about 100 national
societies, says the request ``is without a doubt the greatest
challenge we have ever faced _ and we welcome it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs, June 30</NOTE>
