<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--BladderCancer Adv03   06-29 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Bladder Cancer, Adv 03,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, July 3, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>TB Treatment Being Evaluated For Use Against Cancer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MORGANTOWN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration is
evaluating the use of a tuberculosis vaccine derived from a harmless
bacteria to fight some forms of bladder cancer, which kills 10,000
Americans a year.
   The American Urological Association is urging the FDA to speed up
the approval process for the use of Bacillus Calmette-Guerin. FDA
spokesman Mike Shaffer declined to discuss details of the review,
but said it was ``pretty far along'' and that approval could come in
as little as a year.
   ``It isn't so much a matter of safety because it's already being
used for something,'' Shaffer said. ``It's a question of
effectiveness.''
   Doctors have known since the 1880s that severe bacterial
infections can shrink some tumors by stimulating the immune system.
``Some doctors actually treated patients with bacterial infections
before the advent of chemotherapy and radiation therapy,'' said Dr.
Donald Lamm, chairman of the urology department at the West Virginia
University Medical Center.
   Chemicals and radiation replaced bacteria therapy in the 1950s.
But research on BCG, which has been used as a TB vaccine since 1921,
continued because of its powerful effect on the body's immune system.
   Lamm said his research and studies by Memorial Sloan-Kettering
Cancer Center in New York have indicated that BCG is cheaper than
surgery and more effective than chemotherapy against early cases of
superficial bladder cancer.
   ``My frustration and the frustration of doctors caring for
patients with bladder cancer is that the FDA has failed to approve
BCG for use in treating the disease,'' said Lamm, who heads a
urological association committee that is urging the FDA to speed up
its approval process for BCG.
   Research indicates that BCG reduces the recurrence of bladder
cancer nearly twice as effectively as traditional chemotherapy and
dramatically decreases the mortality rate of bladder cancer
patients, he said.
   Doctors can treat bladder cancer patients with BCG only with
federal approval, and must warn patients that it is an experimental
treatment whose effectiveness and safety cannot be guaranteed, Lamm
said. ``They can receive the vaccine but their insurance companies
and Medicare won't pay for it.''
   A typical six-week treatment costs about $435 for the vaccine;
comparable chemotherapy costs would run from about $1,000 to $2,500,
he said.
   ``BCG has been used as an experimental cancer treatment for 20
years and it's been given to billions of people as a TB vaccine with
just a handful of deaths,'' said Dr. Michael Groves, head of the
pharmaceutical department at the University of Illinois at Chicago
Institute of Tuberculosis Research.
   The Chicago college was the only producer of thestrain of BCG
used in the United States until 1987, when it transferred production
to Bionetics Research Inc. of Rockville, Md., which is concentrating
on its use against cancer.
   BCG works best on the earliest stages of bladder cancer, before
the malignant cells have had a chance to spread to the deeper layers
of tissue to muscle that make up the balloon-shaped organ, Lamm said.
   Bladder cancer is the fifth most common cancer in the United
States. It kills about 10,000 Americans annually, typically male
smokers over age 50, and more than 47,000 new cases are expected to
be diagnosed this year. The most common warning signs are blood in
the urine and frequency of urination.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 3</NOTE>
