<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Briefs Adv03   06-29 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Briefs, Adv 03,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, July 3, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Murder-Victim ID Techniques To Be Used On Damaged Mummy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anthropologist who reconstructs faces
to help identify murder victims has taken up a case that's 3,400
years old.
   Virginia Smith is working on the face of the mummy of Then-Hotep,
an Egyptian woman believed to have met a violent death. X-rays taken
of the mummy in 1985 revealed that both thigh bones were shattered
and her head was gashed.
   Smith is making a rubber mold of Then-Hotep's skull and will
build a clay replica of the woman's presumed features.
   The process involves a series of measurements to indicate the
thickness of tissue that would have covered specific points on the
skull, following formulas based on sex, age, weight and ethnic
background.
   Then-Hotep's mummy was damaged in the 1937 Ohio River flood,
which washed away the dried skin and the ears and promoted growth of
mold on the linen wrappings. The mummy was baked and dried, but has
never been restored.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Researchers Nearing End of Three-Year Pine Forest Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EATONTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some pine forests react to pollution while
others don't, and researchers hope by December to have some idea why.
   University of Georgia and Emory University researchers are
wrapping up a three-year study, costing $800,000 to $1 million, on
the effects of acid rain and other pollutants on pine forests.
   The researchers are particularly concerned about the loblolly
pine, one of the mainstays of Georgia's timber industry. The number
of loblolly pines in the region has decreased, though the drop may
have resulted from drought, changing land use patterns or normal
variation, said forest hydrologist John Dowd.
   The study is looking at material deposited by rain and
particulate matter in the air, as well as ozone, Dowd said. ``The
ozone is a photochemical oxidant not emitted by a source. It's
produced by the atmosphere. It's quite high in this non-urban area.
The air here is cleaner than that in the Northeast but it's dirtier
than that in the West. The air here is intermediate.''
   Researchers also are trying to determine whether acid rain pulls
nutrients from the soil, said biologist Larry Ragsdale of Emory.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 3</NOTE>
