<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   06-29 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Share Prices Plunge, Dollar Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Morning Nikkei, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange plunged in
early trading Thursday, while the U.S. dollar moved lower against
the Japanese yen.
   The dollar was changing hands at 143.30 yen at late morning.
Opening lower at 143.15 yen, down 0.40 yen from Wednesday's
143.55-yen close, the dollar moved in the range of 142.90 to 143.38
yen.
   The dollar closed at 142.98 yen in New York overnight.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which shed
223.61 points Wednesday, lost another 266.71 points, or 0.80
percent, ending the morning session to settle at 32,978.89 points.
   Dealers said the index fell mainly because Japanese investors
were concerned about recent political instablity.
   A Nomura Securities dealer said a majority of institutional
investors remained on the sidelines, avoiding major moves due to
political uncertainty. The dealer spoke on condition of anonymity.
   On Wednesday, major Japanese newspapers reported Prime Minister
Sousuke Uno had expressed his desire to resign over reports that
allegations of a new sex scandal involving Uno may be carried in a
magazine later this week. Uno, in office less than a month, denied
any intention to resign.
   ``Mr. Uno's scandal had affected the foreign exchange rates and
weakened the yen, which further discouraged participants' buying
incentives,'' the dealer added.
   In currency dealings, traders said the dollar inched down earlier
in Tokyo as Japanese investors began selling it for profit-taking.
   Kyodo News Service reported the Bank of Japan intervened in the
market by selling dollars, which aided the currency in staying
lower. The intervention could not be confirmed through commercial
banks and the central bank does not comment on its monetary
activities.
   Minori Takeuchi, trader with Chemical Bank, said Thursday's
fluctuation was mainly due to by foreign investors' position
adjustments.
   ``Tokyo investors avoided making major moves,'' she said, ``and
very few people wanted to buy the yen because of Mr. Uno's geisha
scandal,'' she said.
   ``Also, Japanese investors are trying not to buy much yen before
the elections,'' Ms. Takeuchi said.
   Tokyo's elections for its prefectural council take place Sunday,
and elections for Japan's upper house of Parliament are scheduled
for July 23.
</TEXT>
