<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ConstructionContracts     06-29 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Construction Contracts,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Construction Contracts Down in May But Outlook Remains Bright: Survey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction contracts fell by 3 percent in May,
although commercial building rebounded sharply from April, according
to an industry survey.
   The value of newly started construction contracts fell to an
annual rate of $249.9 billion last month from $256.8 billion in
April, the F.W. Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill Information Services Co.
said Wednesday.
   Despite last month's slight decline, the group said the
construction outlook in the second quarter and for the rest of the
year looked promising due to a downturn in interest rates.
   ``Lower interest rates in the rest of the year will help sustain
the current rebound, and we're upgrading our 1989 outlook for
construction,'' said George A. Christie, F.W. Dodge's chief
economist.
   Overall construction contracting for the first five months of the
year totaled $100.72 billion, down 1 percent from a year earlier.
   During May, newly started commercial, industrial and
institutional structures rose 11 percent to an annualized $91.4
billion, Dodge said.
   Industrial construction, which set the pace for nonresidential
work in May with a 40 percent increase, included a $300 million
expansion of a petrochemical complex near Houston.
   Residential building, meanwhile, slipped 9 percent in May to an
annualized $115.3 billion, largely due to previously higher interest
rates.
   Contracting for non-building construction, including public works
projects, fell 11 percent last month to an annualized value of $43.2
billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
