<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-IsuzuAd     06-29 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Isuzu Ad,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Who Lied? Business Week Tussles With Creator Of Joe Isuzu</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The advertising agency that created fibbing car
pitchman Joe Isuzu is charging that Business Week lied _ or rather
``lied'' _ in its June 12 issue about American Isuzu Motors Inc.'s
car sales.
   The quotation marks are important because The Wall Street Journal
had refused to run an advertisement about the accusation until the
agency put quotation marks around the word ``lied.''
   The full-page, $82,000 ad is scheduled to appear in Thursday's
editions of the Journal, according to Jerry Della Femina, chairman
of Della Femina, McNamee WCRS Inc., the agency that created the Joe
Isuzu character.
   In an article about the auto industry, Business Week accurately
reported in a one-sentence mention of Isuzu that the company's car
sales fell 38 percent last year. But it failed to note that Isuzu's
sales of trucks and other vehicles, which account for 80 percent of
its business, rose 4 percent.
   The magazine said the Joe Isuzu character ``hasn't created a
positive image for Isuzu.'' The character smiles as he spouts
exaggerations or untruths about the vehicles while captions point
out, ``he's lying.''
   Business Week ran the agency's letter to the editor criticizing
the article. But the magazine turned down Della Femina's ad, ``the
reason being we did not lie, and the ad says we lied. It's not a
logical ad as far as we're concerned,'' spokeswoman Mary McGeachy
said Wednesday.
   ``They're angry and they want to kill me but the fact is they
managed to screw up a very successful character and make it seem
like it wasn't doing well, when it really is,'' Della Femina said in
an interview Wednesday.
   Della Femina said his agency, rather than the automaker, was
paying the full cost of the Wall Street Journal ad. He said it may
run in other publications as well. He said he was pleased with the
addition of the quotation marks around ``lied.''
   ``I didn't want it to be that strident. I was just so mad when I
wrote it,'' he said.
   The Wall Street Journal, by company policy, declines to comment
on ads appearing in forthcoming editions. But Robert Higgins, the
Journal's director of advertising services, said Wednesday, ``I have
talked to Jerry and we did work something out.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
