<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Avon-Mediplex     06-29 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Avon-Mediplex,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avon's Sale of Health Care Unit Falls Through</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avon Products Inc. says it has called off an
agreement to sell the health care operations of its Mediplex Group
partly because the buyer appeared unable to get financing for the
deal.
   The sale agreement with an acquisition group called West Corner
also was terminated because of a lawsuit filed by Meditrust, which
leases properties to Avon's Mediplex division.
   Meditrust, a real estate investment trust that specializes in
health care properties, contends that it has the right to approve
buyers of the Mediplex holdings under terms of its property leases.
   Avon said Wednesday it may sue Meditrust for interfering in its
sale plans.
   The deal with West Corner was to have closed on June 30 but it
appeared that the acquisition group wouldn't be able to raise
adequate financing by then, Avon said.
   Under the agreement, Avon was to receive $55 million in cash for
the Mediplex health care division.
   Mediplex's health care business includes nursing homes, alcohol
and drug abuse treatment centers and psychiatric treatment
facilities. Mediplex, based in Wellesley, Mass., also has a
construction division which has about $100 million of work in
progress. Once the work is finished Avon intends to close the
construction arm of Mediplex.
   The Mediplex sale was to be an element in the cosmetics maker's
strategy to divest its holdings in the health care services field so
it could concentrate more closely on its beauty products business.
   This strategy came under intense scrutiny earlier this spring as
Avon fought off an unsolicited $2.1 billion takeover bid from
another direct-selling company, Amway Corp. Avon's board rejected
the bid and Amway withdrew its offer.
   Avon said it still plans to sell Mediplex and noted that Mediplex
has become profitable so it won't be a drain on its parent company.
   The collapse of the deal with West Corner won't impair Avon's
financial prospects, the company said. Earnings still are expected
to range between $2.30 and $2.40 a share this year, Avon said in a
news release.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
