<DOCNO> AP890629-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-LIN-McCaw     06-29 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LIN-McCaw,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Allows LIN To Transfer Control Of TV Station Licenses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Commmunications Commission says it
will allow LIN Broadcasting Corp. to transfer control of the
licenses of seven television stations to a new company, LIN
Television Corp.
   The commission, ruling Wednesday that the proposed transfer was a
routine transaction that does not violate FCC rules, said it would
remain neutral as to whether or not the transfer would affect the
$6.5 billion hostile takeover bid McCaw Cellular Communications has
made for LIN.
   LIN announced in late May _ a week before McCaw's tender offer _
that it would spin off its television stations. The New York
City-based LIN said it would operate its cellular telephone and
specialty publishing business as a separate company, with LIN
shareholders to own stock in both LIN Broadcasting and LIN
Television.
   The decision by LIN was viewed as an attempt to complicate
McCaw's takeover bid, which would combine two of the nation's
largest cellular telephone companies.
   McCaw, through MMM Holdings, objected to the LIN transfer at the
FCC.
   McCaw, which is the nation's largest cellular company with 50
million potential customers, on June 6 said it would offer $120 a
share for the 90.2 percent of LIN it does not already own. With the
merger the Kirkland, Wash.-based McCaw would have 68 million
potential customers.
   But McCaw made its tender offer contingent on LIN staying intact.
LIN has lucrative cellular franchises in New York, Los Angeles,
Philadelphia, Dallas and Houston. McCaw has cellular operations in
Seattle, San Francisco, Miami, Denver, Minneapolis and Portland, Ore.
   McCaw told the FCC that approving the transfer would allow LIN to
use the spin-off as a ``tactical weapon'' which ``would unduly favor
incumbent management'' in violation of commission policy.
   McCaw also said Securities and Exchange Commission rules require
that LIN's board consider McCaw's offer.
   But the FCC said LIN's proposal was ``a quintessential pro forma
transfer of control, a corporate restructuring which does not result
in a substantial change in the ownership or control of the licensed
facilities.''
   ``We conclude that it would inappropriately thrust the FCC into
the midst of this hostile tender offer if we were to act in a
non-routine manner here,'' the FCC said in a statement signed by
Alex Felker, chief of the commission's mass media bureau.
   The FCC said it would leave it to the SEC to decide whether LIN's
board of directors was properly considering McCaw's tender offer.
   The television stations are: WAND, Decatur, Ill.; W68AA,
Danville, Ill.; WAVY, Portsmouth, Va.; WOTV, Grand Rapids, Mich.;
WISH, Indianapolis; WANE, Fort Wayne, Ind.; KXAS, Fort Worth, Texas;
and KXAN, Austin, Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
