<FIRST>r f PM-IBMAdvertising     06-29 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IBM Advertising,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Announces New Personal Computer Advertising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. is
beginning a third wave of advertising for its personal computers
today, and this time there are no famous characters akin to Charlie
Chaplin's Little Tramp or the cast of M-A-S-H.
   The tag line of the new campaign is ``How're you going to do it?
PS-2 it!'' The television ads are singing commercials and the print
ones are based on cartoons by artists for The New Yorker magazine.
   The new campaign is the first major one prepared for IBM by
Lintas:New York, which is dividing IBM's account with Wells, Rich
Greene Inc. Those agencies took over last year when IBM fired Lord
Federico Einstein Inc., the creator of the Little Tramp and M-A-S-H
ads.
   A company spokesman, Ray Meurer, described the new ads as ``bold
and contemporary.''
   ``The ads respond to business people who say they want to use the
computer as a competitive tool today and in the future,'' IBM said.
   The TV commercials will air during the Wimbledon tennis
tournament coverage Saturday and Sunday and during the All-Star
Baseball Game on July 11. The print ads were scheduled to start
running Thursday in publications such as The Wall Street Journal,
Business Week, Forbes and Fortune, the company said.
</TEXT>
