<DOCNO> AP890629-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MaglevTrain     06-29 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Maglev Train,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Panel Endorses Innovative High-Tech Train</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state panel has endorsed a $500 million,
300-mph magnetically levitated train that would run between the
Orlando airport and Walt Disney World.
   The Florida High Speed Rail Transportation Commission voted
Wednesday to recommend certification of the project, subject to a
list of conditions aimed at satisfying a number of concerns. The
train's builders say it will be a showcase project to demonstrate
the technology worldwide.
   ``This project is of major significance to Florida because it
brings in absolutely brand-new technology'' that may eventually be
blended into a mass transit system for the area, Commission Chairman
Malcolm Kirschenbaum said.
   The governor and his Cabinet will make the final decision on the
project after a series of public hearings.
   In making a recommendation for certification, the commission's
executive director, Charles H. Smith, said, ``The project is
financially feasible and no public subsidies are needed.''
   Under the plan, the 17.5-mile long system would be built by
Maglev Transit Inc. and would begin operating in 1994.
   The technology involves powerful magnets that levitate the train
a fraction of an inch above an elevated track, eliminating friction
and allowing high speeds.
   Magnetic levitation trains have been used experimentally in Japan
and Germany for years, but no commercial system is in operation.
   Transportation experts expect other cities in this country and
other nations to follow Orlando's lead if the technology is
successfully demonstrated with paying customers.
   ``The key is to get one system to operate successfully, and
people will just jump on board, and they will say this is the way to
go,'' said Jim Powell, a scientist at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
   Maglev and other high-speed rail systems are seen as one answer
to highway traffic congestion and crowded airports.
   ``The interest is just picking up all over the country,'' said
Robert Casey, director of the High Speed Rail Association, a
Pittsburgh trade group.
   Sen. Daniel Moynihan, D-N.Y., a major booster of maglev trains,
intends to lobby the Bush Administration to allocate at least $1
billion to help U.S. industry develop the technology, said a staff
member.
   Powell, who pioneered maglev research during the early 1960s,
said government funding and lack of interest halted research in this
country in the early 1970s. But West Germany and Japan continued
working and are now the leaders in the field.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
