<DOCNO> AP890629-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0254EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessExpectations     06-29 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Expectations,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Business Optimism For Third Quarter Declines Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business executives have lowered their
expectations for third-quarter sales and profits in line with
economic data suggesting the economy is slowing, according to a
national survey.
   Most of the 1,500 business executives polled believe the economy
will slow enough to curb inflation in the July-September period but
not enough to fuel a full-blown recession in the second half, said
the report, released Wednesday by Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp.
   The latest quarterly Survey of Business Expectations by the
business research company was conducted May 15-31 and included
manufacturers, retailers and wholesalers.
   The decline in optimism was particularly strong among
manufacturers, due to the recent rise in the dollar against major
currencies and increased foreign competition, said Joseph W. Duncan,
Dun &amp; Bradstreet economist.
   Nevertheless, overall optimism remained at historically high
levels, he said.
   ``The recent declines in interest rates, as well as continued
exports to Europe and Japan should continue to boost manufacturers'
sales,'' Duncan said.
   The Sales Optimism Index declined to 67, down seven points from
the second quarter and off six points from the third quarter of
1988, the survey found.
   Manufacturers were the least optimistic, followed by wholesalers
and retailers.
   Profit expectations also fell, down 8 points to 61 from a
five-year high of 69 in the second quarter. However, the outlook for
higher profits remained slightly higher than in the first quarter of
1989.
   Manufacturers and wholesalers believe prices will not rise as
much as in the second quarter but retailers expect to see some
gains. That index posted a seven-point drop to 39.
   Business executives also expect tighter inventories, fewer new
hires and lower durable goods orders, the survey showed.
   The survey's indexes are calculated by subtracting the percentage
of respondents predicting decreases from the percentage of those
expecting increases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
