<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0303EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Semiconductors-Health     06-29 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Semiconductors-Health,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Asks Government Health Watch at Semiconductor Factories</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union official told Congress that the
government should closely monitor an industry-sponsored study and
also undertake its own study of potential health hazards facing
workers at semiconductor manufacturing plants.
   Barbara J. Easterling, executive vice president of the
Communications Workers of America, said Wednesday that employees at
semiconductor factories frequently work under ``very dangerous
conditions.''
   ``The carnage in the semiconductor workplace is not scored in the
spilled blood of wage earners or visible damage to their bodies,''
she said. ``Instead, it is imposed on the invisible world of
workers' chromosomes and tissues through ingestion of hazardous
substances.''
   The Semiconductor Industry Association, representing the
country's major semiconductor manufacturers, is currently sponsoring
a three-year study in response to concern over reported high rates
of miscarriages among pregnant workers and other potential health
effects.
   Testifying before the House Education and Labor subcommittee on
health and safety, Ms. Easterling said that ``the National Institute
for Occupational Safety and Health should closely oversee the
Semiconductor Industry Association study.''
   ``In fact, it would be best if the federal government initiated
its own study of semiconductor factories, utilizing government
scientists to examine possible health hazards,'' she said.
   The communications union represents about 7,000 employees of
semiconductor manufacturers, while most workers in the industry are
not covered by union contracts.
   Potentially hazardous substances to which workers can be exposed
at semiconductor plants include toxic solvents, acids, caustics,
metals, plastics, resins and asbestos. Workers also may be exposed
to radio-frequency radiation, lasers and ultraviolet light.
   Lee Neal, the Semiconductor Industry Association's director of
occupational health, safety and environmental programs, told the
House panel that ``SIA has sponsored the development and maintenance
of the most comprehensive industry-sponsored occupational injury and
illness surveillance system in operation in the U.S.''
   He said Labor Department statistics show that in 1987, the rate
of occupational injury and illness was 4.3 cases per 100 employees
in the semiconductor industry, as compared with an average of 11.9
cases for all manufacturing sectors.
   Late last year, Neal said, SIA signed an agreement with the
University of California at Davis to undertake the three-year, $3
million study to examine the health of workers at 16 semiconductor
manufacturers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890629-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 0303EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Oil-Penalties     06-29 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil-Penalties,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miller Says Safety Violations on Offshore Rigs Are Going Unpunished</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. George Miller, chairman of a House
Interior subcommittee, says that thousands of safety violations on
offshore oil rigs are going unpunished.
   The California Democrat told reporters Wednesday that ``the
failure to enforce the offshore oil drilling law shows the
scrupulous indifference of the Reagan administration and its
successor toward environmental law enforcement.''
   Miller, head of the subcommittee on water, power and offshore
energy resources, said he has learned that 16,000 safety violations
were found on such rigs in the last four years but no civil
penalties have been imposed and there has been only one criminal
punishment.
   Miller said his office began investigating offshore rigs when
word was received of a $750,000 criminal penalty against Texaco last
year for failing to conduct certain safety tests on a rig off the
California coast in 1986. Through information from the Interior
Department's Minerals Management Service, Miller said he found that
civil penalities stopped in 1983.
   In that year, a federal court, acting on an appeal of a case
involving Chevron U.S.A. Inc., ruled that civil penalities could be
assessed but only after the responsible party was given notice of
the violation and a reasonable period to correct it.
   Miller said he has asked for information about what kind of
follow-up, in lieu of fines, is done by the service. Interior
Secretary Manuel Lujan said in a June 2 letter to Miller that the
service is working on guidelines that would comply with the 1983
federal court requirements.
   Miller said the Interior Department should have acted long ago to
correct its enforcement policies, and ``by its inaction, the Bush
administration has extended the Reagan-Watt-Hodel lackadaisical
approach toward the environmental hazards of offshore oil
drilling.'' James G. Watt and Donald P. Hodel were interior
secretaries under President Reagan.
   ``We're just getting access to information as to exactly how bad
the previous administration was and how hard they were working to
diminish the effectiveness of the federal government,'' said Miller.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
