<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     06-29 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Tokyo Stocks Off Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged down against the Japanese yen
today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index plunged.
   The dollar closed at 142.90 yen, down 0.65 yen from its 143.55
yen close the previous day. It opened at 143.15 yen and ranged
between 142.85 yen and 143.38 yen. The dollar had climbed 3.37 yen
in the two previous trading days.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 289.29 points, or 0.87
percent, closing at 32,956.31. The index had lost 223.61 points
Wednesday.
   Stock dealers attributed the index's fall to a lack of energy in
the market amid uncertainties over the political effects of
allegations that new Prime Minister Sousuke Uno had kept paid
mistresses in the past.
   In thin trading today, volume on the first section was estimated
at 400 million shares, down from Wednesday's 600 million.
   Kazuhiro Nomura, a dealer with the New Japan Securities Co., said
most investors stayed on the sidelines due to uncertainties over
domestic politics and fluctuations in the foreign exchange rate.
   ``The stock market has been gradually recovering from the initial
impact of Mr. Uno's geisha scandal, but many institutional investors
were still reluctant to buy any issues,'' he said.
   On Wednesday, major Japanese newspapers reported that Uno had
expressed a desire to resign, after less than a month in office,
over allegations concernin his ``woman problems.'' Uno denied any
intention to resign.
   ``Also, we can't expect much buying incentive among Japanese
market players before the major elections,'' Nomura added.
   Tokyo citizens vote Sunday for their municipal council, and
elections for Japan's upper house of Parliament are scheduled July
23.
   In currency dealings, traders said the dollar's fall resulted
from selling for profit-taking.
   ``Although Japanese market players had little incentive to buy
the yen, they were not aggressive enough to buy the dollar beyond
the 144 yen level either,'' said Bank of Tokyo trader Masafumi
Koyama. ``That's because they're afraid the dollar might keep rising
again after surpassing that level.''
   After the currency rose beyond the 144-yen level June 12, it kept
rising and reached a close of 151.30 yen on June 15. Many investors
consider 144 yen as a dividing point that determines market
direction.
   Koyama said Japanese investors also were generally pessimistic
over the ruling Liberal Democratic Party's prospects in the upcoming
elections and were reluctant to make major moves.
   The Bank of Japan was believed to have sold dollars to support
the yen, but neither the amount nor the intervention were confirmed.
The central bank does not comment on its foreign exchange market
activitites.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
