<FIRST>u f PM-CapitalGains     06-29 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Capital Gains,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rostenkowski Gives Up on Cutting Capital Gains Tax</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee has given up the idea of cutting the capital gains tax
because of Democratic opposition, according to a published report
today.
   Rep. Dan Rosetenkowski, D.-Ill., said he plans to fill a $5.3
billion tax-increase bill with revenue-raising provisions instead of
coupling a temporary reduction in the capital gains tax with
expansions of tax breaks for low-income people.
   Rostenkowksi said in an interview with the Wall Street Journal
that he encountered stronger resistance than expected from Democrats
on his committee to reducing the tax on gains from the sale of
securities and other assets.
   ``I never anticipated there would be as much resistance to
capital gains as there was,'' he told the newspaper.
   Democrats had argued the tax break would be too large a benefit
for wealthy people and also probably would cost the government
revenue in the long run.
   Rostenkowski's plan, which he termed a ``trial balloon,'' would
have paired the cut with a reduction for low-income people in areas
such as earned income tax credit and child care credit.
   He said President Bush had supported the idea of cutting the
capital gains tax and that his balanced plan came after the
president had suggested ``Why don't you try to put together a
package?''
   The chairman's plan would have reduced the capital gains rate for
a year from the current top rate of as much as 33 percent, and to
help lower-income individuals with expended tax credits.
   He said the plan would have raised about $15 billion over two
years because of churning of assets during the short-term change.
   Rosetnkowski said he now will focus on ways of raising the $5.3
billion tax increase called for in the congressional budget
resolution for fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1.
   He said because of that need, some tax breaks due to expire this
year will have to wait a year to be extended. He said he was
considering a variety of provisions that Bush would be most likely
to accept given his pledge not to increase taxes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
