<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   06-29 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Retreat In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly lower
in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting
wetter weather forecasts for the Midwest and a weakening of bullish
attitudes in the wheat market.
   The early selling of corn and soybean futures was partially a
reaction to Wednesday's six-to-10-day National Weather Service
outlook for near-normal rainfall in the Midwest.
   The soybean market also was pressured by prospects for a
temporary resumption of soybean sales to processors in Brazil after
a 2{-week boycott. Brazilian producers are considering the
government's request for a 10-day cooling-off period in the
soybean-growers' protest against the government's agricultural and
economic policies.
   The wheat market slipped on ideas that the gains of the three
previous sessions were overdone and on fears that the relatively
high prices could stifle export business.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 4} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $4.07{ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents
lower to 1 cent higher with July at $2.63\ a bushel; oats were 2
cents lower to { cent higher with July at $1.48{ a bushel; soybeans
were 1 cent to 8} cents lower with July at $7.19 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mixed
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .03 cent to .40 cent higher with August at 70.82
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .35 cent higher with
August at 81.40 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent lower to .30 cent
higher with July at 49.05 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.28 cent lower to .27 cent higher with July at 35.62 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
