<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Hooker-Sale     06-29 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hooker-Sale,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hooker Likely to Liquidate U.S. Retail, Property Holdings, Newspaper
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hooker Corp., the financially troubled Australian
real estate developer and retail concern, may liquidate all of its
U.S. department stores and shopping malls, according to a report
published Thursday.
   The Wall Street Journal quoted J. Frank Haasbeek, president of
Hooker's U.S. subisiary, as saying: ``It looks like Hooker will sell
everything over the next 12 to 24 months.''
   An assistant to Haasbeek at his office at L.J. Hooker Corp. in
Atlanta said Haasbeek was traveling Thursday and unavailable to
comment.
   Hooker might maintain a presence in the United States if it finds
investors willing to become joint-venture partners in proposed
shopping malls in Florida and North Carolina, the Journal said.
   Earlier this month, Hooker said it was looking for partners to
take stakes in its B. Altman and Bonwit Teller department store
chains and in malls in Cincinnati, Denver and Columbia, S.C.
   The Journal said Haasbeek indicated Hooker thinks chances of
finding partners for those operations are bleak.
   Haasbeek said Hooker is looking for an investment banking firm to
handle the B. Altman and Bonwit Teller divisions. He hopes to have a
tentative agreement to sell both chains by the early autumn.
   Hooker acquired Bonwit Teller, which has stores in the East,
Midwest and Florida, for about $92 million in August 1987. It bought
B. Altman, with stores in the Northeast, for about $100 million the
following month of that year.
   The investment firm First Boston Corp. already has been hired to
handle the sale of Hooker's malls in Cincinnati, Denver and Columbia
as well as the Merksamer Jewelery chain.
   Hooker also has put up for sale its interests in Sakowitz, a
Houston-based retailer, and in Parisian Inc., major department store
chain in the Southeast.
   Among its other U.S. holdings that Hooker is selling are a U.S.
residential construction business, nine strip shopping centers in
Florida and Ohio and six vacant tracts of land. Hooker already has
reached an agreement to sell its U.S. industrial operations to
divisions of Japan's Kajima Corp.
   Hooker has said it is suffering from a cash squeeze largely due
to high Australian interest rates and other unfavorable economic
conditions that have hurt its property develpment business in that
country.
   Last week, Hooker reached an agreement with its creditor banks on
a four-month moratorium on repaying principal on outstanding loans.
The banks, to which Hooker owes about $700 million, also agreed to
maintain credit lines at current levels.
</TEXT>
