<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-HollyFarms     06-29 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holly Farms,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tyson to Sell Two Holly Farms Divisions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGDALE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tyson Foods Inc., which last week won a
protracted fight for rival Holly Farms Corp., says it plans to sell
two Holly Farms divisions by mid-August to help pay off some of the
costs of the acquisition.
   Tyson Chairman Don Tyson said Wednesday company managers decided
to sell Holly Farms' rendering and flour and bakery supply divisions
and hoped to have the businesses sold by Aug. 15.
   In a proxy statement prepared for a special stockholders meeting
in April, Holly Farms projected the flour division would have sales
of $298 million, with income of $21 million this year, while the
rendering division would have $172 million in sales and income of
$18 million for the year.
   Tyson said he had not yet decided which, if any, of the Holly
Farms director-officers he'll keep on his management team.
   ``We'll make that decision on the 18th when I pay for the Holly
shares,'' Tyson said, referring to the July 18 deadline for Holly
Farms shareholders to tender their stock to Tyson.
   Tyson Foods, which began its efforts to take over Holly Farms in
October, clinched the deal last week with a cash offer of $1.4
billion or $70 a share. Holly Farms had tried to thwart Tyson's
efforts by agreeing to merge with ConAgra Inc. of Omaha, Neb.
   Holly Farms and ConAgra terminated their merger agreement, which
had been rejected by Holly Farms stockholders.
</TEXT>
