<FIRST>u f PM-EasternHearing 1stLd-Writethru   06-29 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern Hearing, 1st Ld-Writethru,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Committee Examining Eastern Airlines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOP 5 grafs new with Carlucci testimony; picks up at pvs 4th
graf, Eastern's management. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci told
Congress today he is still willing to become interim head of Eastern
Airlines to help meet a congressional committee's goal of restoring
it as a major carrier.
   Carlucci told the House Public Works and Transportation aviation
subcommittee he supports the plan of Chicago businessman Joseph
Ritchie, already spurned by Eastern Chairman Frank Lorenzo, to buy
the airline in partnership with Eastern's striking employees.
   ``This approach is the only one that has a chance of restoring
Eastern to its once-proud status,'' said Carlucci, who headed the
Pentagon in the latter part of the Reagan administration.
   Ritchie, president of Chicago Research &amp; Trading group, submitted
to the subcommittee a plan he said can still restore Eastern as ``a
major competitor in the airline industry.''
   Lorenzo rejected Ritchie's earlier union-backed attempt to buy
the airline, along with several other offers. Carlucci said he had
agreed to serve as interim chief executive officer of the airline
because Ritchie's plan appeared to have the support of both
employees and creditors.
   Eastern's management has said it plans to rebuild the airline as
a smaller carrier. Eastern, which had been the nation's
sixth-largest airline, has operated only limited flights since a
Machinists strike in March led to a sympathy walkout by pilots and
flight attendants.
   Other witnesses scheduled at the hearing included officials of
Eastern, its striking unions, the bankruptcy court, the Department
of Transportation and the Federal Aviation Administration.
   The committee, in a letter seeking testimony, said it ``believes
that restoration of Eastern as a major carrier is critical, to avoid
a substantial loss of jobs, economic damage to the communities in
which Eastern's employees are based, and an adverse impact on
consumers.''
   Subcommittee chairman James L. Oberstar, D-Minn., said the panel
is concerned that the course chosen by a New York bankruptcy court
to allow Eastern to sell off assets ``will lead to the liquidation
of Eastern.'' The airline filed for protection from creditors under
bankruptcy laws after the strike began.
   Oberstar said the panel seeks to determine how the loss of
Eastern as a major carrier will affect service and fares in the
markets it serves.
   He said the committee will examine both Ritchie's and Eastern's
plans, the bankruptcy court's ability to consider the public
interest, and any steps the Transportation Department has taken to
consider the effects of the airline's reorganization on air travel,
Eastern's employees and its creditors.
   Rep. Newt Gingrich of Georgia, subcommittee member and House GOP
whip, has asked Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner to intervene
in the bankruptcy court's proceedings.
   ``Our concern is urgent,'' Gingrich said in a letter to Skinner
last week, ``because it appears likely Eastern Airlines will be sold
off in pieces, resulting in less than a fully integrated competitive
carrier.''
   Gingrich accused Lorenzo, head of Texas Air Corp. which owns
Eastern, of having an interest in not building up Eastern as a
competitor to his other airline, Continental.
   Gingrich said that because no assistant attorney general for
antitrust has yet been confirmed, ``the bankruptcy and possible sale
of Eastern Airlines is taking place without proper guidance from the
Bush administration.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
