<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Persistent interest-rate worries and uncertainty
about the economy combined to drive stock prices sharply lower today.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 40.97 points to
2,463.77 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 5 to 1 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 248 up, 1,290
down and 378 unchanged.
   West Germany today raised two key interest rates by half a
percentage point in an evident effort to curb strong economic growth
in that country. Several other European nations also raised their
rates.
   Analysts didn't expect that to have any immediate effect on the
Federal Reserve's credit policy in this country, where all signs
point to slowing growth in business activity.
   In fact, some brokers say, investors in the U.S. markets lately
seem to have begun worrying more in recent days about a possible
economic slump.
   On Wednesday the government reported that the index of leading
economic indicators dropped 1.2 percent in May.
   Losers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, down 2[ at 111}; General Electric, down } at 52|; Union
Carbide, down | at 26, and American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, down | at
35{.
   Banc One led the active list, up 5{ at 33{. The company, which
had been considered a long shot, won the bidding to acquire the
failed banks formerly operated by MCorp.
   Technology stocks traded in the over-the-counter market came
under pressure for the second straight session. Intel dropped 1] to
29[; Apple Computer 1\ to 40{; Sun Microsystems ] to 16|, and
Ashton-Tate } to 17}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slumped 2.62 to 179.25. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down 4.59 at 361.42.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 121.14 million shares with two
hours to go.
