<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1431EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-AirbusDeal     06-29 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Airbus Deal,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gulf Air To Buy 24 Airbus Planes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANTILLY, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airbus Industrie announced Thursday that
Gulf Air will buy 24 aircraft for use on its Middle Eastern routes
in a deal worth at least $960 million.
   The deal includes 12 each of Airbus' A320 and A321 planes with
options to purchase six additional A320s.
   The A320 is a single-aisle, twin-engine aircraft seating 150
passengers in a two-class layout. The A321 is a stretched version of
the A320, seating 186 passengers.
   Gulf Air, which is owned jointly by the Arab states of Bahrain,
Oman, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates, will begin taking delivery
of the A320s in the spring of 1992, and A321s in the second half of
1994.
   Airbus and Gulf Air, which is based in Bahrain, did not release a
total package price of the deal, but Airbus said the A320's basic
price is $38 million, while the A321 sells for $42 million, making
the minimum price for the 24 aircraft $960 million, exclusive of
spare parts and training.
   The new planes will replace Boeing 737-200 aircraft.
   Airbus has received firm orders for 505 A320s from 25 customers,
and commitments for 30 A321s from three customers.
</TEXT>
