<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1433EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   06-29 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Sharply Down As Rate Fears Return</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Renewed nervousness about the British interest-rate
outlook, following a rate increase in West Germany, pushed share
prices on London's stock exchange sharply down Thursday.
   Still, the British pound's relative resilience helped to reassure
the stock market that British rates could perhaps hold at current
levels.
   ``Nobody's panicking yet,'' commented one dealer.
   At the close the FT-SE 100-share index was down 27.4 points, or
1.24 percent, at 2182.0. Volume slowed to 426.8 million shares from
Wednesday's 456.6 million shares.
   Dealers and analysts noted the London market had been vulnerable
to bad news following its recent strong runup on relatively little
volume.
   Dealers and analysts say nervousness is likely to persist as
participants wait to see how the pound weathers British inflation
data and further reports on Britain's trade deficit in coming weeks.
   ``The (equity) market won't get carried away until the trend in
the balance of payments is confirmed to be improving and until there
is an improvement in the inflation profile,'' Reynolds said. This is
likely to keep the British market on hold at least until late
summer, the Prudential-Bache economist predicted.
</TEXT>
