<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-29 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mostly Lower On Weather, Brazil Concerns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
lower Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade, with wheat leading the
way on ideas that the strong gains of the three previous sessions
had been exaggerated.
   Despite a rain-related slowdown in the winter wheat harvest,
especially in the South and Southeast, analysts said the movement of
new wheat to market was bound to force prices lower.
   Further selling of wheat futures was prompted by fears that the
relatively high prices reached this week could stifle export demand.
   Corn and soybean futures slipped following Wednesday's
six-to-10-day National Weather Service outlook for near-normal
rainfall in the Midwest.
   The soybean market also was pressured by prospects for a
temporary resumption of soybean sales to processors in Brazil after
a 2{-week boycott. Brazilian producers are considering their
government's request for a 10-day cooling-off period in their
protest against the country's agricultural and economic policies.
   At the close, wheat was 2{ cents to 7\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $4.05 a bushel; corn was { cent
lower to \ cent higher with July at $2.64\ a bushel; oats were 1
cent to 4 cents lower with July at $1.46{ a bushel; soybeans were 1
cent to 7 cents lower with July at $7.23{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
