<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1631EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Spain-Telefonica     06-29 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spain-Telefonica,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Telefonica 1988 Profits Rise 18 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Net profits at Telefonica de Espana, the
state-controlled telephone monopoly, rose 18 percent in 1988 over
the previous year as the fast-growing Spanish economy continued to
spur strong demand, company president Candido Velazquez said
Thursday.
   Velazquez said net profits in 1988 totaled 62.84 billion pesetas,
or $507 million, up from 53.24 billion pesetas in 1987.
   Revenue in 1988 increased to 612.53 billion pesetas, or $4.93
billion, from 568.70 billion pesetas the previous year.
   Velazquez said the company expected to catch up with exploding
demand for telephone services by mid-1992, in time for the Barcelona
'92 Summer Olympics and the Expo '92 World's Fair to commemorate
explorer Christopher Colombus' voyage to the New World.
   Consumer and media criticism of Telefonica has been great for the
last year due to months of waiting required for installation of new
lines.
   Former Telefonica president Luis Solana left his post last
December to take over as director general of state-run Spanish
Television after being blasted by the media and consumers for
failing to foresee the explosion in demand.
</TEXT>
