<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     06-29 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recession Fears Clobber Precious Metal Futures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of silver, gold and platinum fell sharply Thursday
amid growing fears that the U.S. economy is sliding inexorably into
a recession.
   On other markets, coffee futures sank; energy futures climbed;
grains and soybeans were mostly lower; and livestock and meat
futures were mixed.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled $5.30 to $6.20
lower with the contract for delivery in August at $373.90 a troy
ounce; silver was 16.5 cents to 19.8 cents lower with July at $5.12
a troy ounce.
   Platinum was $4.40 to $6.70 lower on the New York Mercantile
Exchange with July slipping below the psychologically important $500
level to settle at $496.90 a troy ounce.
   Analysts said fears of a recession have pervaded the financial
markets, encouraged by weakening economic indicators and relatively
high interest rates, which tend to slow the economy's growth.
   To explain Thursday's selloff in precious metals, they cited such
diverse factors as this week's stock market decline, a general
downturn in commodity prices, a stronger dollar and the tightening
of interest rates in Europe.
   ``It appears the Europeans are now going to take strong measures
in combating inflation,'' said Peter Cardillo, a commodity trading
adviser with Josephthal &amp; Co. in New York.
   Some experts had turned bullish on precious metals after last
week's strong rally in the gold market, but with little
follow-through buying by investors this week, those attitudes are
fading.
   ``The lack of bullion demand from just about every quarter makes
these rallies weak rallies and without any real backup,'' said
William O'Neill, director of research with Elders Futures Inc. in
New York.
   Coffee futures gave up nearly all of Wednesday's gains on New
York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange, falling amid renewed
pessimism about the prospects for a new international price-support
agreement.
   Members of the International Coffee Organization are scheduled to
vote Monday on two proposals for a pact to succeed the current
6-year agreement, which expires on Sept. 30.
   But neither proposal is expected to pass, and some of the largest
coffee-producing nations are pushing for a suspension of export
quotas if neither proposal is accepted.
   The International Coffee Organization is composed of 74 major
coffee-producing and consuming nations. It attempts to stabilize
coffee prices by limiting sales of coffee by the producers to the
consumers.
   Coffee settled unchanged to 2.78 cents lower with July at $1.116
a pound.
   Oil futures prices rose on the New York Mercantile Exchange in a
moderate rebound from Wednesday's steep decline.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 2 cents lower to 23
cents higher with August at $20.26 a barrel; heating oil was .24
cent lower to .27 cent higher with July at 49.45 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .14 cent to .37 cent higher with July at 61.52
cents a gallon.
   Wheat futures retreated on the Chicago Board of Trade on ideas
that the strong gains of the three previous sessions had been
exaggerated.
   Corn was nearly unchanged but soybean futures were lower,
pressured by prospects for a temporary resumption of soybean sales
to processors in Brazil after a 2{-week boycott by producers to
protest their government's agricultural and economic policies.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents to 7\ cents lower with July at $4.05 a
bushel; corn was \ cent lower to { cent higher with July at $2.64{ a
bushel; oats were 3 cents to 4\ cents lower with July at $1.46\ a
bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 6\ cents lower with July at $7.22{ a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in cautious trading ahead
of Friday's quarterly hogs-and-pigs inventory report from the
Agriculture Department.
   Live cattle settled .25 cent lower to .35 cent higher with August
at 70.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent to .20 cent
higher with August at 81.22 cents a pound; live hogs were .60 cent
lower to .17 cent higher with July at 48.90 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .20 cent to 1 cent lower with July at 34.70 cents
a pound.
</TEXT>
