<FIRST>r f AM-AnimalTesting-Colgate     06-29 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Animal Testing-Colgate,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colgate-Palmolive, Marrow-Tech Researching Alternatives to Animal
Testing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PISCATAWAY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colgate-Palmolive Co. and Marrow-Tech
Inc. announced Thursday they will collaborate on researching
possible alternatives to using animals in product tests.
   Under the agreement, Colgate's scientists will study the use of
Marrow-Tech's living skin replacement in a variety of skin
sensitivity and toxicity tests, according to Marrow-Tech spokeswoman
Susan A. Noonan.
   Marrow-Tech, based in Elmswood, N.Y., has been working on methods
of growing human tissues outside the body. The company has
successfully replicated bone marrow, skin and liver tissues, Ms.
Noonan said.
   Colgate is one of the country's major makers of consumer products
ranging from toothpaste to soaps.
   A number of companies in a variety of industries such as
cosmetics, pharmaceuticals and chemicals, are engaging in efforts to
find ways to assure their products are safe for consumer use without
having to test them on animals.
   Last week, Avon Products Inc. announced a permanent end to animal
testing, becoming the first major cosmetics maker to completely
replace animal tests with alternatives.
</TEXT>
