<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Pilots     06-29 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Pilots,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unions Picket Working Pilots' Homes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern-Hearing, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines union members on Thursday took
actions against former colleagues who have defied their nearly
4-month-old strike, picketing the homes of three pilots and the
business of another and announcing plans to fine working pilots.
   Tim Holder, an Air Line Pilots Association official in Atlanta,
said disciplinary proceedings will begin July 26 to seek fines
against some 220 pilots who have flown during the strike. Holder
said he expects penalties to be ``substantial,'' running to
thousands of dollars for each offender.
   The ALPA constitution calls for penalties against members who
disobey orders from the master executive council of the union, which
represents pilots at most major airlines. Disciplinary hearings for
Eastern pilots will be conducted by a three-member panel of pilots
from other airlines, Holder said.
   Meanwhile, Eastern union officials said they would continue
pickets at flying pilots' homes.
   ``This has sunk to a new low,'' said Tom Bueter, a 23-year
Eastern pilot who confronted seven pilots and a flight attendant
outside the home of his neighbor, pilot Roberto Freytes. ``These
people are losing, they perceive they're losing, and now they're
becoming more and more desperate.''
   Bueter and Freytes have continued to fly for Eastern during their
union's strike.
   ``We're going to do this every day at different homes,'' said
Edgar Belaval, a striking Eastern pilot picketing outside Freytes'
home in suburban southwest Dade County, Fla.
   ``Our striking pilots, flight attendants and (Machinists)
apparently lost all sense of decency today,'' Eastern spokesman
Robin Matell said in a message to employees. ``Whatever happened to
the notion that a man's home is his castle? Wouldn't you know the
chicken-hearted picketers selected homes where for the most part the
husbands were out flying and only the wife and kids were home.''
   Matell, a management veteran of strikes at several airlines, said
he had never heard of picketers going to private homes.
   Gary Greksa, a spokesman for ALPA, said the union obtained police
permits to picket three homes and the Keg South, a tavern owned by a
pilot and flight attendant who have crossed picket lines.
   ``There's been a lot of press lately and a very heavy advertising
campaign by the company ... it's led a lot of people to believe that
the strike is over,'' Greksa said. ``We do every little bit of
activity we can to keep it in the public eye.''
   Greksa said ALPA has begun running radio ads about the strike.
Other union sources have indicated the strikers plan a mass protest
July 4 at Miami International Airport and at other airports at which
Eastern flies.
   At least 3,400 of the 3,600 Eastern pilots joined the Machinists
union March 4 when that union went on strike. The flight attendants
union also is honoring picket lines.
   Eastern last week asked the bankruptcy court to terminate its
contract with the pilots union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890629-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1934EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru   06-29 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0253,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Finishes Mostly Higher Here Despite European Rate Hikes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 18th graf, `On the ...,' to CLARIFY that gold price quoted
is the August price and to change the comparision figure to August's figure
from Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar staged a puzzling turnaround Thursday
when it finished mostly higher in domestic trading despite
announcements that a string of European central banks will hike key
lending rates.
   Gold prices were mixed. Republic National Bank of New York quoted
a troy ounce of gold at $370.15 as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $374.40
late Wednesday.
   The dollar began to tumble after West Germany's Bundesbank
announced it would hike its discount and Lombard rates by half a
percentage point each, effective Friday. The discount rate will rise
to 5 percent and the Lombard rate to 7 percent, their highest levels
since the early 1980s.
   Similar actions followed in France, Switzerland, Belgium, the
Netherlands, Denmark and Austria.
   Higher rates overseas typically depress the dollar by enhancing
the value of foreign investments. Rather than purchase dollars to
invest in U.S. securities, foreign investors will keep their funds
overseas when rates there are attractive.
   Following the central banks' announcements, the dollar fell a
steep 2.3 pfennigs to 1.9390 West German marks. But before trading
ended in Europe and midway through the domestic session, the dollar
began to turn around, a phenomenon that had many traders scratching
their heads.
   ``There's no reasonable justification for it,'' said Frank Conte,
vice president of foreign exchange at Barclays Bank PLC in New York.
``The dollar should be a lot lower.''
   Some said the recovery was due to a variety of technical factors,
including the fact that traders already had begun to square up their
positions ahead of the July 4th holiday weekend.
   But Robert Ryan, a vice president at Irving Trust Co., noted that
heavy Japanese dollar-buying in the face of political difficulties
in Tokyo worked to boost the U.S. currency.
   ``The yen kept weakening and it impacted the other currencies,
and the dollar came back,'' he said. ``Today's activity showed total
bearishness toward the yen.''
   While the European rate hikes may have caught some traders by
surprise, more dealers were jolted by the dollar's resilience.
   Still, Bank of Boston senior trader Scott Horwitz cautioned that
the dollar's strength should not necessarily be interpreted as ``a
trendsetting reaction.''
   ``The dollar turns on a dime,'' he said, adding that Thursday's
recovery was ``more a product of a four-day U.S. holiday.''
   In Tokyo, the dollar slipped to 142.90 Japanese yen from 143.55
on Wednesday. Later in London, the U.S. currency traded lower at
142.53. In New York, however, the dollar climbed to 144.00 yen, from
143.25 yen on Wednesday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.5650 late Thursday, more
expensive for buyers than Wednesday's late $1.5613. Later in New
York, it cost $1.5435 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5580 on
Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday, inlcuded: 1.9640 West German marks, up from 1.9620;
1.6880 Swiss francs, down from 1.6885; 6.6690 French francs, up from
6.6605; 1,419.00 Italian lire, up from 1,416.00, and 1.1946 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1965.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,
included: 1.9430 West German marks, down from 1.9630; 1.6650 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6870; 6.5925 French francs, down from 6.6645;
2.1875 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2125; 1,407.00 Italian lire, down
from 1,421.50, and 1.1950 Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for delivery
in the current month, August, slipped to $373.90 a troy ounce, from
Wednesday's late bid of $379.20.
   Gold bullion prices were unchanged in London at a bid price of
$375.25 a troy ounce late Thursday, but rose in Zurich to $376.00 an
ounce bid, from $373.75. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid
$376.45, up from $373.55.
   Silver prices fell. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery settled at $5.120 a troy ounce, down from $5.282.
Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.28 bid a troy ounce, down
from $5.30.
