<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 1935EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-PrimeComputer     06-29 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prime Computer,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whitney Launches Tender Offer for Prime; MAI Still Mulling Counter
Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.H. Whitney &amp; Co. launched a $1.25 billion tender
offer for Prime Computer Inc. on Thursday, but rival bidder MAI
Basic Four Inc. said it would try to exceed that price.
   ``MAI's position is, it is still evaluating the situation and is
hopeful that we will be able to beat the Whitney offer,'' said Toni
Lee, a spokeswoman for the Tustin, Calif., computer firm.
   Wall Street, however, treated MAI's statement with skepticism.
Prime's stock closed at $19.25, up 25 cents, while MAI shares
dropped 12{ cents to $5.75 in composite trading Thursday on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   Securities analysts said they doubted MAI would be able to obtain
financing for an offer high enough to wrest Prime away from J.H.
Whitney.
   ``I don't think we're going to see a bidding war,'' said Stephen
K. Smith, who follows the computer industry for the brokerage firm
of PaineWebber Inc. in New York.
   Prime is a Natick-based maker of minicomputers and computer-aided
design and manufacturing equipment. In the face of a hostile, $1.1
billion bid from MAI, its board of directors agreed June 23 to a
merger with J.H. Whitney, a private venture capital firm in New York
City.
   Whitney's offer is $21.50 a share in cash for Prime's 49.5
million outstanding shares of common stock, which represents about
79 percent of the company's stock on a fully diluted basis.
   For the remaining 21 percent of the shares, Whitney said it would
exchange securities with a face value of $22 per share. Securities
analysts have estimated the overall value of the offer at about $20
a share, or $1.25 billion.
   The Whitney offer expires July 27, the day after Prime's annual
meeting. MAI has said repeatedly that it would wage a proxy battle
to elect its nominees to the board of directors at the meeting.
   Prime, which has about 11,200 employees and annual revenues of
$1.6 billion, has seen its earnings plummet during the takeover
battle. It reported a loss of $5 million on sales of $387 million
during the first quarter of 1989.
   MAI, which had 1988 revenues of about $421 million, has offered
$19.50 a share in cash for about 75 percent of Prime's shares and a
mixture of preferred stock and bonds for the remainder. Analysts
have valued that offer at about $18 a share.
   MAI Chairman Bennett S. LeBow had said June 22 it would increase
its offer, but no increase has yet been announced. On Thursday, the
company extended its previous offer until July 6.
</TEXT>
