<FIRST>u f AM-CapitalGains     06-29 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capital Gains,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brady Says Administration Still Seeking Capital Gains Cut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady said
Thursday the administration will continue to seek a capital gains
tax cut despite a leading Democratic congressman's decision to look
elsewhere for revenue-raising provisions.
   Chairman Dan Rostenkowski of the House Ways and Means Committee
was reported Thursday to have said he had given up the idea of
cutting the capital gains tax because of Democratic opposition.
   Instead, the Illinois Democrat told the Wall Street Journal in an
interview, he plans to file a $5.3 billion tax-increase bill with
revenue-raising provisions instead of coupling a temporary reduction
in the capital gains tax with expansions of tax breaks for poor
people.
   Rostenkowksi said he encountered stronger resistance than
expected from Democrats, who argued the tax break would be too large
a benefit for wealthy people and also probably would cost the
government revenue in the long run.
   Brady noted in a statement Thursday that President Bush has made
a capital gains tax cut a key element of his economic program.
   ``It will lower the cost of capital, create incentives for
investment in the long-term productive capacity of American
industry, make American firms more competitive internationally and
create new job opportunities,'' Brady said.
   ``All Americans will benefit. We will emphasize these economic
benefits as we work with Congress to achieve enactment of the
capital gains measure,'' he added.
   In the interview, Rostenkowski described his capital gains tax
cut proposal as ``a kind of test balloon'' that he floated at Bush's
suggestion.
   The plan would have reduced the capital gains rate for a year
from the current top rate of as much as 33 percent, and would have
helped lower-income individuals with expanded tax credits for earned
income and child care.
   He said the plan would have raised about $15 billion over two
years because of churning of assets during the short-term change.
   Rostenkowski said he was considering a variety of revenue-raising
provisions that Bush would be most likely to accept given his pledge
not to increase taxes.
</TEXT>
