<FIRST>r f AM-ComputerWhiz 1stLd-Writethru f0146 06-29 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Computer Whiz, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0146,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Entrepreneur Tex Hildreth Convicted of Criminal Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with sentencing, verdict on addition charges.
Edits to tighten. No pickup. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computer entrepreneur accused of stealing
nearly $1 million from investors was sentenced to up to 15 years in
prison Thursday after he was convicted of 46 of 50 criminal charges.
   A jury that convicted Tex Z. Hildreth on 26 of 28 counts of
larceny Wednesday found him guilty on 20 of 22 additional charges
Thursday. Norfolk Superior Court Judge Roger J. Donahue sentenced
him to state prison in Walpole.
   The jury reached its decision on the first 28 counts Wednesday
after deliberating more than eight hours.
   Prosecutors contended Hildreth, 25, stole nearly $1 million from
investors and three banks between 1985 and 1988.
   He was accused of misrepresenting the success of his computer
consulting company, Massdata Corp. of Braintree, and claiming
falsely that he was on the verge of inheriting a multimillion-dollar
family trust fund.
   When a criminal investigation of Massdata began in May 1988,
Hildreth and his mother, Rose, fled and attempted suicide in a New
Hampshire hotel room.
   In a surprise move Tuesday, Hildreth chose not to take the stand
in his own defense, although his lawyer had said at the beginning of
the trial that Hildreth would testify. His trial lasted 12 days.
   Hildreth's defense has been that he was innocent by reason of
insanity.
   Two psychiatrists and a neuropsychologist who examined him
testifed that he suffers a variety of psychiatric troubles,
including personality disorders and manic depression. But under
questioning by the prosecution, they acknowledged that Hildreth is
not psychotic or unable to distinguish reality from fantasy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
