<DOCNO> AP890629-0303 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-89 2357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Dunkin'Donuts     06-29 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dunkin' Donuts,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Firms Say Rebuff Won't Stop Them From Dunkin' Donuts Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANDOLPH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold shoulder from Dunkin' Donuts
management won't deter two Canadian companies that want to gobble up
the doughnut chain, the Canadian firms said Thursday.
   Dunkin' Donuts' board of directors advised shareholders Wednesday
not to tender their shares for the $43 per share offered by Cara
Operations Limited and Kingsbridge Capital Group, both of Toronto.
   In a statement, the Canadian firms said the rejection of their
``all-cash, all-shares offer ... demonstrates the continuing
contempt of the Dunkin' Donuts board of directors for its fiduciary
duty to the owners of Dunkin' Donuts _ the common shareholders.''
   Dunkin' Donuts, based in this Boston suburb, has rejected a
friendly buy-out offer from the groups and taken several steps to
make itself a less tasty takeover target, including adopting a
``poison pill'' preferred stock plan and an employee stock ownership
program.
   Cara and Kingsbridge said those measures will cost shareholders a
total of $7.6 million, more than 40 percent of Dunkin' Donuts 1988
net income, substantially damaging earnings.
   Furthermore, Dunkin' Donuts agreed to pay its financial advisers
and backers, Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. and General Electric Capital Corp.,
more than $2.5 million at shareholders' expense, the Canadian
companies said.
   The companies reaffirmed their offer, which expires July 13, and
said they are prepared to commit up to $80 million in equity and
debt as well as short-term financing to making the takeover succeed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
